WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.520
[Amit Varma]: The great thing about cinema is that you can lose yourself in it, and you can also find

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:14.900
[Amit Varma]: yourself in it. You can use cinema for entertainment and escapism, and you can also use it as we

00:00:14.900 --> 00:00:20.120
[Amit Varma]: use all great art, to understand the world and our own selves better. Any true film lover

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:25.100
[Amit Varma]: will do both of these, often at the same time. And maybe as time passes and you grow older,

00:00:25.100 --> 00:00:29.320
[Amit Varma]: you can map out your life and the person you are through the films that you have loved.

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And for a film lover to talk to other film lovers, there are few joys greater than that.

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:38.160
[Amit Varma]: This episode is about exactly that, as I got two close friends who are also cinema buffs

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:43.280
[Amit Varma]: to have a chat about movies. Now, I know that these days, authorities scan conversations

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:47.920
[Amit Varma]: for keywords and haul people off to jail if there's any suspicious language, regardless

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:53.740
[Amit Varma]: of context. But I can't help saying this. Our recording today was a riot. We had a blast.

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:59.520
[Amit Varma]: This episode is da bomb. If you love films, this conversation may make you explode with

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:03.660
[Unknown]: happiness.

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:08.840
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:16.280
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:20.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guests today are Jai Arjun Singh and Subrat Mohanty.

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:24.480
[Amit Varma]: Jai is one of our best writers on cinema, and we've recorded a popular episode in the

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:28.480
[Amit Varma]: past. I'll link that from the show notes. Subrat was a regular contributor to the cult

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:33.800
[Amit Varma]: film blog of the auties, Passion for Cinema, and he also hosts a fantastic podcast called

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.640
[Amit Varma]: Haal Chaal Theek Thaak Hai. These two guys both love cinema and also know a lot about

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:43.040
[Amit Varma]: it. And I thought I'd get them together to chat about films, the great films of the past

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:47.440
[Amit Varma]: that we miss out on because of the recency effect, how Indian cinema has developed over

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:53.000
[Amit Varma]: the years, how we watch movies as film lovers, how films have changed us, and so on. We also

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.320
[Amit Varma]: recommend many, many, many good films for you to watch. So you could think of this as

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:01.760
[Amit Varma]: an unstructured kind of film appreciation course. But before we talk cinema, let's talk

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:06.480
[Amit Varma]: money. Let's go to a unique kind of commercial break. Capital Gyaan by Deepak Chenoy. This

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:19.280
[Unknown]: is like a show within a commercial from the kind sponsors of this episode, Capital Mind.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:24.080
[Unknown]: Imagine you had to bet on who will win the next Wimbledon. Currently, it seems Djokovic

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:29.720
[Unknown]: is a strong bet. Well, during 2003 to 2008, it was Roger Federer and Serena Williams.

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:35.320
[Unknown]: In the 90s, it was Steffi Graf. If you have to bet, you generally bet on the best. And

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:41.640
[Unknown]: the best are the folks who win consistently. Businesses are the same. A business with strong

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:48.000
[Unknown]: growth tends to keep growing. And this growth can often last several quarters or years.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.560
[Unknown]: Stock prices behave even more similarly. A company whose stock price is accelerating

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:58.880
[Unknown]: or building momentum is often a company whose business is doing well too. What goes up continues

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:06.080
[Unknown]: to go up until it doesn't. Just like Federer met Natal and those wins became rarer. What

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:12.760
[Unknown]: if you only held a stock when it was in form? You moved on mercilessly when it stopped performing

00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:19.160
[Unknown]: and were still okay to come back if and when it started up again. This is the crux of momentum

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:25.600
[Unknown]: investing. Buy stocks in momentum, stick with the winners, prune your losers and be vigilant

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:30.800
[Unknown]: about when they swap places. This isn't a new discovery. It's been studied and documented

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:36.080
[Unknown]: for decades. For everyone who says the market is efficient and that all information is priced

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:41.520
[Unknown]: in, research has shown that momentum is a well-documented anomaly. A portfolio of high

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:46.560
[Unknown]: momentum stocks has a strong chance of outperforming the broader market over time. Opportunities

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:52.320
[Unknown]: don't only lie when prices are low. Sometimes they emerge when prices are uncomfortably

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:58.960
[Unknown]: high too. I'm Deepak Shannoi, CEO at Capital Mind. In our portfolio management service,

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:04.040
[Unknown]: we have built portfolios using momentum as one of our core strategies. Talk to us and

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:10.520
[Unknown]: we'll tell you more about such counterintuitive but effective strategies. We're at cm.social

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:19.120
[Unknown]: slash seen unseen. Bet on the company's in form. cm.social slash seen unseen.

