[Amit Varma]: And Subrat, you're a first timer here. So I'd love to sort of start by asking you about

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:13.400
[Amit Varma]: your journey. And your journey is so intertwined with, you know, loving films and all of that,

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:18.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, that is not even a separate question. So So, you know, tell me about where did you

00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:20.840
[Amit Varma]: grow up? What was early life like?

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:27.680
[Guest 2]: Right. So Amit, if you are truly a Hindi film fan, then Jai is the thing that comes first.

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:33.200
[Unknown]: And after that, it's Veeru. Usually Jai and Veeru.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:35.440
[Unknown]: Even I got that reference.

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:43.360
[Guest 2]: Right. So about about my growing up, you know, I grew up in a really small town in in southern

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:48.200
[Guest 2]: Odisha. And like many of your guests often say, you know, there are there are only few

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:55.680
[Guest 2]: things to do in such towns in 80s and early 90s. You, you played cricket, you followed

00:05:55.680 --> 00:06:02.520
[Guest 2]: cricket and every single, you know, opportunity that you got to watch a film or see the straight

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:08.800
[Guest 2]: run Do Darshan channel and watch those TV serials you did. And do not just watch them,

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:14.520
[Guest 2]: at least in my case, I literally not literally, but I really drank them, you know, in the

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:21.440
[Guest 2]: sense that every single scene, every single dialogue was, has been permanently etched.

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:28.920
[Guest 2]: I often have this sort of, you know, bet with someone that I can pretty much sing every

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:34.960
[Guest 2]: single 80s jingle fully in Hindi or English.

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:40.480
[Guest 2]: Watch him run, watch him play. He's a winner all the way. You become a Maltova mum.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:41.480
[Amit Varma]: The next one.

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:49.720
[Guest 2]: Added strength and energy, malt and cocoa, malt and cocoa, something. That's what makes

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:51.720
[Guest 2]: you a Maltova mum.

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:58.080
[Unknown]: I didn't know there would be an immediate test of my...

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:02.280
[Amit Varma]: Singer sewing machine. Singer sewing machine. I like that because I thought the girls in

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:03.280
[Amit Varma]: that were cute.

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:04.280
[Amit Varma]: The Hindi or the English one?

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:05.280
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:06.280
[Guest 2]: Any of them.

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:10.120
[Guest 2]: Do you remember those days of your childhood? You decorated those days with merit.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:12.000
[Unknown]: Singer used to be singer merit in India.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.480
[Unknown]: Those childhood memories, those talks, you decorated them with merit.

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:20.880
[Guest 2]: By the way, singer, I didn't realize till much later when I was in Sri Lanka that it

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:27.960
[Guest 2]: was actually a British company that was Sri Lanka based. And when they left that, they

00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:32.760
[Guest 2]: left behind the singer. It was like the Indian agency houses that were left behind for tea

00:07:32.760 --> 00:07:42.280
[Guest 2]: and other commodities. So, anyway, back. Thankfully, I cleared the two quick, rapid, you know,

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:43.280
[Amit Varma]: questions that you gave.

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:46.880
[Amit Varma]: It's a sign of my poor memory that I actually asked you about two of the really popular

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:50.320
[Amit Varma]: jingles, you know, ideally, you should have taken something obscure and tested it, since

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:51.320
[Amit Varma]: you said every jingle.

00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:59.400
[Guest 2]: I mean, yeah, the TV serials, their songs, so on and so forth. But so yeah, so there

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:06.160
[Guest 2]: was a, I think, just the absolute lack of any other avenue to sort of, you know, engage

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:10.720
[Guest 2]: yourself. But I think that was the case for most other kids also. But in my case, I guess

00:08:10.720 --> 00:08:16.800
[Guest 2]: it just became somewhat more intense than others, because I think a lot of us, you know,

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:23.280
[Guest 2]: who have been on your shows as well are introverts. So you create your own sort of universe and

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:28.480
[Guest 2]: you stay in it, you, you think about it, you, you know, play it back in your mind.

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:29.480
[Guest 2]: Were you a daydreamer?

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:36.240
[Guest 2]: Lots, actually, quite a bit. I mean, all kinds of imaginary friends in my head. And that

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:41.320
[Guest 2]: took a long time to go. They were there for a long, long period of time. So yeah, and

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:50.000
[Guest 2]: then the other thing was that my father was also into films. So in our home, the idea

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.640
[Guest 2]: that you would watch a film had no sort of, you know, stigma kind of thing attached to

00:08:54.640 --> 00:09:00.080
[Guest 2]: it, which oftentimes I saw in my, you know, other friends, their parents would, you know,

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:05.280
[Guest 2]: comment on it. But in our house, you know, you watch as many films as you want. And it

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:09.840
[Guest 2]: used to be an event if there was a film on Doordarshan, like my father would start telling

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:16.440
[Guest 2]: us the previous day that tomorrow, you know, there is, there is Kashmir Ki Kali, he would

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:22.760
[Guest 2]: start giving us that, you know, where was he in 1964, when he watched that film, you

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:27.120
[Guest 2]: know, then this song will come. And when the movie will start playing, the minute he hears

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:31.880
[Guest 2]: the first train of the music, he'll say, now this is the song. And, you know, as a kid,

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:35.240
[Guest 2]: all of those things seemed magic. In fact, the one thing that my father did, which I

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:40.520
[Guest 2]: genuinely thought was magic, and therefore, then I sort of worked on it was, he, I mean,

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:46.120
[Guest 2]: we would play the radio. And that guy will, you know, the announcer will say that, Abhi

00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:54.520
[Guest 2]: bhai, suniye film Mughal-e-Azam ka, Nata Mangeshkar ka gaana, Sangeetkar Naushad, and whatever

00:09:54.520 --> 00:10:00.920
[Guest 2]: Geetkar hai, Shakeel. And my father will say, Khuda Nige Bahan Ho Tumhara. And then the

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:07.440
[Guest 2]: song will come. How did this guy know? By the time I was 12, I was beating my father

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:14.120
[Guest 2]: in that game. So because it just became an obsession. So yeah, so I mean, just to, you

00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:21.200
[Guest 2]: know, go back, I mean, since it was a small town, we barely had any exposure to Hollywood.

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:28.360
[Guest 2]: And you know, the whole Bollywood scene was initially, you watch whatever came in the

00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest 2]: cinema hall, there was only one cinema hall. But I possibly, you know, this is like genuine

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:40.720
[Guest 2]: cinema Paradiso thing. Main wahan hota tha, projectionist uncle hote the, hamara kaam

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:45.560
[Guest 2]: chalta tha. But then the video revolution also happened. And then this, you know, this

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:53.680
[Guest 2]: 25 rupees main you rent out the video recording, that player for a day. And then the idea was,

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:58.560
[Guest 2]: how do you maximize because that's, you know, economics, fixed cost of use pe kitna variable

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:05.320
[Guest 2]: chala sakte ho. So then we would get six or eight cassettes. And then you know that you

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:11.400
[Guest 2]: want to watch two, the other six were tukka, whatever was there in that guy's, in that

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:16.840
[Guest 2]: library, right, you just picked up and you started watching them. So this continued till

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:23.240
[Guest 2]: about when I was in school. And I think I can safely say that everything that was there

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:28.800
[Guest 2]: to be shown on Doordarshan, Hindi, English, Malayalam, all regional languages, Saturday

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:35.400
[Guest 2]: afternoon, I used to just watch every single one of them, any film related programs, you

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:41.640
[Guest 2]: know, baato baato mein, this has been Handa's program and this Tabassum's phool khile hain

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:47.440
[Guest 2]: gulshan gulshan and just, you know, watch every single one of them and just store it

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:56.360
[Guest 2]: in your head. A few things happened then, one was the video, library wala possibly saw

00:11:56.360 --> 00:12:01.600
[Guest 2]: the, you know, initial change in taste of the people there. And he started stocking

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:09.080
[Guest 2]: up some, you know, Hollywood films. So, Indiana Jones was one of those early ones, which was

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:14.320
[Guest 2]: when I first realized ki kuch hai, there is something very different about these films

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:22.680
[Guest 2]: and he had some, the usual Superman, the original, which as kids we all enjoyed. And then, and

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:29.760
[Guest 2]: then by the time we were 14 or so, we were interested in other kind of cassettes as well.

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:33.320
[Guest 2]: And so then that guy would give us one of the two, right, he would either give us some

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:40.160
[Guest 2]: horror film. And I don't know if you know this, this, I mean, Evil Dead, as a film has

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:44.760
[Guest 2]: been seen by every single guy in chota kasbah of India in the late 80s, early 90s, because

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:50.840
[Guest 2]: the video cassette of Evil Dead was possibly the most most sort of ripped and copied video

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:57.360
[Guest 2]: cassette of all times. Baad mein pata chala ki wo Sam Raimi ne banaya hai. And much later

00:12:57.360 --> 00:13:03.880
[Guest 2]: I watched it again. And I realized, maybe the craft is good. I mean, it's quite a quite

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:08.680
[Guest 2]: a good film. But anyway, so either we were watching crazy horror shit, which none of

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:16.480
[Guest 2]: us had any idea whether it's good or bad. So, you know, Evil Dead and this whole early

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:21.120
[Guest 2]: graven filmography or carpenter filmography, some random, I mean, sometimes there's not

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:25.840
[Guest 2]: even be full films. And we would just watch some parts of it and then the cassette would

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:33.160
[Guest 2]: get stuck or something would happen. And then the Doordarshan, you know, also started showing

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:41.000
[Guest 2]: on these Friday evenings, after 10pm films. And because I was a somewhat of a decent student,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:46.440
[Guest 2]: my parents thought that if he's sitting alone, and you know, after dinner, he must be studying,

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:52.840
[Guest 2]: which I was most of the days, but Friday, I would turn on the TV, put the volume to

00:13:52.840 --> 00:14:02.600
[Guest 2]: zero and watch those Friday night Doordarshan English films. They were a mixed bag. I mean,

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:11.800
[Guest 2]: some of those were really good films. Somewhere like she'll be wearing pink pajamas or something.

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:21.200
[Guest 2]: So the return was variable. But I got whatever my teenage, you know, hormonal wants were,

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:24.920
[Guest 2]: they were getting satisfied as part of that. So that that was how it went on till about

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:29.840
[Guest 2]: 17. At 17, I went to engineering college, which was this complete disaster in terms

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:35.280
[Guest 2]: of you know, liking, getting to see things etc. So all that I did in engineering college

00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:42.640
[Guest 2]: was watch the standard Bollywood fare. And then occasionally, you would get some video

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:46.560
[Guest 2]: cassettes again the same way and watch some of those films. But thankfully, since it was

00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:53.480
[Guest 2]: a bit a bit of a bigger town, there used to be some like big releases, you know, The Fugitive

00:14:53.480 --> 00:14:59.960
[Guest 2]: or something, those kind of movies would come in the bodyguard in the mid 90s, early 90s

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:10.080
[Guest 2]: etc. But then in one of those years, I went to Kolkata for my summer training. And I did

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:18.800
[Guest 2]: that at, you know, one of those MNC plants in Calcutta. And since I was always interested

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:23.960
[Guest 2]: in it, people told me that you must go to this place called Nandan. And I didn't have

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:30.000
[Guest 2]: a clue about Nandan then, but then I went to Nandan and I realized this is like, you

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.680
[Guest 2]: know, the cultural hub of Kolkata of a certain kind of a certain Badralok variety. And Nandan

00:15:34.680 --> 00:15:41.080
[Guest 2]: had then three halls, the two larger ones and one small, just about 40 seater. And the

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:50.000
[Guest 2]: 40 seater would play like great films all the time. And so that those two months, I

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:55.640
[Guest 2]: think I did, I watched all kinds of things. Mind you, in this during the same time, because

00:15:55.640 --> 00:16:02.400
[Guest 2]: of the sort of the desert that the engineering college was, I had gotten myself a membership

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:07.160
[Guest 2]: of the local Max Muller Bhavan. That engineering college was in a town that had a steel plant

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:12.440
[Guest 2]: that had a German partnership. You know, Nehru had done all these partnerships, each steel

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:17.200
[Guest 2]: plant had some was German, some was Brit, some was Russian, something else or some other

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:23.200
[Guest 2]: thing. And so I had told my one of my profs that please give me that membership. He was

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:26.360
[Guest 2]: like, why would you want a Max Muller? Have you come here to do engineering or have you

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:31.880
[Guest 2]: come to Max Muller Bhavan to study? I said, forgive me, give it to me. So I was reading

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:36.440
[Guest 2]: quite indiscriminately, all kinds of stuff. So I would go into the library, no idea, there

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:42.080
[Guest 2]: was no internet or anything to guide your taste. I was decent at quizzing. So I knew

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:46.440
[Guest 2]: some famous books. So if I saw a famous book, I'd pick it up. Otherwise, it was like Milan

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:50.800
[Guest 2]: Kundera. Genuinely, I thought he was an Indian author. So I picked up the first one. First

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:55.040
[Guest 2]: thing I remember is I read The Unbearable Lightness of Being. I was not like you, Amit,

00:16:55.040 --> 00:17:00.920
[Guest 2]: who was reading the whole of Shakespeare canon by the time he was 10. But I was reading Kundera

00:17:00.920 --> 00:17:07.080
[Guest 2]: in 18. And then when I finished all Kundera, then some one day I saw Antichrist. So I thought

00:17:07.080 --> 00:17:12.400
[Guest 2]: maybe this is also a good book. It looked well-thumbed. I don't know who was reading.

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:17.880
[Guest 2]: Some German expats were reading him, I guess, in that place. So I picked those things up.

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:23.720
[Guest 2]: So I did the same thing in Kolkata. Kuch bhi aara tha, dekh liya. And that's where I think

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:29.720
[Guest 2]: I saw some, I mean, I didn't know what, why they were looking different or appearing different,

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:35.840
[Guest 2]: but I knew something intense was happening on the screen. I mean, I remember watching,

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:43.400
[Guest 2]: you know, 400 Blows. And I realized yeh kuch toh hai boss. Something is there. And I mean,

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:47.920
[Guest 2]: the usual thing was happening. It was some summer kind of fest and they were just playing

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:52.880
[Guest 2]: French New Wave and some Italian New Wave and all of those stuff. Pasolini. And so I

00:17:52.880 --> 00:18:00.200
[Guest 2]: watched a few of those. Sodor and whatever. 120 Days. Then I came back. The usual life

00:18:00.200 --> 00:18:04.480
[Guest 2]: continued. But that got became a bit of a thing that I'm missing out on something. Something

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:10.800
[Guest 2]: big is there out there. So every couple of months I would make the Kolkata trip. It was

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:16.400
[Guest 2]: like about six or seven hours in train. And watch whatever was playing in the cinema hall.

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:22.440
[Guest 2]: And Kolkata did have reasonably good, you know, new films coming in there. And then

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:28.080
[Guest 2]: spend time in, in Nandan. And that sort of whetted my appetite quite a bit. By the time

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:35.160
[Guest 2]: I left it, and then I did my postgrad in Kolkata itself. So that became a good sort of a place

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:39.520
[Guest 2]: to do all of this. And then after postgrad, as luck would have it, I had a job that took

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:46.640
[Guest 2]: me all over the world for the first 10 years. That I just completely sated myself. What

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:54.360
[Guest 2]: also had happened one big thing that people often don't realize. The, you know, these

00:18:54.360 --> 00:19:02.200
[Guest 2]: cable wala started showing TCM in India. Again, you know, I don't know why they don't do it

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:06.080
[Guest 2]: now in India. That thing just ran for some seven, eight years.

00:19:06.080 --> 00:19:07.080
[Guest 1]: What is TCM?

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:12.320
[Guest 2]: It used to be called TNT when they started out. The Turner Network Television. And then

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:13.320
[Guest 2]: it became TCM later.

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:17.680
[Guest 2]: It's the Turner classic movies. It's still there actually in the US. There is an app

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:22.200
[Guest 2]: but you can't pay in India because that app is not available in India. There is a hack

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:31.600
[Guest 2]: around it. I will tell you some other time. So, TCM used to just all the time, show you,

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:41.080
[Guest 2]: you know, the great films of the 30s, 40s and the 50s. And it was available. So that

00:19:41.080 --> 00:19:47.400
[Guest 2]: plus the, I mean, I used to be at least 20 or 25 weeks outside of India. And as luck

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:52.120
[Guest 2]: would have it, a lot of it in Europe. And as luck would have it for a long time in places

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:56.520
[Guest 2]: like Poland and Czech Republic and in Poland in a place called Woods, L-O-D-Z, it's called

00:19:56.520 --> 00:20:01.600
[Guest 2]: but it has one of the great film schools of Eastern Europe. In fact, all the great Polish

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:07.360
[Guest 2]: filmmakers actually studied or taught at the Woods Filmmaking School, Andrzej Wajda and

00:20:07.360 --> 00:20:13.920
[Guest 2]: all of these guys. But you go in the afternoon, you can just, you know, spend your time watching

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:20.920
[Guest 2]: films peacefully. I mean, it was like a completely different world. So those seven, eight years

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:28.440
[Guest 2]: where, when I sort of just watched whatever came my way. And then, you know, when I would

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:36.480
[Guest 2]: be in the US, you know, two weeks in the US, I, my, kaam khatam hua, 6.30 get back, watch

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:42.920
[Guest 2]: some of those US late evening television stuff, which was all great fun. I mean, all these

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:49.400
[Guest 2]: light show and, you know, David Letterman stuff. And then around 8.30 or 9, turn on

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:55.880
[Guest 2]: one of those film channels. And there were like six, seven of them and at any time, something

00:20:55.880 --> 00:21:02.880
[Guest 2]: good would be coming. So the one great passion of mine during that time was, I just got caught

00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:09.680
[Guest 2]: into these, you know, this American 70s kind of one pack of filmmakers, who I think are

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:15.600
[Guest 2]: still somewhat underrated. I mean, you know, we talk of all of these 60s and 50s guys,

00:21:15.600 --> 00:21:24.080
[Guest 2]: but these guys are great, are great still. And that was staple HBO or whatever that free

00:21:24.080 --> 00:21:29.600
[Guest 2]: to air channels fair. I mean, they used to put one or the other one that time. So yeah,

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:36.900
[Guest 2]: so that by the time, you know, by, by the time I was like, mid 30s, the combination

00:21:36.900 --> 00:21:43.840
[Guest 2]: of reading all kinds of stuff and watching all kinds of stuff and connecting the two

00:21:43.840 --> 00:21:50.920
[Guest 2]: had kind of made me what I am I mean, in the sense that, you know, I used to do my work,

00:21:50.920 --> 00:21:56.640
[Guest 2]: but you know, I, I was in a place where, you know, all of these things were coming together.

00:21:56.640 --> 00:22:04.400
[Guest 2]: And I always had this great interest in connecting it more than just watching one film or a book

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:08.440
[Guest 2]: or what, you know, just by on its own. And there is a way to appreciate it on its own

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:14.800
[Guest 2]: as well. My, the great fun I used to have was in sort of finding somewhat strained linkages

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:19.720
[Guest 2]: at times. But it was good fun to find those linkages. And yeah, great memories of those

00:22:19.720 --> 00:22:24.360
[Guest 2]: days. I mean, being in New York, going to East Village, there is a Korean video store,

00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:29.600
[Guest 2]: very famous. I don't know if you shut down now. If you go there, you will, I mean, just

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:35.080
[Guest 2]: the best of world cinema would be there for you to buy. And I remember actually meeting

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:40.360
[Guest 2]: Spike Lee there, who was shocked to know that somebody in India watches this film. It was

00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:49.440
[Unknown]: 2006. What are you saying? Firstly, how do you recognize me? You're a great guy. I recognize

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:57.800
[Unknown]: you. What have you watched? I said, I was do the right thing. And what are you getting

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:03.040
[Unknown]: out of that? You know, this fight between African American and Italian families in New

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:12.480
[Guest 2]: York. But yeah, I mean, so yeah, I mean, to cut a long story, not so short. This is really

00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:19.200
[Guest 2]: what it is. I mean, this, it's a constant evolution, but very strong passion for both

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:25.920
[Amit Varma]: books and movies. So I sometimes feel that, you know, a long story can never be too long.

00:23:25.920 --> 00:23:29.440
[Amit Varma]: Borges once made a map of the world, wrote a story about a map of the world, which was

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:33.520
[Amit Varma]: as big as the world itself, you know, and I think the best stories can actually be longer

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:37.440
[Amit Varma]: than what their story is about. Because, like, it's not good. By the way, that Shakespeare

00:23:37.440 --> 00:23:43.160
[Amit Varma]: Tana just reflected on that. I did read all of Shakespeare at 10. But my favorite play

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:47.640
[Amit Varma]: of Shakespeare was Titus Andronicus. So it is clear that I did not read with much discernment.

00:23:47.640 --> 00:23:54.160
[Amit Varma]: But when the TK exciting story I want to take off on something you said, which intrigued

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:59.700
[Amit Varma]: me a lot and ask kind of both of you about that. You mentioned that, you know, your father

00:23:59.700 --> 00:24:04.960
[Amit Varma]: would watch all of these films, and they had a lot of watch that song while I show and

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:08.640
[Amit Varma]: it had a lot of resonance with him and he'd be able to name the song before it came just

00:24:08.640 --> 00:24:14.240
[Amit Varma]: from who the playback singer is and all that. And you could also do that by 12. And what

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:19.440
[Amit Varma]: what I see happening there is that there is obviously a part of your father which is touched

00:24:19.440 --> 00:24:24.240
[Amit Varma]: by that, which is touched by a particular kind of culture, a particular kind of song.

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:28.880
[Amit Varma]: And through that, you are sharing in that. And typically, what happens is men don't share

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:33.440
[Amit Varma]: feelings, especially between father and son, especially in a society like India, we're

00:24:33.440 --> 00:24:37.060
[Amit Varma]: never sharing feelings, you never really know the other person, you're kind of imprisoned

00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:42.340
[Amit Varma]: in your respective roles and the grooves that you've gotten into. And I'm just thinking

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:46.560
[Amit Varma]: aloud here. But when you said that, it seemed that that is a very interesting way to get

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:51.040
[Amit Varma]: to know somebody else, especially in this particular kind of relationship, through a

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:56.660
[Amit Varma]: particular kind of art, like I think my father also, until the end wasn't really communicative.

00:24:56.660 --> 00:25:02.360
[Amit Varma]: But I could get glimpses of his by the kind of things he wanted to read in his last days.

00:25:02.360 --> 00:25:06.680
[Amit Varma]: He'd asked me to, you know, he shared my Amazon account. So he asked me to buy some Stefan

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:10.440
[Amit Varma]: Zwick for him on the Kindle, which I did. And then I started reading Zwick myself and

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:13.840
[Amit Varma]: all I had read of Stefan Zwick before that was the Royal Game, which was about chess

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:18.520
[Amit Varma]: and all that. But then you look at his writings on exile, on feeling not at home where you

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:24.840
[Amit Varma]: are, and there is something in that. So, you know, what are sort of your thoughts on this,

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:30.240
[Amit Varma]: on how these shared interests between people are not just shared interests, but they are

00:25:30.240 --> 00:25:34.880
[Amit Varma]: a kind of connection, because you're getting, you're in a sense, when I tell you about a

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:38.880
[Amit Varma]: book I really like, I am bearing a part of myself to you and vice versa.

00:25:38.880 --> 00:25:44.840
[Guest 1]: Yeah, before I come to that, Amit, I just wanted to say, listening to Subrata, I was

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:50.720
[Guest 1]: just reminded again of how even when the specifics of our lives are different, you know, someone

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:54.760
[Guest 1]: growing up in a small town, someone growing up in Delhi, for instance, but there's something

00:25:54.760 --> 00:26:01.120
[Guest 1]: about there's a shared experience when it comes to Indians of a particular generation,

00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:07.400
[Guest 1]: going through this journey of the 1980s. So much of what you said was just instantly relatable,

00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:10.880
[Guest 1]: even though, you know, the specifics of my life may have been different. You know what

00:26:10.880 --> 00:26:16.080
[Guest 1]: you said about the horror films. Today, I think of myself as someone who's, you know,

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:20.160
[Guest 1]: at risk of sounding pompous, something of an authority on horror cinema. It's something

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:25.520
[Guest 1]: that I've been very interested in, you know, going back to the 1910s, 1920s, all sorts

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:29.800
[Guest 1]: of horror films. But listening to Subrata, I was actually reminded that one of my entry

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:36.000
[Guest 1]: points into horror cinema was for base reasons, which is for the potentially salacious content,

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:40.240
[Guest 1]: because as you know, in the 1980s, certain sorts of horror films were among mainstream

00:26:40.240 --> 00:26:45.000
[Guest 1]: films that were somewhat available at video parlours. They were the ones where you had

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:52.040
[Guest 1]: the most chance of seeing nudity, for instance. You know, you have the classic 1980s American

00:26:52.040 --> 00:26:58.000
[Guest 1]: cliche of the coeds making out before the monster comes for them, you know, and the

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:04.120
[Guest 1]: whole moralistic thing, the evil dead, the Friday the 13th series and so on. So I was

00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:07.280
[Guest 1]: reminded of that. And of course, what you said about the Friday night films and what

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:12.840
[Guest 1]: you said about the regional language, the non Hindi language films that would play on

00:27:12.840 --> 00:27:16.960
[Guest 1]: Sunday. There's so much shared experience there. To come to what you said just now,

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:23.440
[Guest 1]: Amit, I was also, it's true, obviously, you know, the way in which we get to know other

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:30.120
[Guest 1]: people through these shared tastes. And in fact, since you mentioned parents and since

00:27:30.120 --> 00:27:36.120
[Guest 1]: you mentioned a father specifically, I was also reminded that I had quite a problematic

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:40.360
[Guest 1]: relationship with my father in the sense that my parents were divorced when I was 9 or 10.

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:44.160
[Guest 1]: My father had a history of substance abuse, there was domestic violence, etc. It wasn't

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:49.560
[Guest 1]: a very happy situation. And then he passed away a few years ago, and again, in very sad

00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:54.240
[Guest 1]: circumstances. And there's a lot of regret that I have whenever it comes to him not being

00:27:54.240 --> 00:28:00.400
[Guest 1]: able to bond with him or talk with him. Yet one of the fondest and gentlest memories that

00:28:00.400 --> 00:28:07.120
[Guest 1]: I have vis-a-vis my father, which is also something that's a reminder that there was

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:11.920
[Guest 1]: a point in his life, at least when things were relatively normal, when he was interested

00:28:11.920 --> 00:28:17.440
[Guest 1]: in the same things that I would independently become interested in later. When I was 16,

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:21.160
[Guest 1]: on my birthday, he gifted me an old book of his, which was actually a book of his dating

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:28.640
[Guest 1]: back to the early 70s. It's Garson Cannon's book on Katharine Hepburn and Spencer Tracy.

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:33.720
[Guest 1]: Tracy and Hepburn. It's a very personal book on Tracy and Hepburn written by one of their

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:40.680
[Guest 1]: closest friends. So it's a warm, affectionate, up-close look at these two great stars. And

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:46.000
[Guest 1]: my father, when he was fairly young, just in his early, when he was around 20, 21, he

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:51.280
[Guest 1]: bought the book and he had it with him. He gifted it to me more than 20 years later.

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:55.800
[Guest 1]: And I still have it with me. He has a very nice dedication on it. And it strikes me that

00:28:55.800 --> 00:29:01.280
[Guest 1]: I never actually sat with him and discussed old films with him. That never really happened.

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:04.840
[Guest 1]: But this did provide me a window into the things that he might have been interested

00:29:04.840 --> 00:29:09.640
[Guest 1]: in as well. And of course, with my mother, it was a different relationship. It was a

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:15.680
[Guest 1]: much, much closer, much more long lasting relationship. Some of my movie love came from

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:21.760
[Guest 1]: her. She was a very egalitarian viewer. She never really had highbrow taste, but she was

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:28.040
[Guest 1]: into all sorts of films in the 90s, which was supposedly such a bad time for mainstream

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:32.160
[Guest 1]: Hindi cinema. She would be sitting and watching video cassettes of everything and refusing

00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:36.400
[Guest 1]: to even fast forward the songs, which is something that everybody did back then because the songs

00:29:36.400 --> 00:29:43.160
[Guest 1]: were so lousy and you just felt like you deluded yourself that the rest of the film is worthwhile,

00:29:43.160 --> 00:29:47.920
[Guest 1]: but fast forward the song. She would insist on the song being played all the way through

00:29:47.920 --> 00:29:53.280
[Guest 1]: no matter how tuneless it was. So that, of course, also played a part. At the same time,

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:58.440
[Guest 1]: she also from her South Bombay childhood, she had memories of Hollywood films of an

00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:03.760
[Guest 1]: earlier of another era, which were perhaps more sophisticated films. So that did come

00:30:03.760 --> 00:30:09.080
[Guest 1]: down to me a bit. But yeah, what you say about the shared experiences is obviously completely

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:10.080
[Guest 1]: true.

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:18.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, just on that book, Hebburn and Tracy book, they never married. Tracy was still,

00:30:18.320 --> 00:30:24.320
[Guest 2]: you know, he had, he was married and he never, but, you know, and Tracy was, I mean, he was

00:30:24.320 --> 00:30:29.520
[Guest 2]: really ill in his last days. And, you know, it's an industrial lore as to how Hebburn

00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:35.640
[Guest 2]: took care of him in the last few years. And again, these are things that, these are things

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:40.240
[Guest 2]: that have picked up just watching some random documentary in some evening or somewhere.

00:30:40.240 --> 00:30:44.480
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's just amazing how many things you pick up if you just are interested in

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:49.760
[Guest 2]: films about, you know, about just the people and the characters. But going back, you know,

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:55.160
[Guest 2]: the interesting thing is my on, you know, about father and shared interests and things

00:30:55.160 --> 00:31:01.240
[Guest 2]: of that kind. I mean, there is always this part of you that wants to prove, you know,

00:31:01.240 --> 00:31:05.760
[Guest 2]: to your father that you are, you are good, right? And you're good in the things that

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:11.360
[Guest 2]: he values, right? So, that obviously, so this was not the rebel phase. This was the early

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:15.480
[Guest 2]: phase when, you know, you would like to show to him that you are, you are really a good

00:31:15.480 --> 00:31:21.880
[Guest 2]: guy. And so I was, I was interested in doing that. But quite honestly, somewhere the thing

00:31:21.880 --> 00:31:31.720
[Guest 2]: also changed where I really started liking that stuff. And I often, I mean, I have this

00:31:31.720 --> 00:31:37.640
[Guest 2]: arguments and sometimes written about it as to run that podcast, I have mentioned this

00:31:37.640 --> 00:31:43.640
[Guest 2]: a few times, you can, you can, you know, point to, you know, the 40s and the 50s and the

00:31:43.640 --> 00:31:48.600
[Guest 2]: 60s of Hindi cinema. And Hindi cinema is what I'm more comfortable with. I've seen some

00:31:48.600 --> 00:31:52.840
[Guest 2]: of the other language cinemas during that time. And some of that might be true, might

00:31:52.840 --> 00:31:57.760
[Guest 2]: hold true for them as well. Maybe the story might not be sometimes great, the acting could

00:31:57.760 --> 00:32:06.000
[Guest 2]: be a bit hammy and theatrical. But when it comes to music, for that 20-25 years, I mean,

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:12.520
[Guest 2]: I've with reasonable amount of objectivity now that I've heard a lot of the, you know,

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:20.720
[Guest 2]: just the Hollywood musical golden age of 50s and 60s. And then listen to, you know, the

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:27.000
[Guest 2]: other songs, the other stuff. I think this was second to none, you know, just the idea

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:34.640
[Guest 2]: of the composer coming up with those tunes, the lyric being written in a way that is both

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:42.480
[Guest 2]: relevant to that script, but on its own great poetry. Some of the best singers, I don't

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:47.960
[Guest 2]: think the three have come together so well. At any time, I mean, there might be just a

00:32:47.960 --> 00:32:56.600
[Guest 2]: few similar phases, maybe some late, you know, 19th century France and maybe Hollywood, you

00:32:56.600 --> 00:33:02.080
[Guest 2]: know, the golden age of Hollywood musicals. But I mean, it's very difficult to find that

00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:08.440
[Guest 2]: kind of coming together of talent and just the quality of that output. And I don't think

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:15.160
[Guest 2]: people fully appreciate now in India, what was that phase like? And I guess it will take

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:19.880
[Guest 2]: maybe another 100 years later, we'll just be wondering how did this happen. And for

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:26.720
[Guest 2]: at least me, I was deeply invested in it. And it's almost like now it's, I mean, every

00:33:26.720 --> 00:33:36.320
[Guest 2]: day I just go deeper into it. So I'm never bored of it. You know, it's on a standalone

00:33:36.320 --> 00:33:41.480
[Guest 2]: basis. Even when I was a child, I realized this was something really good. And that often

00:33:41.480 --> 00:33:44.840
[Guest 2]: I realized also it was something precious, because I could compare it with what I was

00:33:44.840 --> 00:33:50.960
[Guest 2]: listening to then, which was sort of prevalent in the Ganesh Pooja pendals of where I was

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:55.720
[Guest 2]: growing up. You know, and I realized that was we've lost something precious, but whatever

00:33:55.720 --> 00:34:02.560
[Guest 2]: this was, this is really, really good stuff. And that realization was, maybe my father

00:34:02.560 --> 00:34:09.680
[Guest 2]: stoked it. Maybe in order to impress, I continued to sort of invest time on it. But once I was

00:34:09.680 --> 00:34:14.120
[Guest 2]: out of it, and just on a standalone basis, I just became completely obsessed with it.

00:34:14.120 --> 00:34:19.720
[Guest 2]: And that obsession continues. I mean, I, I've not gone back and watched a lot of old Hindi

00:34:19.720 --> 00:34:26.920
[Guest 2]: films, a second or a third time, a few I have. But songs every morning, I mean, I start my

00:34:26.920 --> 00:34:34.440
[Guest 2]: day with, after the initial Bheem Sen Joshi and Mallika Arjun Mansoor and Kumar Gandha,

00:34:34.440 --> 00:34:41.320
[Guest 2]: that's like for about 20 minutes, my first port of call is Ratha. So I, you know, so

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:47.560
[Guest 2]: yeah, so my father led me into that. And then, you know, I'm always grateful that I discovered

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:54.320
[Guest 2]: something that has given a lot of comfort in some sense meaning to my life from there

00:34:54.320 --> 00:35:00.200
[Guest 2]: on. I mean, it's, like I said, it's an OSS in my life, if everything else is going wrong,

00:35:00.200 --> 00:35:05.160
[Guest 2]: that thing in the morning, just puts everything into perspective that no matter how things

00:35:05.160 --> 00:35:09.520
[Guest 2]: are, how bad they are, this will always stay with me and this appreciation of what is what

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:11.280
[Guest 2]: I'm hearing will always stay with me.

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:17.680
[Guest 1]: If I can just, just add something to that. Subrata, you of course, are talking more about

00:35:17.680 --> 00:35:22.120
[Guest 1]: the audio experience, you know, the combination of the song, the lyric, the quality of the

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:27.600
[Guest 1]: singing, the composition and so on. There's that other dimension to it, which is not consistently

00:35:27.600 --> 00:35:33.080
[Guest 1]: there, but certainly in the films of some directors like Vijay Anand, Guru Dutt, Raj

00:35:33.080 --> 00:35:41.040
[Guest 1]: Kapoor to some degree, Bimal Roy, the visualization. And of course, we all know that there are

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:47.000
[Guest 1]: many instances in old Hindi cinema of a great song not being brought well to the screen,

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:51.320
[Guest 1]: you know, there's a lip syncing is a bit off, the actors gestures are a bit off, the editing

00:35:51.320 --> 00:35:59.640
[Guest 1]: is less than perfect. But, you know, there's so many other cases in the films of the filmmakers

00:35:59.640 --> 00:36:04.960
[Guest 1]: I mentioned, where there's so much attention to detail that's gone into how the thing appears

00:36:04.960 --> 00:36:10.480
[Guest 1]: on the screen, you know, in films like Guide, for instance, or Kagaz Ke Phool or there are

00:36:10.480 --> 00:36:17.080
[Guest 1]: many other films, some of Rishikesh Mukherjee's work as well, some of the later work and it's

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:23.160
[Guest 1]: really quite a remarkable achievement to have all that brought together so well, especially

00:36:23.160 --> 00:36:27.440
[Guest 1]: given the conditions in which many of these films were made, where music was composed

00:36:27.440 --> 00:36:35.400
[Guest 1]: separately, the lyrics were written separately, very often, in some cases, musical sequences

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:39.600
[Guest 1]: were shot by the assistant director, rather than the main director. This wasn't the case

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:44.200
[Guest 1]: for people like Guru Dutt and Vijay Anand and Rishikesh Mukherjee, but it was the case

00:36:44.200 --> 00:36:50.040
[Guest 1]: sometimes. So that really, and I'm speaking now as someone who has to admit to having

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:55.440
[Guest 1]: come a bit late to that particular world. It really, it was fairly late in life that

00:36:55.440 --> 00:37:01.240
[Guest 1]: I really rediscovered or properly discovered the Hindi cinema of the 50s, 60s, found myself

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:07.040
[Guest 1]: sufficiently immersed in it, despite the many little flaws or little or big flaws that you

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:12.400
[Guest 1]: pointed out, you know, the awkwardness, the tonal unevenness of many of those films, the

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:19.000
[Guest 1]: formulaic nature of some of them. But the good stuff, you know, it's fairly late in

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:25.280
[Guest 1]: life, it's just swept over me. And that's also one reason why I ended up doing this

00:37:25.280 --> 00:37:29.480
[Guest 1]: book on Rishikesh Mukherjee, because it just came from a place where I had suddenly in

00:37:29.480 --> 00:37:34.760
[Guest 1]: my 30s, I said, Wow, okay, I've discovered this world. And there was a time when I used

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:39.800
[Guest 1]: to think of cinema only in terms of good cinema only in terms of the Goddards and the felonies

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:44.440
[Guest 1]: and that sort of thing. And suddenly, this is a new language that I'm rediscovering and

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:50.120
[Guest 1]: finding warmth and something really stimulating in it as well.

00:37:50.120 --> 00:37:56.280
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so I mean, you know, since we are talking about this, sometimes I, you know, mention

00:37:56.280 --> 00:38:01.840
[Guest 2]: this just to give people a bit of context about some of these people and some of these

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:06.200
[Guest 2]: names and maybe later they became caricatures of their own, sort of what they were doing.

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:12.760
[Guest 2]: So for instance, take Raj Kapoor. By the time he was 25, he was running a studio, he was

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:19.560
[Guest 2]: a producer, he was a director, he got some of the best talents together, you know, Shankar,

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:27.720
[Guest 2]: Jai Kishan, Hasrat, Shailendra, Lata, Mukesh, K. A. Abbas, for writing scripts, Ramanand

00:38:27.720 --> 00:38:35.080
[Guest 2]: Sagar was his assistant, of course, he went on to make Ramayana with those arrows flying

00:38:35.080 --> 00:38:40.160
[Guest 2]: from one end to the other, and one of them disappearing and much to the surprise of Lakshman.

00:38:40.160 --> 00:38:44.760
[Guest 2]: I mean, this entire Kedar Sharma, there were a whole lot of people that he brought together

00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:49.520
[Guest 2]: when he was 25. I mean, he was just leader of men, women, whatever you might call it.

00:38:49.520 --> 00:38:55.880
[Guest 2]: And then he was asking them to, I mean, those initial films, I mean, you know, Aag is a

00:38:55.880 --> 00:39:01.960
[Guest 2]: little uneven. I mean, it's still a very powerful story, and very different story. I mean, it's

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:07.720
[Guest 2]: a story of three different women, one of who has actually had, and he kind of repeated

00:39:07.720 --> 00:39:15.000
[Guest 2]: the story later in Satyam, Shivam, Sundaram. But you take Awara, you take Shree Charasubis,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:20.840
[Guest 2]: these are just almost like, you know, for a 27 year old, for a 28 year old to be producer,

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:25.200
[Guest 2]: director, then do all of these things together, and bring that story to light. And these are

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:32.160
[Guest 2]: not like just domestic successes. I mean, Awara was just an international, global hit.

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:37.040
[Guest 2]: I mean, even when you go now to Greece, you know, forget the Eastern Europe, that is of

00:39:37.040 --> 00:39:43.360
[Guest 2]: course, a well documented story. There's just fans of Nargis and fans of Awara. But just

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:50.000
[Guest 2]: to point one particular, and sometimes people fully, I mean, don't appreciate this. So just

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:54.440
[Guest 2]: take Shree Charasubis, right? There's Shree Charasubis, I mean, for those who have not

00:39:54.440 --> 00:40:01.160
[Guest 2]: seen the film, is a classic story of a guy coming from a village, comes to big bad, bad

00:40:01.160 --> 00:40:09.960
[Guest 2]: Bombay. He's a, you know, he's a simpleton, but he's a guy who sort of, you know, he knows

00:40:09.960 --> 00:40:14.600
[Guest 2]: the ways of the world, very quickly gets to sort of appreciate it, falls in love with

00:40:14.600 --> 00:40:21.440
[Guest 2]: a girl in the Juggi, who's Nargis. So this is Raj Kapoor who comes in. And then of course,

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:29.120
[Guest 2]: is really a deft hand at cards. And so, you know, he starts playing that Amit. And after

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:36.040
[Guest 2]: some time, you know, gets sort of drawn into this, you know, people who, you know, who

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:42.120
[Guest 2]: are rich, but also who are, you know, doing all kinds of nefarious stuff. And then he

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:47.880
[Guest 2]: there is a pivotal moment in the film, right, where he's taken Nargis to a party because

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:54.760
[Guest 2]: he's been invited and this is all the rich and the famous of Bombay. This is a short,

00:40:54.760 --> 00:41:00.600
[Guest 2]: almost a replica of the Taj Palace possibly in the RK studio in Chembur. And there is

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:08.320
[Guest 2]: Nadira, who's in some sense, you know, the other sort of love interest who's, you know,

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:14.320
[Guest 2]: she has that long, thin cigarette holder, and she's smoking that and you know, all of

00:41:14.320 --> 00:41:19.120
[Guest 2]: that. And then Nargis feels uncomfortable and there are some, you know, remarks made

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:24.960
[Guest 2]: and she decides to leave in the middle of the party. And then Raj Kapoor follows her

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:31.320
[Guest 2]: trying to, you know, call her back. And that's when Nadira sings Mud Mud Ke Na Dekh, right?

00:41:31.320 --> 00:41:36.760
[Guest 2]: She's essentially don't look back. If you see that whole picturization, so what happens

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:42.720
[Guest 2]: is she says Mud Mud Ke Na Dekh and then gradually after the first stanza, you can see that Raj

00:41:42.720 --> 00:41:48.640
[Guest 2]: Kapoor has realized there's no point following Nargis now. And this place is glitz and glamour

00:41:48.640 --> 00:41:52.320
[Guest 2]: and all of this is great. I mean, and you know, I have sort of arrived, why should I

00:41:52.320 --> 00:42:00.000
[Guest 2]: go back? And then not just he sort of, you know, he realizes this, he decides that he

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:06.320
[Guest 2]: will accept this, right? And then he joins in the song. I mean, so far it was just Asha

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:13.800
[Guest 2]: singing for Nadira, Mud Mud Ke Na Dekh, right? Now, Raj Kapoor joins in as Mandade and he,

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:19.360
[Guest 2]: there are two stanzas that he sings, right? One of them is Naino Ke Saath, sorry, Mausam

00:42:19.360 --> 00:42:27.160
[Guest 2]: Ke Saath Jo Badalta Jaye, Jo Iske Saanche Mein Hi Dhalta Jaye, Duniya Usi Ki Hai Jo Chalta

00:42:27.160 --> 00:42:35.160
[Guest 2]: Jaye. Both the stanzas are deep in their meaning that, I mean, you just need to, if you have

00:42:35.160 --> 00:42:40.120
[Guest 2]: to be in this game, you have to play the game, you have to modify, change yourself. And that's

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:47.120
[Guest 2]: how you actually win this game. That whole picturization for about seven minutes. You

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:53.240
[Guest 2]: can't get more, you know, better visual sort of storytelling, right? It just captures everything

00:42:53.240 --> 00:42:59.400
[Guest 2]: in a nice lyrical format, great song, great dancing, acting, everything together. Very

00:42:59.400 --> 00:43:05.000
[Guest 2]: difficult to have so much of information packed. And so much of so many emotions, the change,

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:11.320
[Guest 2]: the, and he was doing it when he was 27, right? He was himself dancing and you should see

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:19.040
[Guest 2]: that the way he changes his, you know, the demeanor changes, his sort of how he behaves

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:24.400
[Guest 2]: changes right after he's decided that, okay, she's gone. Now, let me just plunge into this,

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:25.960
[Guest 1]: you know, head first.

00:43:25.960 --> 00:43:31.200
[Guest 1]: He was also, I think, a wonderful song actor, Raj Kapoor, you know, and now someone like

00:43:31.200 --> 00:43:36.240
[Guest 1]: someone like Raj Kapoor is very easy to sort of think of in caricature terms today, you

00:43:36.240 --> 00:43:41.440
[Guest 1]: know, today, a lot of the cinema is just unfashionable today for many, for many young viewers, but

00:43:41.440 --> 00:43:48.240
[Guest 1]: even people of our age who are sort of perhaps a little more intuitively drawn towards restrained,

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:53.760
[Guest 1]: subdued forms of storytelling rather than the melodramatic or the hyper dramatic forms,

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:58.960
[Guest 1]: you know, you look at someone like Raj Kapoor or an actor of that vintage, you just, I was

00:43:58.960 --> 00:44:03.280
[Guest 1]: watching Barsad the other day on the big screen at the India Habitat Center. Now, I have to

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:08.880
[Guest 1]: say that I really think there was a big quality leap from Barsad to Awara, because Barsad is

00:44:08.880 --> 00:44:15.200
[Guest 1]: a film that is difficult even for someone like me to watch. But the number of titters

00:44:15.200 --> 00:44:20.440
[Guest 1]: in the hall, you know, young people were just laughing almost throughout the film, at anything

00:44:20.440 --> 00:44:25.640
[Guest 1]: that that seemed to them even slightly more dramatic than what they used to. So, you know,

00:44:25.640 --> 00:44:29.400
[Guest 1]: then someone like me gets a bit defensive at the same time, even if I can sort of see

00:44:29.400 --> 00:44:33.720
[Guest 1]: the point of what's going on. But I maintain that someone like Raj Kapoor, I really feel

00:44:33.720 --> 00:44:39.080
[Guest 1]: was a wonderful song actor, which is something that, you know, it's an aspect of acting in

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:43.080
[Guest 1]: Hindi cinema that many people have forgotten about now, because partly also because we've

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:48.000
[Guest 1]: entered an age where there is very little lip syncing that happens, you know, you have

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:53.000
[Guest 1]: the more realistic mode of a song, a very good song maybe playing in the background,

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:58.440
[Guest 1]: there's not lip syncing and so on. And as a result, there was the earlier generations

00:44:58.440 --> 00:45:02.680
[Guest 1]: of actors who did this sort of thing well. When you watch the films today, many people

00:45:02.680 --> 00:45:09.600
[Guest 1]: look at it and say, oh, they're just singing, dancing. This is not acting. You know, whereas,

00:45:09.600 --> 00:45:13.680
[Guest 1]: you know, you look at some of the best of them and they've really thrown themselves

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:17.280
[Guest 1]: into that moment. They are performing the moment as well. Raj Kapoor was one of them.

00:45:17.280 --> 00:45:22.520
[Guest 1]: I just wanted to add very quickly, since you said this, though I don't really like facile

00:45:22.520 --> 00:45:26.680
[Guest 1]: comparisons, when I watch the best of Raj Kapoor's early work, especially these scenes

00:45:26.680 --> 00:45:30.800
[Guest 1]: in Awara and Shree Chaar So Bees, which are visually so striking, you know, scenes like

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:35.520
[Guest 1]: that long dream sequence in Awara, a moment where Prithviraj Kapoor is standing by the

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:39.160
[Guest 1]: window and you have that you have that shadow flitting across that face. It always reminds

00:45:39.160 --> 00:45:46.040
[Guest 1]: me of Orson Welles in Hollywood 10 years earlier, and that famous quote where he was given,

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:50.880
[Guest 1]: you know, full freedom almost by RKO to make his first film. And he said, I felt like a

00:45:50.880 --> 00:45:56.680
[Guest 1]: boy with this giant toy train set. And when I look at Raj Kapoor's early work, you see

00:45:56.680 --> 00:46:00.880
[Guest 1]: that same enthusiasm, where can I put the camera? What can I do with it? What can I

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:05.200
[Guest 1]: do with shadows? What can I do? How can I construct this frame? And I think that's that

00:46:05.200 --> 00:46:09.640
[Guest 1]: there's something to be said about that as well, you know, at that age.

00:46:09.640 --> 00:46:13.560
[Amit Varma]: Lots to double click on. And the first one is kind of this, like when you mentioned that,

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:17.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, young people watching that they're laughing because it's so melodramatic, it's

00:46:17.960 --> 00:46:22.360
[Amit Varma]: so whatever. And that's resonant with me, because once upon a time, I would have been

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:28.440
[Amit Varma]: one of those young people, right, I recognized that, that I found a lot of, I mean, my tastes

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:32.520
[Amit Varma]: were obviously drawn towards a more minimal, the more restrained I was, in a sense, fortunate

00:46:32.520 --> 00:46:36.040
[Amit Varma]: enough to be shaped a lot by world cinema. We discussed this in our episode together

00:46:36.040 --> 00:46:41.560
[Amit Varma]: Jay that I once upon a time, I didn't, I looked down on Bollywood a little bit, which obviously

00:46:41.560 --> 00:46:48.240
[Amit Varma]: was a sort of terrible attitude. And recently, I was sort of watching Squid Game, right.

00:46:48.240 --> 00:46:54.240
[Amit Varma]: And I loved Squid Game, but a part of me who kept finding, you know, things to quibble

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:58.440
[Amit Varma]: about the way they acted, and you know, it's not kind of from the Western realistic school

00:46:58.440 --> 00:47:03.360
[Amit Varma]: and all that there's a particular thing happening there. And, and I kept realizing that the

00:47:03.360 --> 00:47:08.440
[Amit Varma]: quibbler was just getting it all wrong, that, you know, that I should just enjoy it for

00:47:08.440 --> 00:47:14.120
[Amit Varma]: what it is, and not try to fit it into my perception of what is worthy art. Like I was

00:47:14.120 --> 00:47:17.480
[Amit Varma]: reading this book called The Immediate Experience, which is a collection of Robert Warshaw's

00:47:17.480 --> 00:47:22.000
[Amit Varma]: essays, famous critic from back in the day. And, and the title says everything, the immediate

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:27.720
[Amit Varma]: experience and Warshaw's whole contention was that, you know, you, you respond in a

00:47:27.720 --> 00:47:32.880
[Amit Varma]: particular way to a film in the moment. And that response is what matters. You know, baaki

00:47:32.880 --> 00:47:37.760
[Amit Varma]: sab jo theory lagate hai, jo gyaan bhatte hai, all that is irrelevant. How are you responding

00:47:37.760 --> 00:47:42.720
[Amit Varma]: to a film in the here and now what is the immediate experience that is what matters

00:47:42.720 --> 00:47:46.640
[Amit Varma]: and Warshaw, of course, was an enemy of pretentiousness. He never liked to use the term film, he would

00:47:46.640 --> 00:47:51.960
[Amit Varma]: always say movie, he championed, you know, B movies, action films, which were otherwise

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:57.560
[Amit Varma]: ignored by, you know, kind of the mainstream sort of critics. And that struck a chord with

00:47:57.560 --> 00:48:03.800
[Amit Varma]: me when I think that sometimes when we criticize cinema or criticize literature or whatever,

00:48:03.800 --> 00:48:09.280
[Amit Varma]: are we overthinking it sometimes, that maybe what really matters is how does it make me

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:14.260
[Amit Varma]: feel in that moment, that you know, your father can see a classic film and hear a classic

00:48:14.260 --> 00:48:18.960
[Amit Varma]: song and feel a particular way. And 30 years later, it can move you in the same way. And

00:48:18.960 --> 00:48:24.840
[Amit Varma]: that alone tells me that my God, it's achieved something to have that sort of resonance.

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:28.840
[Amit Varma]: And after that, if you're going to quibble about ki yaar acting naturalistic nahi thi

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:34.680
[Amit Varma]: yaar editing aise ki, yahaan se yeh kiya aisa nahi karna chahiye tha. And I think and it's

00:48:34.680 --> 00:48:39.800
[Amit Varma]: with age that I've kind of that I kind of recognize this that stop overthinking art.

00:48:39.800 --> 00:48:45.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, sometimes you just got to sit back and soak it in. So what are sort of your ways

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:49.440
[Amit Varma]: of thinking about it? And you know, especially you Jai, you're a professional critic in a

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:53.640
[Amit Varma]: manner of speaking, you've made that journey through different kinds of criticism. And

00:48:53.640 --> 00:48:58.960
[Amit Varma]: we've again discussed some of that journey in our prior episode. So what's your sense

00:48:58.960 --> 00:49:03.520
[Amit Varma]: of that? Has there been a change in you as well with how you view films and art?

00:49:03.520 --> 00:49:07.760
[Guest 1]: Amit, it's a difficult question. I can see both sides of it. You know, I mean, I, you

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:13.480
[Guest 1]: know, I'd actually like to just go entirely with what you said just now about what about

00:49:13.480 --> 00:49:18.560
[Guest 1]: the wash-off position. You know, just let it let the experience sweep over you react

00:49:18.560 --> 00:49:23.440
[Guest 1]: honestly to what what you have experienced in the moment and just do that. And I've had

00:49:23.440 --> 00:49:26.480
[Guest 1]: some wonderful moments of that sort. Also, you know, I can just give you an example of

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:31.360
[Guest 1]: the top of my head. I'd written a piece about this, you know, where, you know, I was watching

00:49:31.360 --> 00:49:34.720
[Guest 1]: Zoya Akhtar's Dil Dhadakne Do, which is and you know, and just and you know, there's this

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:37.760
[Guest 1]: which is which is not really one of the most critically acclaimed films. It's one of those

00:49:37.760 --> 00:49:42.520
[Guest 1]: films that people think of as it's a time it's a it's a film about rich people's problems

00:49:42.520 --> 00:49:48.240
[Guest 1]: and it's not really gritty in the way that Luck by Chance or Gully Boy is. Honestly speaking,

00:49:48.240 --> 00:49:52.400
[Guest 1]: I still think it's my favorite of her films, because it just worked on every level for

00:49:52.400 --> 00:49:57.360
[Guest 1]: me and I was I was just watching it and there's Ranveer Singh on the screen just doing so,

00:49:57.360 --> 00:50:01.640
[Guest 1]: you know, just just walking around being this spoiled rich brat or whatever and I'm just

00:50:01.640 --> 00:50:06.120
[Guest 1]: you know, just interacting with his parents and I just intuitively at one point just lent

00:50:06.120 --> 00:50:09.080
[Guest 1]: across to my wife. I was you know, she was next to me and said, you know, I think this

00:50:09.080 --> 00:50:14.560
[Guest 1]: guy might be our best actor since since Bachchan, you know, I just said that very spontaneously.

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:19.440
[Guest 1]: And of course, later, I sort of thought about it and said, oh, yeah, you know, this is that

00:50:19.440 --> 00:50:27.040
[Guest 1]: was a on the one hand I I get, you know, the value of that instinctive response. But at

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:31.520
[Guest 1]: the same time, there are practical difficulties also, you know, you're say you're you're writing

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:34.520
[Guest 1]: a review that's been written on a three-hour deadline or something, then of course, it

00:50:34.520 --> 00:50:37.920
[Guest 1]: makes sense. You're sitting in the hall and you're, you know, you're taking notes there.

00:50:37.920 --> 00:50:41.720
[Guest 1]: You're trying to capture the immediacy of your experience. You're very aware that that

00:50:41.720 --> 00:50:46.480
[Guest 1]: at some point, you will, you know, you'll be exiting this this dark hall and suddenly

00:50:46.480 --> 00:50:50.600
[Guest 1]: the world, the brightly lit world is going to be impinging on you. And then, you know,

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:54.840
[Guest 1]: you will you'll be overthinking, you'll be remembering the film and maybe feeling sheepish

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:58.600
[Guest 1]: about some things that you that you loved while you were watching them. You're aware

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:03.040
[Guest 1]: of that. So you're trying to capture honesty, capture your reactions in the moment, and

00:51:03.040 --> 00:51:06.800
[Guest 1]: then write the review as quickly as possible and send it out. But what if you're writing

00:51:06.800 --> 00:51:12.600
[Guest 1]: in the form of writing that you have to do is a long form analytical essay with a deadline

00:51:12.600 --> 00:51:18.840
[Guest 1]: of three weeks into the future. At some point, you will, I think it's just human nature to

00:51:18.840 --> 00:51:25.200
[Guest 1]: to be analyzing a little too much to change your view to say, okay, you know, I sort of

00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:30.360
[Guest 1]: had this rush of emotion in the hall, but now I've thought about it a bit and maybe,

00:51:30.360 --> 00:51:35.520
[Guest 1]: you know, I don't feel that way anymore. So I can see the value of both positions depending

00:51:35.520 --> 00:51:39.960
[Guest 1]: on the sort of piece you're writing or the sort of discussion that you're having about

00:51:39.960 --> 00:51:44.840
[Guest 1]: the film. And, you know, I think it's just a practical thing. I think I may have mentioned

00:51:44.840 --> 00:51:52.040
[Guest 1]: this in our earlier conversation. But one reason why I always found it difficult, even

00:51:52.040 --> 00:51:56.440
[Guest 1]: when I was a much younger, more energetic, more enthusiastic film buff going to film

00:51:56.440 --> 00:52:01.800
[Guest 1]: festivals in my 20s. One reason I found it difficult to watch three or four films on

00:52:01.800 --> 00:52:07.500
[Guest 1]: the same day was because I needed that time to myself after watching one film, if it stimulated

00:52:07.500 --> 00:52:12.680
[Guest 1]: me in a certain way, I would need to go and sit by myself, maybe just make some notes,

00:52:12.680 --> 00:52:17.960
[Guest 1]: maybe, you know, get my bearings, articulate to myself or on paper or whatever, what I

00:52:17.960 --> 00:52:21.720
[Guest 1]: felt about that film before going in for the next film. Because otherwise, you're watching

00:52:21.720 --> 00:52:25.240
[Guest 1]: one film when you're watching another, you're watching a third, coming back home at night

00:52:25.240 --> 00:52:29.680
[Guest 1]: and and the immediacy of the experience of the first and the second film are gone. They

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:35.760
[Guest 1]: no longer exist. So it's a difficult question. This is just I probably just rambled on and

00:52:35.760 --> 00:52:40.880
[Guest 1]: on. But I think I can see both sides of the way of doing this.

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:51.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I have always been that viewer. I mean, I just go to a movie and I just respond

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:57.240
[Guest 2]: to it the way you know, it comes to me. I mean, there's not a lot of thought then or

00:52:57.240 --> 00:53:03.040
[Guest 2]: sometimes even later. I mean, I do the connects much later, not in that day, because I have

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:08.720
[Guest 2]: no deadline or anything of that kind. I'm not writing anything. But most of the, I mean,

00:53:08.720 --> 00:53:16.400
[Guest 2]: most of how I watch a film is exactly that way. I mean, I, it's just, just experiencing

00:53:16.400 --> 00:53:22.640
[Guest 2]: it at the moment, during the moment and enjoying it. And that really, in some sense, also explains

00:53:22.640 --> 00:53:29.000
[Guest 2]: some of these things. I mean, like, I just like sort of the big, you know, emotional

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:34.120
[Guest 2]: kind of films. I mean, give me a Casablanca, I'll watch it any number of times. It's just

00:53:34.120 --> 00:53:40.200
[Guest 2]: a great film. I mean, you can say that maybe there are better films in 1942 than that.

00:53:40.200 --> 00:53:45.880
[Guest 2]: Forget about in the history of Hollywood. But I mean, I, I remember the first time when

00:53:45.880 --> 00:53:51.960
[Guest 2]: I saw it and how great it felt. And every time I again watch it, it feels the same way,

00:53:51.960 --> 00:53:57.040
[Guest 2]: right. So and the same thing applies to I mean, all of the 80s and the 90s. I mean,

00:53:57.040 --> 00:54:02.640
[Guest 2]: they were barren time, they were, they were my time. I watched all of them. Rajiv Rai

00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:11.880
[Guest 2]: for the win, any day, right. Suppose you, if you watched Yudh, you know what I'm saying.

00:54:11.880 --> 00:54:18.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, Yudh and Tridev, two great films and Rajiv Rai was just absolutely peak of his

00:54:18.680 --> 00:54:23.720
[Guest 2]: form. And for those who don't know what Yudh is, Yudh is the original film where Anil Kapoor

00:54:23.720 --> 00:54:31.800
[Guest 1]: says Jagas. So, you know, if I can just just add something to perhaps, you know, with a

00:54:31.800 --> 00:54:38.400
[Guest 1]: more specific concrete example to, you know, just expand on that. I think both things can

00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:42.040
[Guest 1]: also go together if you're a professional writer. So, you know, so for instance, I mentioned

00:54:42.040 --> 00:54:45.400
[Guest 1]: the Rishikesh Mukherjee thing, you know, my starting point for the Rishikesh Mukherjee

00:54:45.400 --> 00:54:50.560
[Guest 1]: book happened when I happened to watch a number of his films close together. And I suddenly

00:54:50.560 --> 00:54:56.440
[Guest 1]: felt this thrill of recognising that in films that otherwise didn't really seem to have

00:54:56.440 --> 00:55:02.280
[Guest 1]: anything in common in terms of their plots, there were these little thematic, these themes

00:55:02.280 --> 00:55:07.520
[Guest 1]: running through the films, which seemed to point to a particular sensibility or a particular

00:55:07.520 --> 00:55:11.920
[Guest 1]: director or script writer who was interested in certain themes. And it could be a theme

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:17.640
[Guest 1]: like disguise, pretense, whatever, something like that, in films where the storylines were

00:55:17.640 --> 00:55:25.320
[Guest 1]: completely different, maybe made 20 years apart. But so I felt that thrill of that recognition

00:55:25.320 --> 00:55:30.200
[Guest 1]: of, you know, that there's a sensibility here and I want to explore the sensibility, maybe

00:55:30.200 --> 00:55:34.760
[Guest 1]: write about this director who's made these different works. So that is the immediate

00:55:34.760 --> 00:55:38.320
[Guest 1]: thing, the immediate emotional response. But then when you're sitting and working on the

00:55:38.320 --> 00:55:43.080
[Guest 1]: book over a period of two or three years, while writing those same things, you're also,

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:47.680
[Guest 1]: you know, perforce, you're just, you know, you are analysing, you're bringing in other

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:52.600
[Guest 1]: things, you know, about other films from similar genres, you're providing that contextual stuff

00:55:52.600 --> 00:55:57.840
[Guest 1]: in. So all that also goes in. So the starting point may be the direct, immediate emotional

00:55:57.840 --> 00:56:04.240
[Guest 1]: response. But then, as a professional writer, you will also bring in some of the other post

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:07.040
[Guest 1]: facto analysis that will happen.

00:56:07.040 --> 00:56:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a great point. I mean, first, we, I guess, experience a world and then we

00:56:10.600 --> 00:56:14.880
[Amit Varma]: try to understand it. And, you know, and what you said about film festivals is really is

00:56:14.880 --> 00:56:21.200
[Amit Varma]: resonant to me in the sense that until COVID happened, my annual vacation was spent in

00:56:21.200 --> 00:56:24.860
[Amit Varma]: Bombay itself, where the MAMI film festival would happen, and I would go and I would watch

00:56:24.860 --> 00:56:29.920
[Amit Varma]: four or five films a day or whatever I could, I was an expert at optimising, obviously,

00:56:29.920 --> 00:56:36.040
[Amit Varma]: and just watch 28-29 films in the week that I could. And I get that, that you don't have

00:56:36.040 --> 00:56:40.240
[Amit Varma]: the space to sit back and reflect. So it is all visceral, visceral, visceral, you're

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:45.080
[Amit Varma]: not really thinking about stuff. But at the same time, I guess, you know, you don't have

00:56:45.080 --> 00:56:48.440
[Amit Varma]: a choice, you just want to take in as much as you can, because some of the greatest delights

00:56:48.440 --> 00:56:52.160
[Amit Varma]: are the unexpected ones, something you've never heard of, and it just kind of blows

00:56:52.160 --> 00:56:56.400
[Amit Varma]: you away. And of course, I think the last couple of years I was, you know, life tweeting,

00:56:56.400 --> 00:57:00.840
[Amit Varma]: I was putting out a tweet about every film I watched. And that was, in a sense, I realised

00:57:00.840 --> 00:57:06.540
[Amit Varma]: post facto a way of taking notes for myself also about, you know, what I liked and didn't

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:10.480
[Amit Varma]: like that. And I'm just thinking aloud here, I remember this quote by some translator,

00:57:10.480 --> 00:57:15.160
[Amit Varma]: I've forgotten who I came across this while researching for this episode on translation

00:57:15.160 --> 00:57:20.840
[Amit Varma]: I did with Aruna Vasana. And the quote was something to the effect of that even the act

00:57:20.840 --> 00:57:25.040
[Amit Varma]: of writing is an act of translation, because you're taking your thoughts and you're translating

00:57:25.040 --> 00:57:29.040
[Amit Varma]: them into language. And it strikes me that when you're trying to write about a film or

00:57:29.040 --> 00:57:33.920
[Amit Varma]: write about anything, you know, where you come out of that experience mode, and you

00:57:33.920 --> 00:57:39.080
[Amit Varma]: get into describing it or understanding it, it becomes really difficult because it can

00:57:39.080 --> 00:57:44.720
[Amit Varma]: then be contrived. Like when I think of the great moments in movies, which really moved

00:57:44.720 --> 00:57:48.440
[Amit Varma]: me at the time, which just had me tearing up immediately, you know, as a young person

00:57:48.440 --> 00:57:53.220
[Amit Varma]: dead poet society, the last scene, right for those who haven't seen it and enormously affecting

00:57:53.220 --> 00:57:57.960
[Amit Varma]: for me, those scenes are so powerful, because they just capture the essence of the whole

00:57:57.960 --> 00:58:03.040
[Amit Varma]: thing. And they hit you in the gut with it. And for me, they are impossible to write about,

00:58:03.040 --> 00:58:07.840
[Amit Varma]: I can write about other aspects of the craft and, you know, other things here and there.

00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:13.920
[Amit Varma]: But for me, I can't capture that essential thing, you know, and I understand that part

00:58:13.920 --> 00:58:17.840
[Amit Varma]: of our job is not just to experience the world, but to write about it. That's what writers

00:58:17.840 --> 00:58:23.620
[Amit Varma]: do. That's what we all try to do it, you know, differing levels, but it seems incredibly

00:58:23.620 --> 00:58:26.840
[Amit Varma]: difficult in one person. And you're right, I agree with you that it's possible for both

00:58:26.840 --> 00:58:31.440
[Amit Varma]: to go together. And to me, my favorite film critic for that reason is Roger Ebert, because

00:58:31.440 --> 00:58:36.280
[Amit Varma]: you got a sense of both conditions, you got a sense of how a film moved him deeply. And

00:58:36.280 --> 00:58:40.360
[Amit Varma]: at the same time, you got insight into the craft and, you know, like his writing about

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:45.480
[Amit Varma]: Ramin Bairani, for example, when he wrote about the film Goodbye Solo, you know, the

00:58:45.480 --> 00:58:50.480
[Amit Varma]: review moved me so much that I watched the film and was blown away by it, you know, where

00:58:50.480 --> 00:58:55.560
[Amit Varma]: he you know, Bairani is getting to the heart of the human condition with that film. And,

00:58:55.560 --> 00:58:59.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, Ebert's writing about that film, you know, leads you there as well.

00:58:59.480 --> 00:59:04.760
[Guest 1]: Yeah, no, I, I also want to want to ask you a question somewhat related to this, but but

00:59:04.760 --> 00:59:10.800
[Guest 1]: also before before that, also just to add that, you know, you can also take this this

00:59:10.800 --> 00:59:16.760
[Guest 1]: business of reacting only emotionally and only this in the moment, you can perhaps take

00:59:16.760 --> 00:59:20.560
[Guest 1]: it too far at times, you know, someone like Pauline Kyle, for instance, she was famous

00:59:20.560 --> 00:59:25.320
[Guest 1]: for and she's been criticized a lot for it laterally. She was famous for insisting on

00:59:25.320 --> 00:59:29.480
[Guest 1]: never seeing a film a second time. Watch it once, you know, just, you know, your scribble

00:59:29.480 --> 00:59:32.680
[Guest 1]: away sitting there in the dark, you know, which which is wonderful. And of course, we

00:59:32.680 --> 00:59:37.120
[Guest 1]: know her body of work and where it came from and the passion. It's not in doubt at all.

00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:42.160
[Guest 1]: But she never kept herself open to revisiting a film and possibly changing her mind about

00:59:42.160 --> 00:59:47.600
[Guest 1]: it. That's something that can also be done, right? You can, you might very honestly have

00:59:47.600 --> 00:59:52.520
[Guest 1]: a particular emotional experience to a film, watching it the first time, and then 10 years

00:59:52.520 --> 00:59:56.840
[Guest 1]: later, you're watching it again and you have a different sort of emotional experience,

00:59:56.840 --> 01:00:01.920
[Guest 1]: which might be, you know, it might not be as good as before, or it might be good in

01:00:01.920 --> 01:00:05.840
[Guest 1]: a different way or whatever it is, but you feel differently about it. Someone like her

01:00:05.840 --> 01:00:10.920
[Guest 1]: did not did not keep herself open to that possibility. And she has been criticized for

01:00:10.920 --> 01:00:15.440
[Guest 1]: it by other critics as well, you know, for just closing that. I wanted to ask you, Amit,

01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:20.280
[Guest 1]: since you mentioned sometime back that you feel like you've become a little more open

01:00:20.280 --> 01:00:25.760
[Guest 1]: to other modes, to the more dramatic or, you know, the other forms of expression that aren't

01:00:25.760 --> 01:00:31.600
[Guest 1]: necessarily psychological realism. I remember I'm asking you this because on two or three

01:00:31.600 --> 01:00:37.200
[Guest 1]: separate occasions on email lists that we've been on or conversations that we've had, I've

01:00:37.200 --> 01:00:41.040
[Guest 1]: seen you put up your list of 10 favorite films. So you know, so I remember the first time

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:44.480
[Guest 1]: I saw this may have been around 15 years ago, and the last time may have been four or five

01:00:44.480 --> 01:00:49.320
[Guest 1]: years ago. So you have films like Decalogue in it, you have John Huston's The Dead, which

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:55.560
[Guest 1]: is a film that he astonishingly made in his 80s, from the James Joyce story, In the Bedroom,

01:00:55.560 --> 01:01:00.000
[Guest 1]: if I remember right, films like that, films that are mostly, you know, from a certain

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:06.360
[Guest 1]: mode of understated psychological realism. And I remember that I saw two lists that you

01:01:06.360 --> 01:01:10.280
[Guest 1]: had made maybe a few years apart that were more or less the same, more or less the same

01:01:10.280 --> 01:01:15.240
[Guest 1]: films in them. Do you feel like if you were to make a list today, that there would be

01:01:15.240 --> 01:01:19.920
[Guest 1]: you know, you don't have to name the films, but that there would be one or two films that

01:01:19.920 --> 01:01:25.840
[Guest 1]: don't fit that particular mode of psychological realism or understatement, something that's

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:32.440
[Guest 1]: louder, brassier, would there be something like that, a film or a web series even?

01:01:32.440 --> 01:01:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Devdas by Sanjay Leela Bhansali. In fact, I remember Devdas by Bhansali, Devdas and

01:01:40.240 --> 01:01:45.480
[Amit Varma]: Parineeta came out around the same time. And I really liked Parineeta as an example of

01:01:45.480 --> 01:01:50.640
[Amit Varma]: melodrama well done. And Devdas is an example of melodrama overdone. But anyway, I won't

01:01:50.640 --> 01:01:55.840
[Amit Varma]: elaborate on that. But that's a great question. And it's also a great observation. Because,

01:01:55.840 --> 01:01:59.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, in the note that I sent you guys in the email, I said, let's talk about five

01:01:59.240 --> 01:02:05.240
[Amit Varma]: under appreciated film. And that got me to thinking about what are my favorite films

01:02:05.240 --> 01:02:10.400
[Amit Varma]: today. And I realized the folly of ever having made a list like that, like, of course, we

01:02:10.400 --> 01:02:15.840
[Amit Varma]: love making lists, 10 films, 10, whatever. And I think when you're a teenager, it's fine.

01:02:15.840 --> 01:02:22.160
[Amit Varma]: But I think later, I think I mean, I for me, everything contains multitudes in a way that

01:02:22.160 --> 01:02:28.480
[Amit Varma]: I cannot put rankings, I can no longer, you know, rankings and star ratings and all that

01:02:28.480 --> 01:02:34.340
[Amit Varma]: just just seem weird to me. And it seems to reduce a film down to a set of qualities which

01:02:34.340 --> 01:02:40.520
[Amit Varma]: you are then quantifying. If I am to talk about, make a list of films, I would probably

01:02:40.520 --> 01:02:46.200
[Amit Varma]: do that on the basis of what moved me at the time what I felt like at the time and, you

01:02:46.200 --> 01:02:52.760
[Amit Varma]: know, not pontificate on greater artistic merits and all of that. And the thing is that

01:02:52.760 --> 01:02:56.720
[Amit Varma]: my sensibilities are what they are, and my tastes are what they are. So there's no value

01:02:56.720 --> 01:03:02.160
[Amit Varma]: judgment, I may not have a taste for a particular kind of maximalist expressionistic art or

01:03:02.160 --> 01:03:09.080
[Amit Varma]: film or whatever. But unlike in the past, I will no longer say that is bad. I will simply

01:03:09.080 --> 01:03:15.440
[Amit Varma]: say keep matlab mere vibe ka nahi hai, right. So even in terms of literature, for example,

01:03:15.440 --> 01:03:20.680
[Amit Varma]: I recognize that Salman Rushdie is a great writer that Arundhati Roy writes gorgeous

01:03:20.680 --> 01:03:27.640
[Amit Varma]: prose, but their writing is, you know, I, my taste is more towards the minimal, which

01:03:27.640 --> 01:03:32.600
[Amit Varma]: is why, for example, Japanese and Korean authors are much more likely to like them among Indians

01:03:32.600 --> 01:03:40.440
[Amit Varma]: and like Vikram Seth more than Rushdie, for example. So I think that is where I kind of,

01:03:40.440 --> 01:03:45.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, your tastes are what they are, you are who you are. But I can appreciate other

01:03:45.080 --> 01:03:50.720
[Amit Varma]: stuff and there are things I like now, there is art I like now, which would not fall into

01:03:50.720 --> 01:03:54.560
[Amit Varma]: that psychological realism sort of domain. Like, for example, I think one of the great

01:03:54.560 --> 01:04:00.160
[Amit Varma]: novels of all time is Raag Darbari, right. And I love reading Woodhouse as a kid. And

01:04:00.160 --> 01:04:06.560
[Amit Varma]: those don't easily fall into, you know, those narrow categories. But broadly, I would say

01:04:06.560 --> 01:04:10.800
[Amit Varma]: that, I mean, I was just about to say, you'll never find a Bhansali film in my top 10. But

01:04:10.800 --> 01:04:16.120
[Amit Varma]: the point is that Bhansali is a bad melodramatic filmmaker, I'm sure there are good melodramatic

01:04:16.120 --> 01:04:21.000
[Amit Varma]: filmmakers. So my appreciation of melodrama exists, but not his.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:25.160
[Guest 1]: We need someone like Paro Mehta Vohra here to defend Bhansali now, because I don't think

01:04:25.160 --> 01:04:27.160
[Guest 1]: I can do it sufficiently.

01:04:27.160 --> 01:04:34.880
[Amit Varma]: Paro, if you're listening. Yeah. So, you know, before we get to get back to Subrata's life,

01:04:34.880 --> 01:04:37.720
[Amit Varma]: I want to double click on one of the points you said where you're talking about the music

01:04:37.720 --> 01:04:44.360
[Amit Varma]: of that era. And I have a couple of questions about that. That one, when there was such

01:04:44.360 --> 01:04:49.640
[Amit Varma]: a perfect confluence of great music, which was not great music, which wasn't appreciated

01:04:49.640 --> 01:04:54.800
[Amit Varma]: by people, everybody loved it, you know, when there was that confluence of great music,

01:04:54.800 --> 01:05:01.480
[Amit Varma]: and all of it kind of coming together, the lyrics, the musicians, all of that. One, why

01:05:01.480 --> 01:05:06.880
[Amit Varma]: did we lose it? Why did it go? Because you'd imagine that even left to pure market forces,

01:05:06.880 --> 01:05:12.360
[Amit Varma]: that is what is successful, that is what is working. So why would it suddenly go, especially

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:17.640
[Amit Varma]: given that today we live in a time where there is scope for diversity, it is not as if the

01:05:17.640 --> 01:05:22.680
[Amit Varma]: mainstream changes, you're stuck. That's all you have. That's not the case today. You have

01:05:22.680 --> 01:05:27.800
[Amit Varma]: a, you know, 1000 flowers are blooming all over the place. So one, I mean, I'll ask you

01:05:27.800 --> 01:05:32.080
[Amit Varma]: two questions, but one at a time, I guess one, why did we, you know, why did it? What

01:05:32.080 --> 01:05:35.760
[Amit Varma]: are your theories on why that era ended? Why did we lose that?

01:05:35.760 --> 01:05:42.480
[Guest 2]: Yeah. I mean, of course, I mean, one of the good things about life is to sit and theorize

01:05:42.480 --> 01:05:47.600
[Guest 2]: on what happened. And I think I've done this conversation with folks a few times in the

01:05:47.600 --> 01:05:53.280
[Guest 2]: past. But just one point on Raag Darbari. I don't know many people if they realize that

01:05:53.280 --> 01:06:01.800
[Guest 2]: in 86, 87, Doordarshan actually had a TV adaptation of Raag Darbari. And it used to play on Thursday

01:06:01.800 --> 01:06:09.160
[Guest 2]: nights at 10 o'clock. With the opening, you know, whatever the title song of just about

01:06:09.160 --> 01:06:13.440
[Guest 2]: a minute by Bheem Sen Joshi. Wow, I didn't know this.

01:06:13.440 --> 01:06:23.240
[Guest 2]: And the song went, saath sur ke saath rang hai, is duniya mein saath something hai, is

01:06:23.240 --> 01:06:30.440
[Guest 2]: ke uske is duniya mein Raag Darbari. It was a beautiful. Yeah. And Alok Nath, fresh from

01:06:30.440 --> 01:06:36.960
[Guest 2]: his success as master Haveli Ram of Buniyat. And well before the world knew of his predatory

01:06:36.960 --> 01:06:51.200
[Guest 2]: ways. And yeah, well before he became the Sanskari, you know, father, was the Pehelwan.

01:06:51.200 --> 01:06:58.160
[Guest 2]: It was a six or eight episodes. But I remember that because I actually saw Raag Darbari before

01:06:58.160 --> 01:07:04.560
[Guest 2]: I read Raag Darbari. Oh my God. But was it good? Was the series? Yeah, I distinctly remember

01:07:04.560 --> 01:07:08.480
[Guest 2]: watching. I remember watching everything. And I was watching everything. But it clearly

01:07:08.480 --> 01:07:12.920
[Guest 2]: left a mark because I realized again ki kuch alag ho raha hai. I'm not processing. I was

01:07:12.920 --> 01:07:18.680
[Guest 2]: 10 years old. But I could sense ki haan yeh kuch hai. And I, it stuck in my head that

01:07:18.680 --> 01:07:22.920
[Guest 2]: there is a thing called Raag Darbari. And then later the moment I came across, I mean,

01:07:22.920 --> 01:07:27.280
[Guest 2]: by the time I was 14 or 15, you know, there used to be this magazine, Hindi magazine called

01:07:27.280 --> 01:07:34.760
[Guest 2]: Dharm Yug. It's a legendary magazine. The editor was a guy called Dharmveer Bharti.

01:07:34.760 --> 01:07:39.960
[Guest 2]: If we lived in a country that appreciated its own writers well, Dharmveer Bharti would

01:07:39.960 --> 01:07:46.560
[Guest 2]: have been in the same league as Hemingway or Faulkner. Because Dharmveer Bharti, before

01:07:46.560 --> 01:07:54.360
[Guest 2]: he turned 30, by 1954, had written three of the greatest Hindi novels of all time.

01:07:54.360 --> 01:08:03.440
[Guest 2]: He wrote Andha Yog. He wrote Suraj Ka Saatva Ghoda. And he was just, and then he just left,

01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:08.640
[Guest 2]: I think, if you remember Sara Rai in your episode, she mentioned that her mother used

01:08:08.640 --> 01:08:13.760
[Guest 2]: to be corresponding with Dharmveer Bharti because Dharm Yug used to be a Times of India

01:08:13.760 --> 01:08:21.600
[Guest 2]: publication or whatever, now Bharat Times publication. And Dharm Yug used to have some

01:08:21.600 --> 01:08:28.800
[Guest 2]: of the best cartoons. I mean, the last page, the best writing on Hindi literature, even

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:36.360
[Guest 2]: really quality writing on cinema. And why did I come to Dharmveer Bharti? I don't know.

01:08:36.360 --> 01:08:42.720
[Guest 2]: I've lost the thread on this one. But yeah, so sorry, yeah. So, Srilal Shukla and then,

01:08:42.720 --> 01:08:47.320
[Guest 2]: you know, I started reading all these Dharmveer Bharti and you know, all of these guys. And,

01:08:47.320 --> 01:08:52.680
[Guest 2]: you know, I realized that there is more here, you know, in terms of just the Indian literature,

01:08:52.680 --> 01:08:57.240
[Guest 2]: which again, gave me a lot of satisfaction as I went through that. In fact, some of these

01:08:57.240 --> 01:09:03.200
[Guest 2]: things like Suraj Ka Saatva Ghoda was an unreliable narrator way before sort of unreliable narrator

01:09:03.200 --> 01:09:08.920
[Guest 2]: was a sort of a thing in the 60s and the 70s. Anyway, going back, coming back to the point

01:09:08.920 --> 01:09:15.080
[Guest 2]: on what happened with, you know, the talent. One is, you know, it is difficult for such

01:09:15.080 --> 01:09:20.920
[Guest 2]: talent to come together and then have very extended stay. We almost had 20 years of it,

01:09:20.920 --> 01:09:28.960
[Guest 2]: which is by itself just amazing. And, you know, these initial set of people, I normally

01:09:28.960 --> 01:09:36.760
[Guest 2]: start with Anil Biswas, and then, you know, possibly SD Burman, I place Shankar Jaikishan

01:09:36.760 --> 01:09:41.080
[Guest 2]: a bit lower, because I think part of the reason why we lost it eventually was because of Shankar

01:09:41.080 --> 01:09:46.360
[Guest 2]: Jaikishan. These were good guys, but they were after sometimes got driven by a lot by

01:09:46.360 --> 01:09:52.320
[Guest 2]: what market wanted, and also did a bit of politicking in terms of awards and all of

01:09:52.320 --> 01:09:58.280
[Guest 2]: that screwed up the sort of just normal environment of people coming together and doing good quality

01:09:58.280 --> 01:10:06.800
[Guest 2]: work. But just that early set of people, Anil Biswas, SD Burman, Chitragupt Roshan, they

01:10:06.800 --> 01:10:14.000
[Guest 2]: were, see Ramchandra and Madan Mohan, these are like really good quality composers. But

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:18.640
[Guest 2]: you only had that much of time. I mean, many of these guys actually had very poor lifestyles.

01:10:18.640 --> 01:10:24.600
[Guest 2]: I mean, almost all of them died of cirrhosis of liver. Almost all of them who died early.

01:10:24.600 --> 01:10:29.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's not, it's normally not mentioned as specifically, but you will realize that

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:36.120
[Guest 2]: some of the great names, they all died before they turned 50, only for one reason. And so,

01:10:36.120 --> 01:10:41.720
[Guest 2]: in some sense, one reason is it's just natural. I mean, they died, who replaced them were

01:10:41.720 --> 01:10:46.520
[Guest 2]: somewhat, you know, ersatz, you know, versions of these guys, obviously wouldn't have the

01:10:46.520 --> 01:10:53.960
[Guest 2]: same quality. So that was one. Second, I just think that what happened was very gradually

01:10:53.960 --> 01:11:03.680
[Guest 2]: at the margins, there was this attempt to have more and more of orchestration, which

01:11:03.680 --> 01:11:10.120
[Guest 2]: up to a point was good. So, you know, you don't realize that by the mid 60s, there was

01:11:10.120 --> 01:11:16.840
[Guest 2]: almost this, you know, there was this competitive race on how many piece orchestra can you put

01:11:16.840 --> 01:11:26.160
[Guest 2]: in with Noshad hitting 100, right? I think he hit first 100 in Aan, an early 50s film.

01:11:26.160 --> 01:11:31.000
[Guest 2]: But after that, you know, and so what he would do is he would book the studio. And he would

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:37.320
[Guest 2]: book every single, every single, you know, instrumentalist in town, all 100 of them.

01:11:37.320 --> 01:11:40.640
[Guest 2]: And they would play. I think the first one I think where he did something of this kind

01:11:40.640 --> 01:11:45.720
[Guest 2]: was Aan. Aan, by the way, was a film, very famously, it was a long film and they took

01:11:45.720 --> 01:11:51.760
[Guest 2]: it out and you know, in various film circuits and one of the famous reviews of Aan was it

01:11:51.760 --> 01:12:05.440
[Guest 2]: went Aan and Aan and Aan. Dilip Kumar and Nadira, Man Mera Ehsaan, and many good songs.

01:12:05.440 --> 01:12:12.360
[Guest 2]: So this kind of a race to bottom on how many pieces you can use, how grand the music can

01:12:12.360 --> 01:12:18.480
[Guest 2]: be in the hands of somewhat of a better quality, you know, composer and artist, it can still

01:12:18.480 --> 01:12:23.680
[Guest 2]: be managed. And let's be honest, I don't want to get into controversies here. Many of these

01:12:23.680 --> 01:12:29.240
[Guest 2]: music composers are completely dependent on their assistants. And it's reasonably well

01:12:29.240 --> 01:12:33.560
[Guest 2]: known, most of our great music composers couldn't write music. They were just not taught that

01:12:33.560 --> 01:12:42.880
[Guest 2]: way. These are all harmonium melody and then the assistants, some of whom are lost to history

01:12:42.880 --> 01:12:46.360
[Guest 2]: because they have not been documented well now a lot of us and a lot of other people

01:12:46.360 --> 01:12:52.200
[Guest 2]: have documented them. They would actually fill the you know, the substance of the song, right?

01:12:52.200 --> 01:12:57.140
[Guest 2]: When the some of these great names, Sebastian de Souza, Anthony Gonzalves, these are mostly

01:12:57.140 --> 01:13:01.840
[Guest 2]: Goan guys, because they were taught in the church how to write music. And then they could

01:13:01.840 --> 01:13:04.600
[Guest 2]: write and they could, you know, give it to other instrumentalists and they could play

01:13:04.600 --> 01:13:13.240
[Guest 2]: Dattara. Naushad had a very famous assistant who himself composed for Pakiza Ghulam Mohammed

01:13:13.240 --> 01:13:20.360
[Guest 2]: and then of course, Mohammed Shafi. These are great names. But anyway, coming back,

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:27.600
[Guest 2]: you had this race for more number of pieces as it started becoming, you know, it started

01:13:27.600 --> 01:13:32.560
[Guest 2]: going into less talented hands. It started turning into a bit of a noise, but then you

01:13:32.560 --> 01:13:37.560
[Guest 2]: know, people were not, you know, bothered about that they would push that. And for some

01:13:37.560 --> 01:13:44.220
[Guest 2]: reason, you know, I think every decade people have lamented that music is becoming worse,

01:13:44.220 --> 01:13:48.240
[Guest 2]: but nothing would reverse it. I have no idea why, right? I mean, you know, you just got

01:13:48.240 --> 01:13:54.840
[Guest 2]: into this gradual decline of having more and more noisy work. And then somewhere the nature

01:13:54.840 --> 01:14:02.400
[Guest 2]: of the story and the script sector also started changing. And I think we started taking in,

01:14:02.400 --> 01:14:11.040
[Guest 2]: you know, a lot of this with less discernment. I think people were, there would be, you know,

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:16.080
[Guest 2]: sort of pauses in this. I mean, you know, some of the good work was continued. I mean,

01:14:16.080 --> 01:14:20.960
[Guest 2]: Khayyam was there. Khayyam was one guy in every decade since 1950 to 1980, he would

01:14:20.960 --> 01:14:28.000
[Guest 2]: make good quality music. RD came in and he had, he contributed to some of this noise,

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:35.360
[Guest 2]: but he also continued to do good work. But I think, I mean, I don't like to take specific

01:14:35.360 --> 01:14:42.280
[Guest 2]: names, but for many of us, you know, Kalyanji, Anandji, Lakshmikant, Pyarelal, later parts,

01:14:42.280 --> 01:14:48.360
[Guest 2]: they were just creating, you know, just noisy stuff with no melody in it, occasional good

01:14:48.360 --> 01:14:55.560
[Guest 2]: songs. And by the time then we had Bachchan, then somewhere the whole thing had changed

01:14:55.560 --> 01:15:01.320
[Guest 2]: and what people were going to watch films for had changed.

01:15:01.320 --> 01:15:09.120
[Guest 2]: And I also think that, you know, as radio started becoming less important, because in

01:15:09.120 --> 01:15:14.520
[Guest 2]: radio, you would listen to the song, you were not having the benefit of the visualization.

01:15:14.520 --> 01:15:19.760
[Guest 2]: By 80s, then radio was also on terminal decline. Then it didn't matter then what you're presenting

01:15:19.760 --> 01:15:25.600
[Guest 2]: and how visually attractive that was. That's all that mattered, right? So, that also started

01:15:25.600 --> 01:15:33.600
[Guest 2]: changing. So, I just think that the primary reason is, you just had a good fortune of

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:37.920
[Guest 2]: 20 years of great people being together, the moment some of them dropped off, you would

01:15:37.920 --> 01:15:43.400
[Guest 2]: have had the eventual decline of that, that kind, that quality of music.

01:15:43.400 --> 01:15:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So, my second question regarding this is that, did you or do you have to be a particular

01:15:50.000 --> 01:15:55.040
[Amit Varma]: kind of person to appreciate that kind of music? Because, you know, you put someone

01:15:55.040 --> 01:16:00.120
[Amit Varma]: from a different environment and make him sit down and listen to say, Anil Biswas or

01:16:00.120 --> 01:16:04.360
[Amit Varma]: SD Burman or whatever, and it may not strike a chord at all, there may be absolutely nothing

01:16:04.360 --> 01:16:07.160
[Amit Varma]: happening there. I shouldn't say it may not strike a chord, of course, it will strike

01:16:07.160 --> 01:16:12.680
[Amit Varma]: a chord, but it won't strike a chord, strike a chord. And does, you know, the kind of art

01:16:12.680 --> 01:16:17.400
[Amit Varma]: which you consume, also shape the kind of person you are. And this could work sort of

01:16:17.400 --> 01:16:22.840
[Amit Varma]: in a, you know, in a virtuous cycle or a vicious cycle or whatever. I mean, those kind of tend

01:16:22.840 --> 01:16:26.200
[Amit Varma]: to imply that there's a judgment call about what is good and what is bad. But you know

01:16:26.200 --> 01:16:30.800
[Amit Varma]: what I mean? They could feed into each other. If you are a sort of a reflective kind of

01:16:30.800 --> 01:16:37.320
[Amit Varma]: person who likes quiet music, and you listen to that, and it just matches. And, you know,

01:16:37.320 --> 01:16:40.560
[Amit Varma]: you listen to more and more of that, and there is a market demand, and there's more and more

01:16:40.560 --> 01:16:45.200
[Amit Varma]: of that getting produced, and so on and so forth, you know, and equally, you could enter

01:16:45.200 --> 01:16:52.080
[Amit Varma]: a cycle of a different sort, you know, and what I sort of find delightful about the present,

01:16:52.080 --> 01:16:55.840
[Amit Varma]: the present era, maybe the last 10-15 years, not in terms of music, which I know nothing

01:16:55.840 --> 01:17:01.040
[Amit Varma]: about, but just in terms of creativity and art and all that, is that the means of production

01:17:01.040 --> 01:17:06.160
[Amit Varma]: is so democratized, that everyone has it, that there is a potential for niches forming,

01:17:06.160 --> 01:17:10.760
[Amit Varma]: which you would otherwise not even have assumed are there, you wouldn't know they exist. You

01:17:10.760 --> 01:17:14.240
[Amit Varma]: know, you can have a gardening podcast, where you would have thought, where is the market

01:17:14.240 --> 01:17:18.440
[Amit Varma]: for this? But it can be wildly popular, or at one point, people would have said, you

01:17:18.440 --> 01:17:21.600
[Amit Varma]: don't know who will listen to a five hour conversation, right? And I'm just thinking

01:17:21.600 --> 01:17:25.920
[Amit Varma]: in the one domain that I know about. But I would imagine the same is true for music,

01:17:25.920 --> 01:17:30.600
[Amit Varma]: that what you should have in this era, I would assume, is that the long tail is being catered

01:17:30.600 --> 01:17:36.200
[Amit Varma]: to that no matter what your tastes are, someone is making something which, you know, feeds

01:17:36.200 --> 01:17:41.800
[Amit Varma]: into that, and vice versa. But instead, a and this kind of bewildering that why should

01:17:41.800 --> 01:17:46.920
[Amit Varma]: a particular kind of music just vanish when it was clearly so popular and please so many

01:17:46.920 --> 01:17:52.560
[Amit Varma]: people in such a way that we still remember it fondly? And secondly, does it mean that

01:17:52.560 --> 01:17:59.480
[Amit Varma]: a particular kind of life a particular kind of terror of a particular kind of person is,

01:17:59.480 --> 01:18:04.000
[Guest 2]: you know, in a sense, not there anymore?

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:11.260
[Guest 2]: Maybe I'll take a crack at it. And you can add, see the I mean, there is a truth to this

01:18:11.260 --> 01:18:16.920
[Guest 2]: that you are as you have to be a certain type, or you become a certain type as you continue

01:18:16.920 --> 01:18:22.440
[Guest 2]: to appreciate this kind of music. I've seen this for this kind of Hindustani classical

01:18:22.440 --> 01:18:29.040
[Guest 2]: or even for ghazals. You know, you we tend to be of a certain kind. Although, even among

01:18:29.040 --> 01:18:34.600
[Guest 2]: us, you know, the sort of that, whatever you call it, the tyranny of small differences

01:18:34.600 --> 01:18:42.560
[Guest 2]: between us is often we are more judgmental about each other. I listen to better stuff.

01:18:42.560 --> 01:18:49.000
[Guest 2]: But it does happen. I mean, you do tend to become a certain type. And I think that's

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:59.640
[Guest 2]: true. The one thing in, at least in my case, like I say, I keep my ears open. And I trust

01:18:59.640 --> 01:19:06.600
[Guest 2]: my ears also reasonably well. So it is that, you know, then gradually, after I sort of

01:19:06.600 --> 01:19:13.080
[Guest 2]: got deeper into this, I kept my ear open to the idea that you could have good music even

01:19:13.080 --> 01:19:17.080
[Guest 2]: in Hollywood, because the first time when I heard, say, for instance, the sound of music,

01:19:17.080 --> 01:19:23.920
[Guest 2]: you know, I got that plastic pack with Rodgers and Hammerstein written. Pata bhi nahi tha

01:19:23.920 --> 01:19:30.240
[Guest 2]: yeh dono hai kaun, sound of music. First time I heard, barring that, Doremi, everything

01:19:30.240 --> 01:19:36.080
[Guest 2]: else seemed like noise to me. Yeh kya hai? Then after, you know, after many years, and

01:19:36.080 --> 01:19:43.480
[Guest 2]: then you heard everything, you know, the showboat, Learn and Lovell and all the other greats.

01:19:43.480 --> 01:19:48.160
[Guest 2]: And then, then wo kaan then open to them also. You realize ki yeh bhi ek music hai. In the

01:19:48.160 --> 01:19:55.600
[Guest 2]: same way, then I got into, for various reasons, into some of the opera stuff, right? I mean,

01:19:55.600 --> 01:20:02.560
[Guest 2]: some great, both Bikini and Verdi. I mean, if you don't, again, many people don't remember,

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:06.720
[Guest 2]: Doodarshan is to actually air the, some of the great operas as well. I mean, one of the

01:20:06.720 --> 01:20:13.360
[Guest 2]: great Saturday afternoons that I spent was actually watching Tosca on Doodarshan on DDI.

01:20:13.360 --> 01:20:18.080
[Guest 2]: Nobody remembers. Nobody even appreciates what Doodarshan was doing for us during those

01:20:18.080 --> 01:20:23.760
[Guest 2]: days. And I had no clue. It's just that for two days, they were showing ki Tosca aayega

01:20:23.760 --> 01:20:32.200
[Guest 2]: Saturday afternoon ko. Aayega toh humne baith jayenge yaar, humne kaunsa kaam hai. But then

01:20:32.200 --> 01:20:37.840
[Guest 2]: you started appreciating that as well. So if you keep your ears, and off late, I mean,

01:20:37.840 --> 01:20:45.040
[Guest 2]: again, just to go back to this point, at least in the last couple of years, maybe the lockdown

01:20:45.040 --> 01:20:49.120
[Guest 2]: and everything else gave me some time. I'm listening to all these people, yeah, this

01:20:49.120 --> 01:20:58.760
[Guest 2]: Dua Lipa and Olivia Rodrigo and, you know, the Lizzo, Billie Eilish, of course, but you

01:20:58.760 --> 01:21:06.360
[Guest 2]: know that this latest, this Lizzo song, which goes as about damn time, great music and whatever

01:21:06.360 --> 01:21:12.200
[Guest 2]: the latest Beyonce album Renaissance. Absolutely fantastic. I mean, mostly she's again gone

01:21:12.200 --> 01:21:18.600
[Guest 2]: back to dance. And you know, it's quite pumped up. It's not like those reflective, like lemonade

01:21:18.600 --> 01:21:29.640
[Guest 2]: stuff. So, I mean, I agree. I am, people often say that I'm of a certain melancholic disposition.

01:21:29.640 --> 01:21:42.520
[Unknown]: My son keeps asking me, what is this you listen to every time some lady is crying? You have

01:21:42.520 --> 01:21:49.400
[Guest 2]: to be careful about what you're saying. But yeah, that sort of people say, you keep listening

01:21:49.400 --> 01:21:53.880
[Guest 2]: to these stuff, you'll become, you'll become, you know, that kind of a person. But I've

01:21:53.880 --> 01:22:00.960
[Guest 2]: kept myself open and which is why sometimes I mean, not to sort of justify this. I mean,

01:22:00.960 --> 01:22:07.000
[Guest 2]: I'm not one of those who have concluded that Hindi cinema, Hindi film music of 40s, 50s

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:10.480
[Guest 2]: and 60s is great, because I like it. I mean, and then over a period of time, I've only

01:22:10.480 --> 01:22:15.160
[Guest 2]: gotten deeper into it. And now I'm, you know, extremist about it. And I don't listen to

01:22:15.160 --> 01:22:21.160
[Guest 2]: anybody else, you know, saying anything else is better. And I have, you know, sampled reasonably

01:22:21.160 --> 01:22:27.240
[Guest 2]: well, some of the other stuff. And I like a lot of that. I listened to a lot of that.

01:22:27.240 --> 01:22:31.000
[Guest 2]: And after having done all of that, I still come back to this, because this is where I

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:38.040
[Guest 2]: find the most comfort. This is where my heart is. So, so yes, I would say that it's not

01:22:38.040 --> 01:22:43.000
[Guest 2]: easy to, you become a person and you continue to be that person. It's very difficult to

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:50.760
[Guest 2]: switch tracks. But to the extent that I've appreciated that there is possibility that

01:22:50.760 --> 01:22:55.760
[Guest 2]: you might discover something better. I have gone out and tried that. And in some ways,

01:22:55.760 --> 01:23:00.080
[Guest 2]: in small little ways, I think I've succeeded as well. I mean, I like a few other genres

01:23:00.080 --> 01:23:01.080
[Guest 2]: of music as well.

01:23:01.080 --> 01:23:06.000
[Guest 1]: I think what you said there also reminded me of that controversy about the film Ae Dil

01:23:06.000 --> 01:23:10.040
[Guest 1]: Hai Mushkil, where the Anushka character in the film at one point say something about

01:23:10.040 --> 01:23:14.160
[Guest 1]: Muhammad Rafi itne boring gaane gaate hai or whatever. And then that, of course, led

01:23:14.160 --> 01:23:19.920
[Guest 1]: to a lot of outrage from from Rafi fans and and so on, because there was that confusion

01:23:19.920 --> 01:23:24.200
[Guest 1]: of, you know, of what the film is saying, as opposed to what a character in the film

01:23:24.200 --> 01:23:29.880
[Guest 1]: is saying, which is a very standard thing. But you know, everything you said, you know,

01:23:29.880 --> 01:23:36.800
[Guest 1]: for me, I just think while there probably is such a thing as a certain type of music

01:23:36.800 --> 01:23:42.080
[Guest 1]: or a certain type of film that you're naturally drawn to, depending on things like your early

01:23:42.080 --> 01:23:48.520
[Guest 1]: conditioning, the things that you're exposed to early on, and so on. Also, but I think

01:23:48.520 --> 01:23:54.360
[Guest 1]: to a great degree, this is also just a function of how much time you have, and how much inclination

01:23:54.360 --> 01:23:58.280
[Guest 1]: or willingness you have to engage with many different things and to begin that process

01:23:58.280 --> 01:24:03.080
[Guest 1]: of discovering something new, something that might lie outside your comfort zone, and then

01:24:03.080 --> 01:24:07.600
[Guest 1]: going with it for a while until it, you know, it sort of, you know, it burrows into your

01:24:07.600 --> 01:24:12.800
[Guest 1]: ears or whatever. So speaking for myself, I've, maybe this is just a function of the

01:24:12.800 --> 01:24:19.600
[Guest 1]: fact that I've spent a disproportionately large amount of my time on movies, and on

01:24:19.600 --> 01:24:25.840
[Guest 1]: cultural stuff, on movies, books, music, compared to a lot of other people. So I tend to have

01:24:25.840 --> 01:24:30.160
[Guest 1]: very, very diverse tastes when it comes to music, you know, if my personal playlist will

01:24:30.160 --> 01:24:35.360
[Guest 1]: have old Hindi film songs from the 40s, 50s, 60s, you know, these beautiful numbers, I

01:24:35.360 --> 01:24:43.840
[Guest 1]: was listening to Aarpaar songs on the way here a while earlier, Geeta Dutt and songs

01:24:43.840 --> 01:24:47.320
[Guest 1]: like that. But at the same time, I will also have Eminem, or I'll also have some heavy

01:24:47.320 --> 01:24:53.920
[Guest 1]: metal, which is stuff that, you know, when I was in my mid teens, you know, 15, 16, or

01:24:53.920 --> 01:24:58.200
[Guest 1]: so on, I started really listening to contemporary Western music for the first time, became a

01:24:58.200 --> 01:25:03.440
[Guest 1]: big fan of all sorts of things, from the Pet Shop Boys to Guns N' Roses, you know, with

01:25:03.440 --> 01:25:07.920
[Guest 1]: U2 and R.E.M. in between and Stone Temple Pilots, everything, while at the same time

01:25:07.920 --> 01:25:13.640
[Guest 1]: retaining my basic love for old Hindi film music as well. I think it's largely, and you

01:25:13.640 --> 01:25:19.560
[Guest 1]: actually hinted at this also in what you were saying, Subrat, it's a function of how much

01:25:19.560 --> 01:25:25.240
[Guest 1]: time you have for these things, and how much you're willing to just explore different types

01:25:25.240 --> 01:25:30.800
[Guest 1]: of things. And then chances are, you will find something that you like in different

01:25:30.800 --> 01:25:35.840
[Guest 1]: genres and different modes. Also, one other thing that, you know, since you raised the

01:25:35.840 --> 01:25:41.240
[Guest 1]: subject, Amit, one thing I've always been a bit curious about, I haven't really quite

01:25:41.240 --> 01:25:47.480
[Guest 1]: figured it out for myself yet, is that when it comes to the songs in the two main languages

01:25:47.480 --> 01:25:52.840
[Guest 1]: that I know, Hindi and English, it's a strange thing. But when I first started listening

01:25:52.840 --> 01:26:00.960
[Guest 1]: to pop and rock in English, not just with people like Dylan or Kohan, people who are

01:26:00.960 --> 01:26:06.800
[Guest 1]: known for their songwriting, for the lyric writing, but even with bands like R.E.M, U2,

01:26:06.800 --> 01:26:14.160
[Guest 1]: etc. For some reason, once a song really embedded itself into my head, I knew the lyrics, I

01:26:14.160 --> 01:26:20.800
[Guest 1]: just learned the lyrics very quickly. So even today, there are songs, entire albums by some

01:26:20.800 --> 01:26:25.760
[Guest 1]: of my favourite artists who I first heard 30-35 years ago, and I just remember the whole

01:26:25.760 --> 01:26:30.000
[Guest 1]: thing, I remember all the words. But with Hindi film music, and I know there are a few

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:37.840
[Guest 1]: others like me, I've always engaged with songs at the level of music, primarily. And

01:26:37.840 --> 01:26:43.040
[Guest 1]: very often, I just haven't registered the lyrics of even iconic songs, unless there's

01:26:43.040 --> 01:26:46.800
[Guest 1]: something really simple and straightforward, like Mera Jhoota Hai Japani or something like

01:26:46.800 --> 01:26:53.080
[Guest 1]: that. So it's so relatively late in life that I've really started appreciating the nuances

01:26:53.080 --> 01:26:59.600
[Guest 1]: between a Sahir Ludhianvi or a Majrooh Sultanpuri as lyricists. It's always been engagement

01:26:59.600 --> 01:27:04.520
[Guest 1]: at the level of music. So that there could be something in the brain that just sort of

01:27:04.520 --> 01:27:10.240
[Guest 1]: prioritises certain things depending on what language you're listening to. I think that's

01:27:10.240 --> 01:27:11.800
[Guest 2]: something to think about as well.

01:27:11.800 --> 01:27:18.400
[Guest 2]: In my case, it's just the opposite. I mean, for me, the Hindi film songs is first about

01:27:18.400 --> 01:27:25.360
[Guest 2]: the lyrics. That's all I remember. I mean, in the sense that's really the core of what

01:27:25.360 --> 01:27:31.760
[Guest 2]: gets me into the song. And that's again an obsession, just hearing it so many times.

01:27:31.760 --> 01:27:37.320
[Guest 2]: I almost, I mean, there are a few of us, lots of us now actually, it's almost like you can

01:27:37.320 --> 01:27:44.240
[Guest 2]: play any song at any time and we can just take the lyrics and do that. I mean, some

01:27:44.240 --> 01:27:51.120
[Guest 2]: of the workplaces that I've been, I have this bit of a, you know, fun contest that goes

01:27:51.120 --> 01:27:59.200
[Guest 2]: on that they can play 100 songs, one after the other. And I can tell them the movie,

01:27:59.200 --> 01:28:02.760
[Guest 2]: the director, the music director, lyricist that I can sing the entire song, at least

01:28:02.760 --> 01:28:07.920
[Guest 2]: the lyrics. So, so yeah, so the lyrics are my point of entry. But you're right, there

01:28:07.920 --> 01:28:10.520
[Guest 2]: is something maybe about the brain and how we process it.

01:28:10.520 --> 01:28:15.680
[Guest 1]: So I've been scolded a lot by poet friends and by friends who are themselves lyricists

01:28:15.680 --> 01:28:22.440
[Guest 1]: or who are very attached to the words of the great lyricists that we've had in Hindi cinema,

01:28:22.440 --> 01:28:28.600
[Guest 1]: the fans of Sahir or someone else or Kefi Kefi or whoever saying, how can you not, you

01:28:28.600 --> 01:28:32.840
[Guest 1]: know, not engage with the song at that level? How can you just sort of have the tune of

01:28:32.840 --> 01:28:37.840
[Guest 1]: the song in your head and, and not really be engaging with the words. But I think it's,

01:28:37.840 --> 01:28:39.080
[Guest 1]: it works that way for some people.

01:28:39.080 --> 01:28:44.680
[Guest 2]: Yeah, in some of them, like for instance, I mean, if you see Do Bhi Ghazmeen, the fact

01:28:44.680 --> 01:28:52.400
[Guest 2]: that now Balraj Sahni has to leave the village and go to the city, while he's given his,

01:28:52.400 --> 01:28:58.720
[Guest 2]: his land is now with the, with the landlord. And as he's walking, you get the song, you

01:28:58.720 --> 01:29:05.480
[Guest 2]: know, Apni Kahani Chhod Ja, Kuch Toh Nishani Chhod Ja, Kaun Kahe, Kis Roj, Fir Tu Aay

01:29:05.480 --> 01:29:10.400
[Guest 2]: Na Aay. I mean, if you listen to the lyrics, and the fact that he's now walking and he's

01:29:10.400 --> 01:29:16.920
[Guest 2]: watching the field for the last time, that whole experience just changes. I mean, you

01:29:16.920 --> 01:29:24.040
[Guest 2]: know, you get goosebumps. I mean, that just, Bimal Roy just got everything together. That's

01:29:24.040 --> 01:29:31.560
[Guest 2]: a very well shot. He's, and Balraj Sahni is just a fantastic actor. So sometimes, and

01:29:31.560 --> 01:29:36.520
[Guest 2]: I realized that was without this lyrics, the scene would have been, I mean, would have

01:29:36.520 --> 01:29:43.600
[Guest 2]: been nothing and just, and Shailendra just gets in many films that, you know, just the

01:29:43.600 --> 01:29:48.560
[Guest 2]: right amount of pathos with the right kind of words, absolutely spot on. I mean, I mean,

01:29:48.560 --> 01:29:54.880
[Guest 2]: I can just go on with about 50 songs of Shailendra. Because more than say, Sahir and others who

01:29:54.880 --> 01:29:59.640
[Guest 2]: were great poets, Shailendra was just born to be a Hindi film lyricist. I mean, he's

01:29:59.640 --> 01:30:04.800
[Guest 2]: of course written some of the great poems as well. He was that whole communist, you

01:30:04.800 --> 01:30:12.200
[Guest 2]: know, song, that's his. But he just knew how to write for Hindi films. And you know, some

01:30:12.200 --> 01:30:16.920
[Guest 2]: of those lyrics just elevate the experience. When you hear it, you know what he's saying.

01:30:16.920 --> 01:30:21.160
[Guest 2]: And then, you know, then the story and everything just falls in place together.

01:30:21.160 --> 01:30:27.120
[Guest 1]: So, Amit, Dharti Ke Pukar Ke is, of course, also an absolute favorite song of one of your

01:30:27.120 --> 01:30:32.800
[Guest 1]: recent guests, Varun, Varun Grover. And they used it to great effect in the opening scene

01:30:32.800 --> 01:30:38.200
[Guest 1]: of Sacred Games episode one. You know, in a completely different context, you know,

01:30:38.200 --> 01:30:42.440
[Guest 1]: the Ganesh Ka Gai Tonde character played by Nawazuddin Siddiqui. And, you know, and Dharti

01:30:42.440 --> 01:30:47.160
[Guest 1]: Ke Pukar Ke is being used there. And it just, you've taken something that that's so much

01:30:47.160 --> 01:30:53.480
[Guest 1]: of, of its time, you know, belongs to the Do Bhi Ka Zameen situation as Subrat was saying,

01:30:53.480 --> 01:30:58.640
[Guest 1]: but you've transposed it here to a completely different, you know, aesthetic and a mode

01:30:58.640 --> 01:31:00.920
[Guest 1]: of storytelling. And it just works there as well.

01:31:00.920 --> 01:31:05.400
[Amit Varma]: Varun, I mean, he's a tremendous artist. I think someone who has imbibed the best of

01:31:05.400 --> 01:31:10.000
[Amit Varma]: the past and is just doing this, you know, bringing it into the work that he does now,

01:31:10.000 --> 01:31:13.680
[Amit Varma]: which is influenced by so many things. So I confess, I had no idea of this. And we didn't

01:31:13.680 --> 01:31:18.880
[Amit Varma]: discuss this. But, you know, personally, where I come from, I'm much closer in terms of that

01:31:18.880 --> 01:31:24.440
[Amit Varma]: music versus lyrics sing to where Jai is, where it's always a music, it's always a vibe

01:31:24.440 --> 01:31:28.120
[Amit Varma]: with exceptions. And the exceptions being the singer songwriters like Springsteen and

01:31:28.120 --> 01:31:32.900
[Amit Varma]: Dylan where, you know, you get into them for a specific reason. And therefore, you kind

01:31:32.900 --> 01:31:37.640
[Amit Varma]: of remember the word. But most of the time, my experience with music is essentially of

01:31:37.640 --> 01:31:42.680
[Amit Varma]: not only not knowing the words, but often misunderstanding them. So like, my catalog

01:31:42.680 --> 01:31:47.440
[Amit Varma]: of memories is full of what is called Mondegreens. Like the recent one, which I just discovered

01:31:47.440 --> 01:31:52.600
[Amit Varma]: yesterday that I had sort of misremembered, it was a BG song tragedy. I always thought

01:31:52.600 --> 01:31:58.160
[Amit Varma]: the lyrics were tragedy. It's a Vulcan sonic tragedy. And obviously, that's not the not

01:31:58.160 --> 01:32:02.880
[Amit Varma]: what it is. I don't even know what it is forgotten already. But in my mind has always been that

01:32:02.880 --> 01:32:08.600
[Amit Varma]: and I'm content with it being that, because I don't need anything more than that. For,

01:32:08.600 --> 01:32:11.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, to enjoy the song, though I don't even like the song. I mean, it's just one

01:32:11.360 --> 01:32:12.360
[Amit Varma]: random example.

01:32:12.360 --> 01:32:19.360
[Guest 2]: The great Hindi film Mondegreen is of course, from Kurbani, Anjaan song. Aap jaisa koi mere

01:32:19.360 --> 01:32:23.880
[Guest 2]: zindagi mein aaye toh baap ban jaye.

01:32:23.880 --> 01:32:30.440
[Guest 1]: I wasn't aware of that one. But but I know that there are some people, some highly Anglicized

01:32:30.440 --> 01:32:35.920
[Guest 1]: people of my generation who, who listened to Ek Akela Shehar Mein and wondered why Amol

01:32:35.920 --> 01:32:38.720
[Amit Varma]: Palekar was always looking for Sabudana.

01:32:38.720 --> 01:32:46.600
[Amit Varma]: That's me. That's me. That's me. Right. Yeah, exactly. So here's my next question. And it

01:32:46.600 --> 01:32:51.400
[Amit Varma]: strikes at what both of you just mentioned, like Subrat, you mentioned about Tosca. Tosca

01:32:51.400 --> 01:32:56.120
[Amit Varma]: aaya hum toh kuch nahi kar rahe hain, batke dekhenge. And you spoke about how getting

01:32:56.120 --> 01:33:00.600
[Amit Varma]: into something requires you're devoting the time to get into it. You can't just listen

01:33:00.600 --> 01:33:05.160
[Amit Varma]: to something casually or whatever you actually, there's an investment you're making of yourself.

01:33:05.160 --> 01:33:10.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, my thought is and I remember having this argument with my dad back in the 90s, where

01:33:10.640 --> 01:33:15.080
[Amit Varma]: he felt that so many channels wasn't such a great thing, like, which is, you know, the

01:33:15.080 --> 01:33:20.200
[Amit Varma]: very old Fabian socialist point of view, but my scene was ki yaar choice aagaya hai, you

01:33:20.200 --> 01:33:25.840
[Amit Varma]: know, abhi like star movies had just come. Star movies was heaven boss. Poora din movies

01:33:25.840 --> 01:33:28.840
[Amit Varma]: hote the usmein humein, you know, where would we get to watch that?

01:33:28.840 --> 01:33:34.320
[Amit Varma]: In 94-95, they had that 100 years of cinema thing, which went on for weeks. And you just

01:33:34.320 --> 01:33:40.040
[Amit Varma]: saw so much stuff. Pagla gaye, khushi se baukla gaye. I remember that. Yeah. So and my father's

01:33:40.040 --> 01:33:44.960
[Amit Varma]: sort of romantic point was ki nahi ek channel jab tha, at least you could look forward to

01:33:44.960 --> 01:33:49.280
[Amit Varma]: things you knew they were there. Today, 30-40 years later, I kind of understand where that's

01:33:49.280 --> 01:33:54.760
[Amit Varma]: coming from, if I don't agree with it completely. In the sense ki Tosca dikhaya, bachche hain

01:33:54.760 --> 01:33:57.640
[Amit Varma]: jinn ke baas kuch nahi hai, they're sitting and watching Tosca, they're taking it in.

01:33:57.640 --> 01:34:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Today, what you have is number one, as Jonathan Haidt has pointed out, most of the content

01:34:03.000 --> 01:34:07.280
[Amit Varma]: we are consuming was produced in the last three days, right? We're not going any further

01:34:07.280 --> 01:34:13.000
[Amit Varma]: back than that. And if I may add to that, we are just scrolling or swiping. Everything

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:18.200
[Amit Varma]: is scroll, swipe, scroll, swipe, aage chalo, peeche chalo. It's, you know, we are having,

01:34:18.200 --> 01:34:26.080
[Amit Varma]: we are living in a world of 15 second experiences. And that kind of immersive thing, where you're

01:34:26.080 --> 01:34:30.640
[Amit Varma]: not scrolling, you're not swiping, you're just sitting, you're taking something in,

01:34:30.640 --> 01:34:33.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, even if it's a three hour Amar Akbar Anthony, you're just sitting there for the

01:34:33.960 --> 01:34:39.200
[Amit Varma]: whole experience. You know, I don't mean ki aapko baith ke Tarkovsky dekhna hai. But,

01:34:39.200 --> 01:34:43.920
[Amit Varma]: and I think that that's fundamental, because everything that you consume in terms of art

01:34:43.920 --> 01:34:49.480
[Amit Varma]: is going to shape you, right? So if all the time I'm watching 15 second things, you know,

01:34:49.480 --> 01:34:55.520
[Amit Varma]: the rhythm of my thinking, just, you know, it's shallow, I'm not really taking anything

01:34:55.520 --> 01:35:01.000
[Amit Varma]: in, the rabbit holes I enter will also be will have this staccato rhythm to them. Ki

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:05.480
[Amit Varma]: acha theek hai, yeh accha laga, yeh pedia dekha, yeh kya, wo kya, wo kya, but that immersion

01:35:05.480 --> 01:35:10.320
[Amit Varma]: is kind of not there. So is this something you've observed? Does it change society in

01:35:10.320 --> 01:35:14.720
[Amit Varma]: a fundamental way when it happens? Or would you say that this is not happening to everybody

01:35:14.720 --> 01:35:19.680
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, there were enough sort of people back then, there were people who didn't

01:35:19.680 --> 01:35:23.440
[Amit Varma]: watch anything or read anything, you know, toh matlab utna farak nahi parta hai. The

01:35:23.440 --> 01:35:26.640
[Amit Varma]: handful of people who are still going to be drawn to fine art are still going to be drawn

01:35:26.640 --> 01:35:31.040
[Amit Varma]: to art, you know, pompous terms, but so what's your sense of this?

01:35:31.040 --> 01:35:35.640
[Guest 1]: I don't know, at risk of sounding like a really conservative old fogie or whatever, I think,

01:35:35.640 --> 01:35:40.160
[Guest 1]: you know, that there is a clearly a problem of attention deficit, which is something I'm

01:35:40.160 --> 01:35:43.600
[Guest 1]: not saying, not necessarily saying this from a position of judgment, I'd like to think

01:35:43.600 --> 01:35:47.560
[Guest 1]: of myself as someone who immerses in different things, you know, what I was saying earlier

01:35:47.560 --> 01:35:53.280
[Guest 1]: about even today, it's very rare for me to watch, you know, even on a day where I'm relatively

01:35:53.280 --> 01:35:58.920
[Guest 1]: free, it's very rare for me to watch more than one film in a day. Because I need that

01:35:58.920 --> 01:36:03.080
[Guest 1]: time to, you know, if you're watching a 90 minute film or a two hour film to then reflect,

01:36:03.080 --> 01:36:08.360
[Guest 1]: think about it. And I try to watch it at one go, minimum distractions, darkened room, even

01:36:08.360 --> 01:36:16.840
[Guest 1]: if I'm just watching it on my laptop or whatever. But even so, I know that even I 70-80% of

01:36:16.840 --> 01:36:21.200
[Guest 1]: the time do find myself distracted by something else, you know, and I won't be able to sort

01:36:21.200 --> 01:36:25.680
[Guest 1]: of resist pausing the film for a while and checking something, you know, I mean, I might

01:36:25.680 --> 01:36:29.960
[Guest 1]: just go to the film's Wikipedia page to check something that I do to follow. And then that

01:36:29.960 --> 01:36:34.000
[Guest 1]: might lead me to meet me to another rabbit hole, because Gmail happens to be open. And

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:40.400
[Guest 1]: there's one unread mail there and you go there. That happens even to someone like me, to whom

01:36:40.400 --> 01:36:46.680
[Guest 1]: immersion comes quite easily and who doesn't normally get sucked into too many different

01:36:46.680 --> 01:36:52.520
[Guest 1]: things. So I can imagine that it does on some level, it is affecting the brains of many

01:36:52.520 --> 01:36:57.200
[Guest 1]: of us, and definitely younger people who have only ever known this sort of life who, you

01:36:57.200 --> 01:37:02.920
[Guest 1]: know, who are just inundated with information all the time, information, the binging culture

01:37:02.920 --> 01:37:07.120
[Guest 1]: that we talk about, you know, the, I'm sure it's not great for the for the eyes as well

01:37:07.120 --> 01:37:10.540
[Guest 1]: or for the for the ears, if you're listening to listening to things or watching things

01:37:10.540 --> 01:37:17.520
[Guest 1]: with with your phones all the time. That's also the physiological side to it. It's and

01:37:17.520 --> 01:37:21.960
[Guest 1]: I'm sure Shoaib does on the whole, I don't want to make very sweeping statements, but

01:37:21.960 --> 01:37:27.800
[Guest 1]: on the whole, it must be affecting people's attention spans. I think it is.

01:37:27.800 --> 01:37:34.160
[Guest 2]: See, I mean, again, my system one, one response is what Jai has mentioned, I feel that way.

01:37:34.160 --> 01:37:41.600
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's all around us. I'm 46. Like I said, I just turned 46. It feels like, they're

01:37:41.600 --> 01:37:47.000
[Guest 2]: missing out on so many things, right? You know, just sit and watch 2001 Space Odyssey

01:37:47.000 --> 01:37:53.920
[Guest 2]: and wait for 30 minutes till the first word is spoken. Listen to Strauss, see what is

01:37:53.920 --> 01:37:59.360
[Guest 2]: happening. Look at what Kubrick is doing. But then you know that there is also this

01:37:59.360 --> 01:38:06.080
[Guest 2]: system to thinking about this, which is how was Mirza Ghalib, for instance, received in

01:38:06.080 --> 01:38:13.920
[Guest 2]: his what we might consider his, you know, peak? I don't think I mean, I think the narcissists

01:38:13.920 --> 01:38:20.120
[Guest 2]: and the purists of his time, including, you know, the ones in the darbar and, you know,

01:38:20.120 --> 01:38:28.960
[Guest 2]: those of us who watched the great television serial Mirza Ghalib by Gulzar in the in the

01:38:28.960 --> 01:38:35.640
[Guest 2]: late 80s. He wasn't necessarily the, you know, the court poet or something. He was there

01:38:35.640 --> 01:38:39.920
[Guest 2]: and thereabouts, but it was Zouk and you know, then there was Meerta Ki Mir and so on and

01:38:39.920 --> 01:38:45.280
[Guest 2]: so forth. Ghalib was often considered to be a bit of a people's poet, a bit of someone

01:38:45.280 --> 01:38:51.600
[Guest 2]: who was pandering to popular taste. And if you recollect the series, there, you know,

01:38:51.600 --> 01:38:57.320
[Guest 2]: there was Neena Gupta who played, you know, Kotesan Nashne Wali and she would often get

01:38:57.320 --> 01:39:02.720
[Guest 2]: in Radhi paper, some of Ghalib's songs, not often, she got a few times and then she would

01:39:02.720 --> 01:39:08.400
[Guest 2]: be singing and Ghalib himself hears that Tere Wade Pe Jiye Toh Yeh Jaan Jhoot Jana Ki Khushi

01:39:08.400 --> 01:39:16.360
[Guest 2]: Se Jee Na Paate Toh Yeh Aitbaar Hota. You know, the fact that it went to those people

01:39:16.360 --> 01:39:21.280
[Guest 2]: and they sort of sang it and therefore it sort of continued and perpetuated and hundred

01:39:21.280 --> 01:39:26.360
[Guest 2]: years later, you know, Ghalib is high art, high culture, while it might not have been

01:39:26.360 --> 01:39:32.520
[Guest 2]: during that point in time. So, some of this, you know, I would say that one has to look

01:39:32.520 --> 01:39:37.360
[Guest 2]: at history and pause and say that it's maybe we should reserve our judgment. Who knows

01:39:37.360 --> 01:39:43.360
[Guest 2]: that, you know, this two minute thing is possibly high art. I mean, for instance, I mean, we

01:39:43.360 --> 01:39:48.920
[Guest 2]: can go back into just the painting stuff, right? I mean, Lichtenstein, you know, he

01:39:48.920 --> 01:39:56.160
[Guest 2]: did the drowning girl, that very famous, almost comic book like art. I mean, I'm sure nobody

01:39:56.160 --> 01:40:00.680
[Guest 2]: thought that to be anything great at that point in time. I mean, you know, now looking

01:40:00.680 --> 01:40:06.680
[Guest 2]: back is there a Kya Kiya Hai or even Jackson Pollock and, you know, all these abstract

01:40:06.680 --> 01:40:13.120
[Guest 2]: expressionist or, you know, Rene Magritte and, you know, all those, you know, crazy

01:40:13.120 --> 01:40:19.040
[Guest 2]: stuff, Golconda and, you know, they were all interesting stuff. But, you know, people would

01:40:19.040 --> 01:40:24.380
[Guest 2]: possibly compare that and say that even impressionism and post impressionist stuff was better than

01:40:24.380 --> 01:40:28.600
[Guest 2]: what are you putting up now, right? And then if you go back another 30 years, people were

01:40:28.600 --> 01:40:35.440
[Guest 2]: asking, Picasso, Kar Kya Rahe Ho? Yeh Kya Hai? Why is everything appearing like a cube?

01:40:35.440 --> 01:40:40.520
[Guest 2]: And then, you know, go to impressionism and even when impressionism was happening, there

01:40:40.520 --> 01:40:46.160
[Guest 2]: was then in UK, this Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood who said that, listen, all these guys have

01:40:46.160 --> 01:40:52.360
[Guest 2]: gone crazy. Let's go back, you know, completely. So, the likes of Rossetti and others, they

01:40:52.360 --> 01:40:56.480
[Guest 2]: just, you know, went all the way back and, you know, so they would paint Ophelia or something

01:40:56.480 --> 01:41:02.440
[Guest 2]: like that, which is very Pre-Raphaelite. So, they almost leaped back 300 years. So, sometimes

01:41:02.440 --> 01:41:10.160
[Guest 2]: I'm like, you know, history should teach us ki hota rahata hai yaar, istare ka. And maybe

01:41:10.160 --> 01:41:16.040
[Guest 2]: 30 years later, you might find this very different and this might be high art. And therefore,

01:41:16.040 --> 01:41:21.280
[Guest 2]: one has to be somewhat, I mean, obviously, in the present, you crib about it, but who

01:41:21.280 --> 01:41:23.800
[Guest 2]: knows later, how will people see this? I mean,

01:41:23.800 --> 01:41:31.040
[Guest 1]: See, my point isn't so much that a two minute thing can't be good art. What I was really

01:41:31.040 --> 01:41:35.840
[Guest 1]: talking about was more about how much there is competing for people's attention right

01:41:35.840 --> 01:41:43.200
[Guest 1]: now and how in that process, you know, even TikTok can be good art. And I mean, I think

01:41:43.200 --> 01:41:50.920
[Guest 1]: you've pointed that out as well in things you've written or spoken about. But if there's

01:41:50.920 --> 01:41:57.680
[Guest 1]: so much available competing for people's attention and people then don't approach these things

01:41:57.680 --> 01:42:03.800
[Guest 1]: with some discernment, with some regard for the limits of their own mind, what they can

01:42:03.800 --> 01:42:07.960
[Guest 1]: process in a single day, then of course, you know, you just have stuff washing over you

01:42:07.960 --> 01:42:14.040
[Guest 1]: all the time. And I think this also sort of this inevitably will lead to situations where

01:42:14.040 --> 01:42:21.480
[Guest 1]: people are not really, where people are dabbling, you know, with, I see this a lot in my spheres

01:42:21.480 --> 01:42:28.280
[Guest 1]: of work, book reviewers, reading novels or whatever, and writing reviews. And you can

01:42:28.280 --> 01:42:32.120
[Guest 1]: tell that the engagement has been very superficial. It's just been, you know, there hasn't been

01:42:32.120 --> 01:42:38.320
[Guest 1]: a real sort of effort to sort of get into it. It's skimming, skimming more than anything

01:42:38.320 --> 01:42:42.960
[Guest 1]: else to sort of just get the easy takeaway from the thing, from what might actually be

01:42:42.960 --> 01:42:46.880
[Guest 1]: quite a complex, nuanced work, but you're looking for the takeaway, you're looking for

01:42:46.880 --> 01:42:50.800
[Guest 1]: a single takeaway. That happens with films, a lot of cultural criticism these days, which

01:42:50.800 --> 01:42:56.880
[Guest 1]: we've talked about elsewhere, where, you know, you have, you have criticism that's centred

01:42:56.880 --> 01:43:04.160
[Guest 1]: on ideology, or very often on on blinkered ideology, is just sort of is centred on looking

01:43:04.160 --> 01:43:10.360
[Guest 1]: at a film and saying, what is the message? What is the filmmaker? What is the filmmaker's

01:43:10.360 --> 01:43:18.760
[Guest 1]: own politics? What is he trying to say? What does this character represent? Is he supporting

01:43:18.760 --> 01:43:23.480
[Guest 1]: this character in the film? Or is he sort of judging the character? And, you know, and

01:43:23.480 --> 01:43:28.920
[Guest 1]: these questions are presented as if they will always have very easy, straightforward answers,

01:43:28.920 --> 01:43:33.160
[Guest 1]: which they very often won't, with a good film, with a good complex film, they won't have

01:43:33.160 --> 01:43:38.040
[Guest 1]: those answers. And I think that that also is very often a function of just, you know,

01:43:38.040 --> 01:43:41.560
[Guest 1]: we have very finite time to, you know, we just need to sort of watch this film, not

01:43:41.560 --> 01:43:46.620
[Guest 1]: think about it too much. We just sort of, you know, just looking for that one easy takeaway

01:43:46.620 --> 01:43:50.520
[Guest 1]: from it. I think that some of that is happening a lot.

01:43:50.520 --> 01:43:54.760
[Amit Varma]: I think part of that, that tendency is that we live in the age of the Ghoja moment, where

01:43:54.760 --> 01:43:59.500
[Amit Varma]: you're looking for someone, something to pass judgment on. Because then if you, the act

01:43:59.500 --> 01:44:03.280
[Amit Varma]: of passing judgment on something means you're placing yourself above it, you're elevating

01:44:03.280 --> 01:44:09.160
[Amit Varma]: yourself, whether in terms of aesthetics or morality or whatever. And it's a toxic tendency.

01:44:09.160 --> 01:44:12.640
[Amit Varma]: And I agree there with you. And we'll talk about politics and art later. But I'll just

01:44:12.640 --> 01:44:18.280
[Amit Varma]: agree with both of you here, in the sense that, yeah, I mean, you know, I briefly taught

01:44:18.280 --> 01:44:23.400
[Amit Varma]: a course, TikTok and Indian society, and the very month that it was banned. But I thought

01:44:23.400 --> 01:44:28.200
[Amit Varma]: there was some tremendous art happening there. A lot of great expression from people who

01:44:28.200 --> 01:44:34.000
[Amit Varma]: don't otherwise have platforms, and who don't otherwise see art from people like themselves.

01:44:34.000 --> 01:44:37.920
[Amit Varma]: And suddenly, you just have to turn a phone at yourself and make something. And initially,

01:44:37.920 --> 01:44:41.880
[Amit Varma]: you're doing lip syncs and memes and all of that. But later, it was going beyond that.

01:44:41.880 --> 01:44:46.600
[Amit Varma]: It blew my mind. It just like, made me so happy to kind of see that happening. At the

01:44:46.600 --> 01:44:51.840
[Amit Varma]: same time, Subrata, your point is great also that, you know, one, of course, how we, you

01:44:51.840 --> 01:44:57.160
[Amit Varma]: know, if you go through history, one should learn not to place things on a hierarchy and

01:44:57.160 --> 01:45:01.840
[Amit Varma]: say, this is good, this is bad. But also, I don't think attention spans are necessarily

01:45:01.840 --> 01:45:07.640
[Amit Varma]: declining as you know, we're having this conversation, people listen to the show, listen to the podcast

01:45:07.640 --> 01:45:11.920
[Amit Varma]: and you, you know, one of you, I think Jay, you spoke about binging as well. And binging

01:45:11.920 --> 01:45:16.080
[Amit Varma]: also indicates that I mean, I do see the addictive nature of binging and you're just watching

01:45:16.080 --> 01:45:20.460
[Amit Varma]: mindlessly through the night. But at the same time, it shows that people have that kind

01:45:20.460 --> 01:45:26.400
[Amit Varma]: of stamina to really get into a story and just really get into it, right. And the fact

01:45:26.400 --> 01:45:32.320
[Amit Varma]: that somebody today can binge something like The Wire or something like Decalogue is delightful

01:45:32.320 --> 01:45:38.320
[Amit Varma]: to me. And that brings me to my next question about a change in form itself. Like if you

01:45:38.320 --> 01:45:43.440
[Amit Varma]: look at the history of cinema, all films are basically short stories. If you look at the

01:45:43.440 --> 01:45:52.120
[Amit Varma]: literature definition of it, there's a certain amount of depth you can get and not much more

01:45:52.120 --> 01:45:58.520
[Amit Varma]: than that, and so on and so forth. Whereas, with the modern web series or OTT content,

01:45:58.520 --> 01:46:02.640
[Amit Varma]: you can stretch out like a novel. Like what I loved about The Wire also was how slowly

01:46:02.640 --> 01:46:08.240
[Amit Varma]: it unfolded, how there wasn't one or two or three major protagonists, where there were

01:46:08.240 --> 01:46:13.960
[Amit Varma]: 14, 15, 20 people who were painted with such depth that you could care for them and remember

01:46:13.960 --> 01:46:18.440
[Amit Varma]: those characters 20 years after the show was over, you know, it's almost that long since

01:46:18.440 --> 01:46:25.080
[Amit Varma]: I saw some of the things I remember. And I think that's a beautiful progression in what

01:46:25.080 --> 01:46:30.240
[Amit Varma]: is possible, as much as the two minute form is possible, the 30 second form is possible,

01:46:30.240 --> 01:46:37.120
[Amit Varma]: and all of that is not necessarily a bad thing. At the same time, now, we can stretch out,

01:46:37.120 --> 01:46:44.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, earlier it felt like an hour long interview is a deep dive. Today, it feels

01:46:44.040 --> 01:46:50.160
[Amit Varma]: like micro content to me, at least as a consumer. Now we can stretch out. Now we can bring that

01:46:50.160 --> 01:46:55.800
[Amit Varma]: herav into our viewing experience. And in a sense, what contradicts a question I ask

01:46:55.800 --> 01:47:00.760
[Amit Varma]: or makes it moot in a certain sense is that, you know, you have long form content kind

01:47:00.760 --> 01:47:05.680
[Amit Varma]: of flourishing like this. So what's your sense of it? Does it change the kind of art that

01:47:05.680 --> 01:47:10.800
[Amit Varma]: is being produced? And does it also then in a positive way, change the kind of viewer

01:47:10.800 --> 01:47:13.720
[Amit Varma]: because consumers are so high is clearly?

01:47:13.720 --> 01:47:20.480
[Guest 1]: Yeah, well, you know, I mean, I agree completely. And this is what I'm saying is necessarily

01:47:20.480 --> 01:47:24.880
[Guest 1]: going to be a little more theoretical than as opposed to sort of coming from first hand

01:47:24.880 --> 01:47:30.760
[Guest 1]: understanding of it, because I haven't watched that many of these really long series myself.

01:47:30.760 --> 01:47:36.040
[Guest 1]: I've seen enough of them to know that enough good ones to know that it's a very exciting

01:47:36.040 --> 01:47:42.920
[Guest 1]: new development. This this especially this concept of the multi the multi season series

01:47:42.920 --> 01:47:47.960
[Guest 1]: where you know, you have five, six seasons over five, six years, and yet you know that,

01:47:47.960 --> 01:47:53.360
[Guest 1]: that the showrunners or the scriptwriters had a grand design in mind right from the

01:47:53.360 --> 01:47:57.120
[Guest 1]: very beginning. You know, so this I keep hearing about this in the context of shows like Breaking

01:47:57.120 --> 01:48:02.280
[Guest 1]: Bad and Better Call Saul, which I haven't seen myself, but I've heard enough about it

01:48:02.280 --> 01:48:07.800
[Guest 1]: from from people whose whose judgment I respect, whose taste I respect to know that it's something

01:48:07.800 --> 01:48:15.240
[Guest 1]: very special and that we really haven't had a precedent for this sort of thing done well

01:48:15.240 --> 01:48:23.680
[Guest 1]: in the past. So yeah, so there is something to be said about that. But but I also do I

01:48:23.680 --> 01:48:30.000
[Guest 1]: think I'm just coming back repeatedly not to the question of quality, whether it's something

01:48:30.000 --> 01:48:34.520
[Guest 1]: that's that's a 60 episode show, or whether it's a two minute TikTok video or whatever

01:48:34.520 --> 01:48:40.760
[Guest 1]: it is, I'm just coming back to the way in which people engage, you know, whether it's

01:48:40.760 --> 01:48:46.480
[Guest 1]: it's something that you know, I know, I suppose it sort of depends on the sort of consumer

01:48:46.480 --> 01:48:51.160
[Guest 1]: you are that that makes a difference. I still know even in today's day and age, I know,

01:48:51.160 --> 01:48:58.760
[Guest 1]: I have friends, writers among them who managed to just switch off all social media, their

01:48:58.760 --> 01:49:03.520
[Guest 1]: phones for hours on end when they have to sit down and read a novel for work or, or

01:49:03.520 --> 01:49:08.040
[Guest 1]: whatever, or just for, for pleasure or something that you just need to do on a particular day.

01:49:08.040 --> 01:49:13.040
[Guest 1]: So this was suppose that is still very much there. But on the whole, I suppose what I'm

01:49:13.040 --> 01:49:17.760
[Guest 1]: just saying is that maybe it is a somewhat conservative position that just sort of dates

01:49:17.760 --> 01:49:24.680
[Guest 1]: me in a way is that a lot of people I know a lot of young people in particular, do seem

01:49:24.680 --> 01:49:31.520
[Guest 1]: to be taking on more than their minds can actually process in a single day, in terms

01:49:31.520 --> 01:49:37.320
[Guest 1]: of the volume of content that's out there. And I see that when I see for instance, on

01:49:37.320 --> 01:49:42.400
[Guest 1]: on Facebook, for instance, if I'm part of a film club forum where discussions are had

01:49:42.400 --> 01:49:49.440
[Guest 1]: about films, it's very common for me to see people who are clearly very serious film buffs,

01:49:49.440 --> 01:49:54.160
[Guest 1]: and who are keen to really engage with things, watch as many things as possible, but who

01:49:54.160 --> 01:49:59.440
[Guest 1]: when they when they say something about a film about a particular film, you'll find

01:49:59.440 --> 01:50:02.840
[Guest 1]: them saying something that just sort of that, that to my mind, at least just indicates a

01:50:02.840 --> 01:50:08.160
[Guest 1]: very superficial takeaway, you know, you've just perhaps engaged with it at the level

01:50:08.160 --> 01:50:12.640
[Guest 1]: of plot, you're saying something also that there's this tendency to, and perhaps there's

01:50:12.640 --> 01:50:17.400
[Guest 1]: something I'm becoming more aware of, because I've been, I'm in the process of teaching.

01:50:17.400 --> 01:50:20.360
[Guest 1]: And I've been doing that for a while, and I'm going to be doing it in a more consolidated

01:50:20.360 --> 01:50:25.920
[Guest 1]: way from from next month, there seems to be this reluctance or inability to really research

01:50:25.920 --> 01:50:32.920
[Guest 1]: something. So, so someone will someone who's clearly a very passionate film buff will watch

01:50:32.920 --> 01:50:39.160
[Guest 1]: a new film that just come out, and will not even after watching it will not even take

01:50:39.160 --> 01:50:43.400
[Guest 1]: the trouble to, to perhaps go to the Wikipedia page to sort of find out something about the

01:50:43.400 --> 01:50:48.080
[Guest 1]: antecedents of the film, what it's based on what it might have been inspired by. So, so

01:50:48.080 --> 01:50:52.800
[Guest 1]: for instance, there, there might be a film that that is a remake of an earlier film.

01:50:52.800 --> 01:50:59.240
[Guest 1]: And this person will not know that at all, but will they write a long post on a film

01:50:59.240 --> 01:51:03.960
[Guest 1]: film discussion forum, discussing the film almost exclusively in terms of its plot and

01:51:03.960 --> 01:51:10.240
[Guest 1]: how it's so interesting, it's such a good film, because it's, it's such an such an original

01:51:10.240 --> 01:51:14.900
[Guest 1]: story or whatever it is, without even realising that, that the plot is actually the least

01:51:14.900 --> 01:51:20.160
[Guest 1]: original thing about it. It's, it's a direct remake of something that that happened 30-40

01:51:20.160 --> 01:51:27.720
[Guest 1]: years ago. And that to my mind is a very surface way of engaging with things. I think I maybe

01:51:27.720 --> 01:51:33.200
[Guest 1]: I just come from an old school thing where I need a lot of context for things. And I

01:51:33.200 --> 01:51:37.840
[Guest 1]: need to sort of have that background, especially as a professional writer, when one is one

01:51:37.840 --> 01:51:44.240
[Guest 1]: is actually putting your thoughts down about something you need to have a depth or breadth

01:51:44.240 --> 01:51:49.720
[Guest 1]: of knowledge about, about the background of the work that you're writing about. So that's

01:51:49.720 --> 01:51:52.240
[Guest 1]: maybe maybe that's what I'm talking about.

01:51:52.240 --> 01:51:58.200
[Amit Varma]: I think maybe, you know, that distinction is not an intergenerational distinction, but

01:51:58.200 --> 01:52:02.800
[Amit Varma]: just exists in the sense some people will always want depth and context and some people

01:52:02.800 --> 01:52:08.200
[Amit Varma]: won't. But the difference today is that the shallow buggers are megaphones also, right?

01:52:08.200 --> 01:52:13.080
[Amit Varma]: Because any, you know, apne zamane mein nahi tha, toh waisa. So now what is it to do? And

01:52:13.080 --> 01:52:16.280
[Amit Varma]: I love the way you're talking about, you know, you're saying the young generation, they're

01:52:16.280 --> 01:52:21.120
[Amit Varma]: not engaging. It's almost like you're telling all young people everywhere, tumse na ho paayega.

01:52:21.120 --> 01:52:26.640
[Guest 1]: You know, so if any of your students know that, that that is, well, it's my bad to use

01:52:26.640 --> 01:52:33.640
[Guest 1]: a to use a use a phrase that's much younger than I am. It's, it was, I think that, you

01:52:33.640 --> 01:52:37.720
[Guest 1]: know, you're right, of course, it's it shouldn't be an age specific thing. And we will be,

01:52:37.720 --> 01:52:42.680
[Guest 1]: we all know people of our own generation and older people older than us who, who have the

01:52:42.680 --> 01:52:49.240
[Guest 1]: same unwillingness or inability to, to, to do those things. I think I'm just thinking

01:52:49.240 --> 01:52:55.760
[Guest 1]: about a lot more because I'm, I'm engaging with or going to be engaging with students

01:52:55.760 --> 01:53:03.120
[Guest 1]: of a certain age, who sort of who bristle at the idea that cinema existed before Christopher

01:53:03.120 --> 01:53:14.320
[Guest 1]: Nolan made movies or whoever. So, so yeah. Actually, see, one, I mean, if you engage

01:53:14.320 --> 01:53:19.280
[Guest 2]: with it, like the way Jai mentioned that, you know, understand the context, a little

01:53:19.280 --> 01:53:23.560
[Guest 2]: bit of the history, the what where it is, you know, what were the antecedents of that

01:53:23.560 --> 01:53:30.560
[Guest 2]: particular film and the story. Actually, you're, what you get out of that piece of art, you

01:53:30.560 --> 01:53:36.160
[Guest 2]: know, increases tremendously. So, it's, you will just like it if you are getting deeper

01:53:36.160 --> 01:53:42.040
[Guest 2]: into it. So, it's not about some kind of, you know, snobbery around just knowing more

01:53:42.040 --> 01:53:48.280
[Guest 2]: about it, just improves your appreciation of art. And the other way of coming at it,

01:53:48.280 --> 01:53:54.440
[Guest 2]: which is if you don't believe this, for instance, is that almost everyone who, whose art you

01:53:54.440 --> 01:53:59.840
[Guest 2]: like, who's creating good, you know, even these long TV series and who's creating good

01:53:59.840 --> 01:54:08.600
[Guest 2]: cinema today, you will notice that they were deeply steeped in the history of the kind

01:54:08.600 --> 01:54:16.040
[Guest 2]: of work that they are doing. Always, it's, you know, Martin Scorsese knew every filmmaker

01:54:16.040 --> 01:54:22.960
[Guest 2]: of the 50s and watched everything, right. And, you know, Tarantino knew everything about,

01:54:22.960 --> 01:54:26.720
[Guest 2]: you know, whether it was French New Wave, or, you know, he knew everything, right. And

01:54:26.720 --> 01:54:35.040
[Guest 2]: even today, if you, including Nolan, right. So, if these guys appreciate what that was,

01:54:35.040 --> 01:54:40.960
[Guest 2]: right, and, and you have to respect the fact that they appreciated all of that, and therefore,

01:54:40.960 --> 01:54:45.840
[Guest 2]: they are creating this work, which you all are, you know, thoroughly enjoying, and possibly

01:54:45.840 --> 01:54:50.160
[Guest 2]: comparing more favorably with what has gone on in the past, then you should respect that

01:54:50.160 --> 01:54:56.120
[Guest 2]: guys, you know, the person that you are really appreciating their taste. And maybe give that

01:54:56.120 --> 01:54:59.240
[Guest 2]: benefit of doubt that we should go back and understand what was happening at that point

01:54:59.240 --> 01:55:04.920
[Guest 2]: in time, because they seem to be coming off a particular chain. And maybe there is something

01:55:04.920 --> 01:55:11.080
[Guest 2]: more to be done there. In fact, that's how, at least in my case, you know, it's not, I

01:55:11.080 --> 01:55:15.720
[Guest 2]: mean, in some cases, it has been random, you know, jump into someone. But in many cases,

01:55:15.720 --> 01:55:21.440
[Guest 2]: it's been this kind, you know, you read somewhere, some Coen brother interview and mentions Preston

01:55:21.440 --> 01:55:28.800
[Guest 2]: Sturges, and you're like, yeah, man, I love these guys. I mean, these guys, for me at

01:55:28.800 --> 01:55:33.240
[Guest 2]: a particular time in, you know, early 2000s, and it was like, I mean, Coen brother toh

01:55:33.240 --> 01:55:39.360
[Guest 2]: kuch bhi karega, purana, apneya, sab jaake dhoond ke dekho. So, why are these guys talking

01:55:39.360 --> 01:55:45.920
[Guest 2]: about someone who was like, 50 years before this time and in such favorable terms. And

01:55:45.920 --> 01:55:51.680
[Guest 2]: so, then you go back to, you know, Sturges, and then you say that, okay, by mistake, maine

01:55:51.680 --> 01:55:56.960
[Guest 2]: ek picture dekh liya tha. I don't even remember, Ball of Fire or something I'd watched. And

01:55:56.960 --> 01:56:02.480
[Guest 2]: then you figure out, you know, that the Lady Eve or what, and then you realize ki kya,

01:56:02.480 --> 01:56:07.640
[Guest 2]: as a scriptwriter, kamaal tha. I mean, you know, the guy could do, you know, really great

01:56:07.640 --> 01:56:13.200
[Guest 2]: script, really tight. I mean, he had a fairly short sort of, you know, real dramatic peak

01:56:13.200 --> 01:56:20.640
[Guest 2]: for 5-6 years. He just wrote, you know, these next level screwball comedy stuff, you know,

01:56:20.640 --> 01:56:26.840
[Guest 2]: the banter, the back and forth. So, yeah, so then you discover that, then you discover

01:56:26.840 --> 01:56:31.320
[Guest 2]: it. I mean, then you find more, then you get deeper into it, then you realize you've never

01:56:31.320 --> 01:56:36.600
[Guest 2]: fully appreciated Barbara Steinweg, then you go down Barbara Steinweg path, and you know,

01:56:36.600 --> 01:56:45.200
[Guest 2]: you get so much out of that stuff. So, I, you know, you will be richer from, you know,

01:56:45.200 --> 01:56:50.440
[Guest 2]: the deeper dive is my sense. I mean, you'll be richer by much more than what you do.

01:56:50.440 --> 01:56:54.560
[Guest 1]: You know, I just want to want to say again, as someone who, I think we may have discussed

01:56:54.560 --> 01:56:58.680
[Guest 1]: this before someone who for whom it happened very randomly, my own journey into really

01:56:58.680 --> 01:57:04.080
[Guest 1]: old cinema, including cinema that was made decades before I was born, had just happened

01:57:04.080 --> 01:57:09.680
[Guest 1]: when I was an adolescent. And I mean, through a series of events that even I can't completely

01:57:09.680 --> 01:57:14.400
[Guest 1]: make sense of, you know, where you just sort of, you know, you just become interested,

01:57:14.400 --> 01:57:20.480
[Guest 1]: you have an aunt somewhere who has some cassettes of 1950s films, you overhear a conversation

01:57:20.480 --> 01:57:24.560
[Guest 1]: between your mother and one of her friends and, or you sort of see Laurence Olivier's

01:57:24.560 --> 01:57:31.640
[Guest 1]: obituary in the newspaper in 1989, in July 1989, front page Times of India, become intrigued

01:57:31.640 --> 01:57:36.440
[Guest 1]: kid, you know, a non-Indian actor on the front page of the Times of India or whatever it

01:57:36.440 --> 01:57:42.760
[Guest 1]: is. There's so many things that can go into this process. I have to clarify since I always

01:57:42.760 --> 01:57:46.400
[Guest 1]: sort of, you know, I get, you know, in my own circles, I get pigeonholed as someone

01:57:46.400 --> 01:57:50.120
[Guest 1]: who's always insisting that you should see older stuff, you should make these deep dives

01:57:50.120 --> 01:57:56.240
[Guest 1]: into all sorts of things that I have all the sympathy in the world for people, young people,

01:57:56.240 --> 01:58:01.480
[Guest 1]: people my own age, whatever, who simply cannot find the time to do this, because there's

01:58:01.480 --> 01:58:05.560
[Guest 1]: so much brilliant stuff, as you pointed out, just now, as we were talking just now, that's,

01:58:05.560 --> 01:58:08.800
[Guest 1]: that's happening in the here and now the content that has been made in the last three days

01:58:08.800 --> 01:58:12.600
[Amit Varma]: or whatever it is, or the last five years, I didn't mean to indicate it was brilliant.

01:58:12.600 --> 01:58:17.320
[Amit Varma]: I meant to indicate it's addictive, but whatever, I mean, it can be both, you know, talking

01:58:17.320 --> 01:58:22.080
[Guest 1]: about stuff like Breaking Bad or The Wire or whatever, also talking about those things

01:58:22.080 --> 01:58:27.160
[Guest 1]: as well. There's so much. So I have a lot of sympathy for people, including people who

01:58:27.160 --> 01:58:34.600
[Guest 1]: are, you know, trying to be professional film writers, I know, you know, some of the finest

01:58:34.600 --> 01:58:38.360
[Guest 1]: film critics in the country right now, and I know, because I know some of them personally

01:58:38.360 --> 01:58:44.400
[Guest 1]: are people who barely have any knowledge of pre 1970s cinema, and they are aware of it

01:58:44.400 --> 01:58:48.280
[Guest 1]: and they feel a bit handicapped by it, but here they are with, with multiple deadlines

01:58:48.280 --> 01:58:53.920
[Guest 1]: every week, you know, with multiple films to watch, new films to watch just for work,

01:58:53.920 --> 01:59:00.640
[Guest 1]: where does one find the time to, to go back and explore films of the 20s, 30s, in a consolidated

01:59:00.640 --> 01:59:04.520
[Guest 1]: structured way where you can really educate yourself in a, in a meaningful way. So that's

01:59:04.520 --> 01:59:11.520
[Guest 1]: why I get that completely. It's just that I do, I do feel that, that inevitably there

01:59:11.520 --> 01:59:16.040
[Guest 1]: will be a sense of loss if you don't have that, have some historical background, you

01:59:16.040 --> 01:59:20.680
[Guest 1]: are going to be missing out on a lot of stuff, you know. So, so for instance, I was just,

01:59:20.680 --> 01:59:25.920
[Guest 1]: just to take one example. And what you said, you know, is, is of course, right, but I have

01:59:25.920 --> 01:59:29.640
[Guest 1]: to say that Martin Scorsese is such an outlier when it comes to these things that he should

01:59:29.640 --> 01:59:35.200
[Unknown]: never be used as an example for anything. He's the sort of guy who will, you know, you'll

01:59:35.200 --> 01:59:42.240
[Guest 1]: name any film to him, you know, you're interviewing him, and you name any film made between 1910

01:59:42.240 --> 01:59:48.240
[Guest 1]: and 1970. And he'll, he'll say, Oh, I've seen that one 30 times or something.

01:59:48.240 --> 01:59:49.240
[Amit Varma]: Have you interviewed him?

01:59:49.240 --> 01:59:57.400
[Guest 1]: No, I haven't. I mean, I'm fine. In my dreams, in my dreams. So I've, so he's, he's, he's

01:59:57.400 --> 02:00:04.640
[Guest 1]: not the best example for this sort of thing. I do know lots of contemporary Indian directors

02:00:04.640 --> 02:00:11.560
[Guest 1]: and scriptwriters who are steeped in, you know, they are aware of stuff that has happened

02:00:11.560 --> 02:00:17.000
[Guest 1]: before, but many of them, a large percentage of them, in my experience, seem to really

02:00:17.000 --> 02:00:22.080
[Guest 1]: have sort of seem to seem to feel like the important stuff in film history really started

02:00:22.080 --> 02:00:28.160
[Guest 1]: in the 1970s with the with the kids in with the kids with beards in the US with the Scorsese

02:00:28.160 --> 02:00:35.360
[Guest 1]: Coppola generation. And they are definitely lacking on the whole, in knowledge about about

02:00:35.360 --> 02:00:39.680
[Guest 1]: the period that you mentioned the Preston Sturges period, the period of the 1940s, or

02:00:39.680 --> 02:00:43.880
[Guest 1]: the 50s, and American cinema, for instance, which I think is one of the great, great for

02:00:43.880 --> 02:00:49.520
[Guest 1]: great founts of, of everything. And, and, of course, the what we call world cinema from

02:00:49.520 --> 02:00:57.320
[Guest 1]: the 1950s. There is that lacking to some that I know, I know lots of Indian scriptwriters,

02:00:57.320 --> 02:01:03.280
[Guest 1]: directors, who are working on some very good web series or films or have been in the last

02:01:03.280 --> 02:01:10.080
[Guest 1]: few years who just whose film education begins with the 1970s. It doesn't go back before

02:01:10.080 --> 02:01:17.200
[Guest 2]: that. So that is there also. That's a it's a great decade to still start

02:01:17.200 --> 02:01:26.080
[Unknown]: with. Coppola, De Palma, it's a great decade, but then as Scorsese, who was a central figure

02:01:26.080 --> 02:01:29.920
[Guest 1]: in that decade keeps saying, you know, we stood on the shoulders of giants, you know,

02:01:29.920 --> 02:01:35.880
[Guest 1]: and and and people, you know, if you're trying to appreciate our work, in a deep way, you

02:01:35.880 --> 02:01:40.760
[Guest 1]: have to sort of go further back, and then then further back beyond that. That's definitely

02:01:40.760 --> 02:01:51.680
[Guest 2]: at least a lot of them just had such strong Hitchcockian hangover. De Palma for sure.

02:01:51.680 --> 02:01:57.240
[Amit Varma]: So you know, Subrata, we'll come back to your story after the break, because you actually,

02:01:57.240 --> 02:02:01.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, knew a lot of the protagonists in the Indian film scene, you wanted to be a

02:02:01.200 --> 02:02:04.680
[Amit Varma]: filmmaker yourself. But we'll come to that after the break. One final big question before

02:02:04.680 --> 02:02:09.880
[Amit Varma]: the break, which sort of takes off from what you were just talking about. Howard Bloom

02:02:09.880 --> 02:02:17.280
[Amit Varma]: has a book called How to Read and Why, right? And, and I'm very curious about how you guys

02:02:17.280 --> 02:02:21.440
[Amit Varma]: would answer the question of how to watch a film and why. And I don't mean this in a

02:02:21.440 --> 02:02:25.720
[Amit Varma]: prescriptive sense, ki bachcho ko batao, ki, you know, ye points hai, ye aapko likhna hai,

02:02:25.720 --> 02:02:29.680
[Amit Varma]: ye karna hai, not like that. But just in a sense of the first time we watch a film, we

02:02:29.680 --> 02:02:34.760
[Amit Varma]: are as children, we are watching the film as you know, it's a linear narrative, it's

02:02:34.760 --> 02:02:39.240
[Amit Varma]: a story you're interested ye hua, iske baad ye hua, so on and so forth. But later layers

02:02:39.240 --> 02:02:44.120
[Amit Varma]: begin to form, you begin to see more in the film, layers form in your own head and of

02:02:44.120 --> 02:02:47.440
[Amit Varma]: how you watch it and the different things that you look for and the different connections

02:02:47.440 --> 02:02:52.920
[Amit Varma]: that you make, and so on. And there are also other layers which you may or may not engage

02:02:52.920 --> 02:02:57.640
[Amit Varma]: with what the filmmaker intended, where is he coming from, and even everything you just

02:02:57.640 --> 02:03:04.600
[Amit Varma]: described, the giants on whose shoulders, you know, she may stand. So, in terms of just

02:03:04.600 --> 02:03:08.960
[Amit Varma]: that experience of watching a film, and not necessarily watching it to write a review

02:03:08.960 --> 02:03:12.640
[Amit Varma]: ki aap notes le rahe ho, ki ye likhna hai, ye likhna hai, ye likhna hai, but just you're

02:03:12.640 --> 02:03:17.160
[Amit Varma]: watching a film for pleasure, you know, how has that changed over the years in the sense

02:03:17.160 --> 02:03:20.360
[Amit Varma]: that you guys look at cinema?

02:03:20.360 --> 02:03:24.960
[Guest 1]: Again, it's difficult to really say, I think it probably works differently for different

02:03:24.960 --> 02:03:31.440
[Guest 1]: people. You know, one of the reasons why I ended up becoming a professional film critic

02:03:31.440 --> 02:03:36.720
[Guest 1]: or someone who was interested in recording his feelings about films from a very early

02:03:36.720 --> 02:03:42.120
[Guest 1]: age going right back to, you know, the age of nine or 10, when I was just scribbling

02:03:42.120 --> 02:03:47.040
[Guest 1]: things randomly on notepads about my favourite Amitabh Bachchan films or whatever it is,

02:03:47.040 --> 02:03:51.440
[Guest 1]: giving them star ratings, which is something that's pretty amusing, because I'm so disdainful

02:03:51.440 --> 02:03:56.160
[Guest 1]: about star ratings and, and these rankings, like, like you were,

02:03:56.160 --> 02:03:59.640
[Amit Varma]: You were giving star ratings to stars. So they were star star ratings.

02:03:59.640 --> 02:04:06.640
[Guest 1]: Star star ratings. Yes, yes. Well, stars and their films. So when you have that particular

02:04:06.640 --> 02:04:11.440
[Guest 1]: imperative, that's something very just a few people have, right? I mean, most people, bless

02:04:11.440 --> 02:04:16.640
[Guest 1]: their souls, because I feel very envious of them are just content to watch a film, you

02:04:16.640 --> 02:04:21.920
[Guest 1]: know, with enthusiasm without, you know, necessarily getting cerebral or, or, or even putting down

02:04:21.920 --> 02:04:27.080
[Guest 1]: thoughts about it. In fact, some of some of my friends who I'm most envious of in this

02:04:27.080 --> 02:04:33.000
[Guest 1]: regard are massive film buffs who can who can have these incredibly informed and intelligent

02:04:33.000 --> 02:04:38.880
[Guest 1]: conversations about cinema, but who don't have that, that writerly impulse at all, that

02:04:38.880 --> 02:04:42.360
[Guest 1]: day that they would they want to sit down and put it down. And I've had that for as

02:04:42.360 --> 02:04:47.200
[Guest 1]: far back as I can remember. So then someone like that, when when you when you're watching

02:04:47.200 --> 02:04:52.440
[Guest 1]: a film, inevitably, you are sort of trying at some conscious level to pick up on certain

02:04:52.440 --> 02:04:58.360
[Guest 1]: things also, depending at what stage in your development you are, as a as a film watcher.

02:04:58.360 --> 02:05:03.840
[Guest 1]: Of course, it's true that I think it's true for the vast majority of us, that that our

02:05:03.840 --> 02:05:09.240
[Guest 1]: first point of engagement with a film is purely at the level of what happens next, what happens

02:05:09.240 --> 02:05:16.720
[Guest 1]: at the plot level, actors, stars, I think a majority of us as initial film buffs, and

02:05:16.720 --> 02:05:22.160
[Guest 1]: maybe even through a lifetime of film watching are most interested in the people on the screen,

02:05:22.160 --> 02:05:27.080
[Guest 1]: and you know, and you know, and developing certain sort of affinities with star personalities,

02:05:27.080 --> 02:05:32.520
[Guest 1]: projecting their own feelings onto them, which is which is why we have the phenomenon of

02:05:32.520 --> 02:05:38.720
[Guest 1]: the big movie star, who may or may not also be a very good actor. Really, there's, I don't

02:05:38.720 --> 02:05:44.280
[Guest 1]: think there can be any one one size fits all answer to a question like this. It just depends

02:05:44.280 --> 02:05:50.920
[Guest 1]: on, you know, what stage of your film development you're at. Now, today, if I were to watch

02:05:50.920 --> 02:05:56.800
[Guest 1]: a film, even if I'm not writing about it on a deadline, chances are that my mind is sufficiently

02:05:56.800 --> 02:06:03.680
[Guest 1]: trained to, on the one hand, pay attention to what's happening at the plot level to sort

02:06:03.680 --> 02:06:09.360
[Guest 1]: of follow what's happening and to be stimulated by that, ab kya hone wala hai, etc. Assuming

02:06:09.360 --> 02:06:14.880
[Guest 1]: that I don't already know much about the film beforehand, but also picking up on little

02:06:14.880 --> 02:06:23.240
[Guest 1]: things at the level of cinematography, sound design, etc. Or at least deriving some enjoyment

02:06:23.240 --> 02:06:28.680
[Guest 1]: from how a well made film is bringing all its elements together and putting them at

02:06:28.680 --> 02:06:34.200
[Guest 1]: the service of creating the experience. So just to give you one example of this very

02:06:34.200 --> 02:06:44.240
[Guest 1]: recent Malayalam film called Malayan Kunju, which is a Fahad Fasil film. And he's already

02:06:44.240 --> 02:06:49.520
[Guest 1]: quite a big name, even among non South Indian viewers who are seeking out Malayalam and

02:06:49.520 --> 02:06:57.680
[Guest 1]: Tamil cinema. It's a film about this character played by Fahad, who is bitter and he's resentful

02:06:57.680 --> 02:07:01.760
[Guest 1]: for various reasons, he's not very happy inside. And then around midway through the film, he

02:07:01.760 --> 02:07:06.360
[Guest 1]: finds himself caught in a landslide, and then it becomes a survival film. And I was watching

02:07:06.360 --> 02:07:10.240
[Guest 1]: it even though I watched it on a laptop screen, unfortunately, I wish I could have seen it

02:07:10.240 --> 02:07:18.720
[Guest 1]: on the big screen, I missed it. I watched it on a laptop screen with the full earphones

02:07:18.720 --> 02:07:23.880
[Guest 1]: plugged in. And while I was very engaged with the story, because it is an engaging story,

02:07:23.880 --> 02:07:28.080
[Guest 1]: you want to know what's going to happen to him from one step to the other. At one point,

02:07:28.080 --> 02:07:33.400
[Guest 1]: I also found myself really reveling in the sound design of the film, because he's a large

02:07:33.400 --> 02:07:39.680
[Guest 1]: part of the second half of the film, he's trapped underwater or somewhere in a cave

02:07:39.680 --> 02:07:46.600
[Guest 1]: below where his house used to be. And there's a sound of a baby wailing in the far distance,

02:07:46.600 --> 02:07:52.400
[Guest 1]: which is a pivotal plot point in the film, a child who used to feel very disturbed by,

02:07:52.400 --> 02:07:57.880
[Guest 1]: but who now sort of becomes like this something for him to hold on to an oral experience for

02:07:57.880 --> 02:08:01.600
[Guest 1]: him to, you know, to remember that there's a world out there that he has to try and get

02:08:01.600 --> 02:08:09.000
[Guest 1]: back to. And I became really fascinated by the sound design of the film. And aware, while

02:08:09.000 --> 02:08:13.880
[Guest 1]: I was immersed in the film, I was also aware that this is what the sound designer and the

02:08:13.880 --> 02:08:18.760
[Guest 1]: director what they've done this, what they've constructed to heighten the experience of

02:08:18.760 --> 02:08:22.800
[Guest 1]: the film. Just one example, you can apply that to cinematography, you can apply that

02:08:22.800 --> 02:08:30.300
[Guest 1]: to editing, background music, whatever. So really, that's, it varies. It also also varies

02:08:30.300 --> 02:08:33.200
[Guest 1]: depending on the type of film it is that there are films that are that are not narrative

02:08:33.200 --> 02:08:39.000
[Guest 1]: films at all the anti narrative films. There's, you know, if you watch a Goddard film from

02:08:39.000 --> 02:08:43.120
[Guest 1]: the 60s, which is, which is not about telling a story in a linear way, or even about telling

02:08:43.120 --> 02:08:47.960
[Guest 1]: any sort of story, sometimes, you're sort of looking at it and, and trying to sort of,

02:08:47.960 --> 02:08:53.320
[Guest 1]: you know, pick up on elements of, you know, the atmosphere created by the film, the perspective

02:08:53.320 --> 02:08:57.240
[Guest 1]: that is being expressed, the little playful things he's doing at the level of forming

02:08:57.240 --> 02:09:02.120
[Guest 1]: it, and maybe it won't be immersive. For you, as a viewer to be more about actually sitting

02:09:02.120 --> 02:09:07.080
[Guest 1]: and being more analytical throughout the thing. What is he doing? What, what camera angle

02:09:07.080 --> 02:09:11.120
[Guest 1]: has he chosen here? Why is he just sort of why is he got a camera fixed on this person

02:09:11.120 --> 02:09:18.080
[Guest 1]: for five minutes, or on this coffee cup with the coffee swirling inside, you know, standing

02:09:18.080 --> 02:09:22.600
[Guest 1]: for the cosmos or whatever it is, you start thinking, thinking, thinking about those things.

02:09:22.600 --> 02:09:28.920
[Guest 1]: It depends on the type of film, the depends on whether you're writing about it, whether

02:09:28.920 --> 02:09:34.080
[Guest 1]: you're watching it primarily for relaxation. So many things.

02:09:34.080 --> 02:09:43.400
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, see, I think one way to look at this is, you know, if you consume something

02:09:43.400 --> 02:09:49.600
[Guest 2]: in fairly regular and large quantities, you start then figuring out what is good or not.

02:09:49.600 --> 02:09:54.320
[Guest 2]: It's just natural. I mean, you know, I love biryani. And over a period of time since I've

02:09:54.320 --> 02:09:59.280
[Guest 2]: eaten so many biryani, the first morsel is enough. And it's very difficult to explain

02:09:59.280 --> 02:10:05.280
[Guest 2]: what's going on in your mind the minute you eat the first morsel, but you know, and even

02:10:05.280 --> 02:10:10.680
[Guest 2]: if there are different types of biryani within them, I know the difference. I mean, the macro

02:10:10.680 --> 02:10:15.200
[Guest 2]: difference is potato, but the micro difference is something very different. And then you

02:10:15.200 --> 02:10:19.800
[Guest 2]: have it, you realize this Kolkata biryani is better than the other one. And so might

02:10:19.800 --> 02:10:25.160
[Guest 2]: be the case with the Mopla biryani or the, you know, the various kinds of rice that they

02:10:25.160 --> 02:10:32.600
[Guest 2]: use in the talap katti biryani or the dindigul biryani. So one is if you watch a lot of it,

02:10:32.600 --> 02:10:37.560
[Guest 2]: you automatically something, you know, you get in your head in terms of how you are able

02:10:37.560 --> 02:10:43.560
[Guest 2]: to appreciate that. So that's definitely happened with me. So in the absence of any formal sort

02:10:43.560 --> 02:10:48.160
[Guest 2]: of learning or anything of that kind, it happened. And I'll tell you some very simple things

02:10:48.160 --> 02:10:54.060
[Guest 2]: like you know, you watch Mukkaddar ka Sikandar. And many people watch it. And sometimes I

02:10:54.060 --> 02:11:00.560
[Guest 2]: tell them that actually it is Devdas. People completely find it, you know, as a revelation

02:11:00.560 --> 02:11:07.600
[Guest 2]: ki yeh Devdas ka story hai. Because, you know, they've just watched it. But when you just

02:11:07.600 --> 02:11:12.640
[Guest 2]: explain it to them, it's the same thing. There is one, you know, Paro and then, you know,

02:11:12.640 --> 02:11:17.040
[Guest 2]: the Rekha's character is a dancer, is a courtesan, she's Chandramukhi and it's exactly the same.

02:11:17.040 --> 02:11:20.840
[Guest 2]: There is Churnilal in the form of Inod Khanna. Chalo Amjad Khan aajaata hai and so on and

02:11:20.840 --> 02:11:26.760
[Guest 2]: so forth. And last mein mar jaata hai. And on the, you know, dies next to Rakhi and stuff.

02:11:26.760 --> 02:11:32.960
[Guest 2]: That only happens if you, you know, after sort of while watching it, you have watched

02:11:32.960 --> 02:11:37.520
[Guest 2]: so many films that you're not just watching it, you're just trying to make some sort of

02:11:37.520 --> 02:11:43.240
[Guest 2]: a meta connect about, you know, what the story is and what does this sort of, you know, is

02:11:43.240 --> 02:11:47.800
[Guest 2]: this similar to some other pattern or some other kind of similar story. And that's at

02:11:47.800 --> 02:11:52.600
[Guest 2]: that level. Forget, like, Jai was mentioning the soundscape and, you know, the camera angles,

02:11:52.600 --> 02:11:57.760
[Guest 2]: etc. will come later. Sometimes people just miss the very obvious plot itself. It seems

02:11:57.760 --> 02:12:03.960
[Guest 2]: very, because you just watch and come out of it, right? So that's, so that's, like,

02:12:03.960 --> 02:12:11.400
[Guest 2]: that's one thing. And I see this even in reading, right? I mean, you, all of us sort of first

02:12:11.400 --> 02:12:16.720
[Guest 2]: started off with harka phulka reading, you know, we did the Woodhouse and the Agatha

02:12:16.720 --> 02:12:22.040
[Guest 2]: Christie's and all that. And even there, by the 10th, Agatha Christie, you start appreciating

02:12:22.040 --> 02:12:27.880
[Guest 2]: how firstly intricate it is, who's saying what, etc, etc. And by the time you are in

02:12:27.880 --> 02:12:32.080
[Guest 2]: the 12th or 13th, you are trying to guess because you now figured out how she sort of

02:12:32.080 --> 02:12:37.600
[Guest 2]: leaves red earrings and clues and things of that kind. Same with Woodhouse. I mean, those

02:12:37.600 --> 02:12:42.000
[Guest 2]: plots might be farcical and silly, but very intricate. I mean, and everything falls in

02:12:42.000 --> 02:12:47.360
[Guest 2]: place at the end, right? And in very sort of funny and in a twisted sort of logical

02:12:47.360 --> 02:12:55.400
[Guest 2]: way, but you know, it falls in place. So I think if you just consume more, you will find

02:12:55.400 --> 02:12:59.880
[Guest 2]: it and you might not be able to articulate it, but often you'll find it. So that's sort

02:12:59.880 --> 02:13:05.280
[Guest 2]: of one way of looking at it. The second is then, you know, one of the things that came

02:13:05.280 --> 02:13:10.400
[Guest 2]: to me over a period of time is just the way the director is showing you the film, right?

02:13:10.400 --> 02:13:15.760
[Guest 2]: Not just you as a viewer watching it. I mean, you know, he could have placed the camera

02:13:15.760 --> 02:13:23.240
[Guest 2]: here, or he could have taken it up and shown you a different view. What does that do to

02:13:23.240 --> 02:13:29.960
[Guest 2]: your viewing experience? You know, and same with, you know, the sound and when you start

02:13:29.960 --> 02:13:34.600
[Guest 2]: realizing that, you know, he's actually or she's actually, you know, playing God, I mean,

02:13:34.600 --> 02:13:40.160
[Guest 2]: they're actually taking you through this, how they want you to experience that particular

02:13:40.160 --> 02:13:48.720
[Guest 2]: scene. And that, I think, that was a moment of sort of, you know, revelation that I, I

02:13:48.720 --> 02:13:54.760
[Guest 2]: mean, I, with some directors, I started realizing that there is something at work here that

02:13:54.760 --> 02:14:01.040
[Guest 2]: you, they are in some sense manipulating or in some sense, they want you to watch the,

02:14:01.040 --> 02:14:07.720
[Guest 2]: you know, drama unfolding in a certain way. And that once you've seen that, then you can't

02:14:07.720 --> 02:14:11.840
[Guest 2]: unsee it. I mean, in the sense you just, you know, next time you're watching a film, you're

02:14:11.840 --> 02:14:17.840
[Guest 2]: doing it both as a viewer and sometimes also as how you are being, you know, you're being

02:14:17.840 --> 02:14:24.080
[Guest 2]: asked to view it. And then of course, that plus the sort of there is always a subtext

02:14:24.080 --> 02:14:28.720
[Guest 2]: or sometimes a subtext or a meta narrative of in every film. I mean, even if the director

02:14:28.720 --> 02:14:34.960
[Guest 2]: sometimes is not fully thinking about it, you as a viewer can appreciate and take away.

02:14:34.960 --> 02:14:39.880
[Guest 2]: And often I've realized, even if it is Prakash Mehra in Mukaddar Ka Sikandar, boss, he's

02:14:39.880 --> 02:14:45.000
[Guest 2]: thinking about it. He's figured that it is Devdasi Banarao. But he's also thinking at

02:14:45.000 --> 02:14:50.120
[Guest 2]: multiple levels the way, the reason he names the character Sikandar, who's technically

02:14:50.120 --> 02:14:56.320
[Guest 2]: means, you know, unconquered or whatever, cannot be defeated. But then, you know, loses

02:14:56.320 --> 02:15:02.400
[Guest 2]: in love. Kar raha hai boss, wo Prakash Mehra hai, par wo poora dimaag laga raha hai, including

02:15:02.400 --> 02:15:07.240
[Guest 2]: naming the character in a certain way and, you know, all of that. And then of course,

02:15:07.240 --> 02:15:14.120
[Guest 2]: with better filmmakers and like one of the films among many rare films, I just love Nayak.

02:15:14.120 --> 02:15:19.800
[Guest 2]: One is, you know, it's just, it's in its own way, contained sort of environment film, right?

02:15:19.800 --> 02:15:25.720
[Guest 2]: They're all in the, in the train, you know, in that single compartment. There is Sharmila

02:15:25.720 --> 02:15:32.320
[Guest 2]: Tagore, who is not taken in by these guys, you know, the fandom or whatever, the fact

02:15:32.320 --> 02:15:38.400
[Guest 2]: that he's a celebrity, the fact that she can, you know, critically ask him questions that

02:15:38.400 --> 02:15:44.600
[Guest 2]: makes him go back and, you know, think and reflect about the journey that he's had. You

02:15:44.600 --> 02:15:50.080
[Guest 2]: realize then that, you know, at a general level, it's a story of somebody sitting there

02:15:50.080 --> 02:15:53.960
[Guest 2]: and she's there and you're seeing a little bit of chemistry, but she's also asking him

02:15:53.960 --> 02:15:58.760
[Guest 2]: some questions, he's thinking about it. But then after some time, you realize that it's

02:15:58.760 --> 02:16:08.760
[Guest 2]: a genuinely a deeper examination of, you know, success, also of, you know, the fact that

02:16:08.760 --> 02:16:13.560
[Guest 2]: you are a celebrity and how do you personally, you know, what do you have to deal with, you

02:16:13.560 --> 02:16:19.560
[Guest 2]: know, thinking about the compromises you have made, so on and so forth. And then you get

02:16:19.560 --> 02:16:26.480
[Guest 2]: a better appreciation of, you know, how the filmmaker has, you know, put that thing together.

02:16:26.480 --> 02:16:30.600
[Guest 2]: So I mean, like I said, you know, there are just these two, three things at least that

02:16:30.600 --> 02:16:35.360
[Guest 2]: I can articulate that sort of opens your mind to it, you know, just the idea of is there

02:16:35.360 --> 02:16:40.640
[Guest 2]: something more where you can connect the plot to the story to how the director wants you

02:16:40.640 --> 02:16:46.240
[Guest 2]: to see it. And, you know, and then once you figure that out, it's how the, you know, what

02:16:46.240 --> 02:16:50.320
[Guest 2]: are the deeper questions or, you know, things that the director is asking. And after some

02:16:50.320 --> 02:16:55.520
[Guest 2]: time, you sometimes start overthinking it, maybe even the director is not doing it. But

02:16:55.520 --> 02:17:01.920
[Guest 2]: you're like, why did he or she wear something there of that kind? And, you know, all of

02:17:01.920 --> 02:17:06.800
[Guest 2]: that, then, why did they suddenly show, why was it raining at that point in time, and

02:17:06.800 --> 02:17:11.320
[Guest 2]: so on and so forth. So, and then you build your own, you know, context and narrative.

02:17:11.320 --> 02:17:16.760
[Guest 2]: But again, it's fairly enriching. And then if you start seeing a body of work of a director

02:17:16.760 --> 02:17:20.880
[Guest 2]: of you then find that there is, then you see that there is even more a pattern because

02:17:20.880 --> 02:17:25.560
[Guest 1]: that guy is doing something similar for a period of time. Yeah, that's, that's a very

02:17:25.560 --> 02:17:28.520
[Guest 1]: important, I was about to come to that, that, you know, if you're talking about the process

02:17:28.520 --> 02:17:33.840
[Guest 1]: of watching films, how does one watch films, then of course, another important factor is

02:17:33.840 --> 02:17:39.280
[Guest 1]: you watch multiple films made by the same director or even featuring the same actor,

02:17:39.280 --> 02:17:44.320
[Guest 1]: or the same cinematographer, you know, music director who has a certain part to play in

02:17:44.320 --> 02:17:48.480
[Guest 1]: the in the making of the film, you start seeing patterns as well, right. And of course, some

02:17:48.480 --> 02:17:52.560
[Guest 1]: of those patterns might just be coming as you know, from from your, your own projections

02:17:52.560 --> 02:17:58.000
[Guest 1]: and overthinking, over reading or whatever you want to call it. Though, as you know,

02:17:58.000 --> 02:18:05.520
[Guest 1]: I'm also a big fan of subtextual analysis taken as far as it can go. I just also wanted

02:18:05.520 --> 02:18:09.220
[Guest 1]: to just interject and this is the sort of thing that happens, this serendipitous sort

02:18:09.220 --> 02:18:13.720
[Guest 1]: of thing that happens when movie buffs are just sitting and talking, right. Complete

02:18:13.720 --> 02:18:18.440
[Guest 1]: coincidence this morning, I was actually writing something about Mukadarka Sikandar. You know,

02:18:18.440 --> 02:18:24.360
[Guest 1]: as part of an essay about Prakash Mehra and Bachchan. And I just wanted to add to what

02:18:24.360 --> 02:18:30.280
[Guest 1]: you said, you know, yeah, you know, it's not just is it, is it very much a Devdas film?

02:18:30.280 --> 02:18:33.680
[Guest 1]: It's also one of the most interesting Devdas films we've had, because it may be the only

02:18:33.680 --> 02:18:42.080
[Guest 1]: one where across the many Indian cultures, where the man is not laying this heavy guilt

02:18:42.080 --> 02:18:49.240
[Guest 1]: trip on the woman, on the woman who, you know, who doesn't reciprocate his, you know, so

02:18:49.240 --> 02:18:53.280
[Guest 1]: one of the moving things about that film for me is the relationship, the fact that the

02:18:53.280 --> 02:18:58.240
[Guest 1]: Bachchan character, even though Rakhi, the Rakhi character, we want to call her the Paro,

02:18:58.240 --> 02:19:04.480
[Guest 1]: Paro like figure, she doesn't, you know, it's unrequited love, she doesn't reciprocate.

02:19:04.480 --> 02:19:10.960
[Guest 1]: He never stops feeling grateful to her and beholden to her in a sense, because of, at

02:19:10.960 --> 02:19:15.800
[Guest 1]: a purely platonic level, what she did for him when he was a child. And that, that devotion

02:19:15.800 --> 02:19:20.880
[Guest 1]: is always there, that that that acknowledgement is there. It doesn't really, it doesn't devolve

02:19:20.880 --> 02:19:27.520
[Guest 1]: into, you know, I'm the, I'm the angsty male who's been rebuffed, and I'm going to put

02:19:27.520 --> 02:19:31.920
[Guest 1]: this major guilt trip on the woman, it doesn't turn into that. So it's quite an unusual Devdas

02:19:31.920 --> 02:19:32.920
[Guest 1]: in that sense.

