[Amit Varma]: Kronenberg banayega kuch. So the next question comes from that, you know, interesting point

02:24:04.600 --> 02:24:08.400
[Amit Varma]: you raised, Subrata, about, you know, that when you're watching a film, it's not just

02:24:08.400 --> 02:24:12.520
[Amit Varma]: what you are bringing to it, but you're also thinking about the director's intentionality.

02:24:12.520 --> 02:24:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Now I had this conversation with Varun in my episode with him, which you haven't heard

02:24:17.280 --> 02:24:22.200
[Amit Varma]: because it's not released, but it'll be released well before yours, of course, where I asked

02:24:22.200 --> 02:24:27.640
[Amit Varma]: him about the ending of Masaan, right? Beautiful film. And the film, of course, and I, since

02:24:27.640 --> 02:24:31.440
[Amit Varma]: I've already given the spoiler away in my episode with Varun, I can just do it again.

02:24:31.440 --> 02:24:34.600
[Amit Varma]: But essentially, there are these two parallel tracks of these two people who have loved

02:24:34.600 --> 02:24:41.160
[Amit Varma]: and lost in different ways. And at the end, they are on the steps at the ghats of the

02:24:41.160 --> 02:24:47.600
[Amit Varma]: river. And that's the first time you see them in one frame. And it's a beautiful moment.

02:24:47.600 --> 02:24:51.560
[Amit Varma]: And I would have ended the film there. Now, how a typical Bollywood treatment of the film

02:24:51.560 --> 02:24:56.280
[Amit Varma]: would have been is that you show them talking, coming together, all kinds of things happen,

02:24:56.280 --> 02:25:01.360
[Amit Varma]: they get married happily ever after. Basically, you spell everything out. The way Neeraj and

02:25:01.360 --> 02:25:06.160
[Amit Varma]: Varun treated it is that they talk to each other briefly, and they get on a boat, and

02:25:06.160 --> 02:25:10.160
[Amit Varma]: then the boat sails away. And then there's a song where the first two lines of the lyric

02:25:10.160 --> 02:25:14.680
[Amit Varma]: indicate something to the effect of life not ending the world continuing, which spells

02:25:14.680 --> 02:25:19.680
[Amit Varma]: it out a little more than I would have, but in an elusive way. And it's not as you know,

02:25:19.680 --> 02:25:24.400
[Amit Varma]: the Bollywood kind of thing. And what's and I of course, as you know, Jai, we discussed

02:25:24.400 --> 02:25:29.560
[Amit Varma]: it last time, I sort of have a bias towards, you know, being allowed to think for myself

02:25:29.560 --> 02:25:34.160
[Amit Varma]: and not being spoon fed in the typical Bollywood way would be spoon fed you in every way, you

02:25:34.160 --> 02:25:38.680
[Amit Varma]: know, show you everything that happens, put background music that forces you to feel in

02:25:38.680 --> 02:25:42.560
[Amit Varma]: a particular way, all of that. And I remember Jai, you pointed out that one of my favorite

02:25:42.560 --> 02:25:47.400
[Amit Varma]: films, Moonlight actually does have a lot of interesting background music happening,

02:25:47.400 --> 02:25:53.520
[Amit Varma]: which therefore seems to go against what I'm saying. So I one, I'm wondering if it is simply

02:25:53.520 --> 02:25:59.560
[Amit Varma]: a question of taste? Or is it the case that as you watch more and more movies, you sort

02:25:59.560 --> 02:26:03.600
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, sometimes you might be in the state of mind where you're completely passive.

02:26:03.600 --> 02:26:08.800
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, there seems to be a continuum along complete passivity, where you're not

02:26:08.800 --> 02:26:13.760
[Amit Varma]: thinking for yourself, and a little bit of involvement where you are using your own imagination

02:26:13.760 --> 02:26:18.560
[Amit Varma]: and putting two and two together. And it seems to me that and perhaps it's my bias speaking,

02:26:18.560 --> 02:26:24.520
[Amit Varma]: but that the more powerful kind of art is where you allow the reader or the viewer to

02:26:24.520 --> 02:26:32.680
[Amit Varma]: be a participant in the sense of that and, you know, not kind of spoon feed them. So

02:26:32.680 --> 02:26:37.440
[Amit Varma]: and that changes the nature of the art that that plays to what the viewer might be wanting

02:26:37.440 --> 02:26:40.880
[Amit Varma]: at that moment. What are your feelings about this? Am I?

02:26:40.880 --> 02:26:45.800
[Guest 1]: I don't know, I feel like there are different ways of being a participant.

02:26:45.800 --> 02:26:48.720
[Amit Varma]: If you remember the film, how would you have ended it? By the way, just curious.

