[Guest 1]: So that is a different sort of participation as well.

02:30:14.480 --> 02:30:18.960
[Guest 1]: It's not just like, to me, at least it's not like, I'm just sitting back in the seat and

02:30:18.960 --> 02:30:23.520
[Guest 1]: you know, and Manmohan Desai is just sort of feeding me mishti doi or whatever and I'm

02:30:23.520 --> 02:30:28.960
[Guest 1]: just sort of just gulping it down without, without thinking about it, which is one of

02:30:28.960 --> 02:30:35.080
[Guest 1]: the reasons why I get a little defensive when when people use words like mindless, mindless

02:30:35.080 --> 02:30:40.160
[Guest 1]: entertainment for for mainstream films, because to me, or when when they say, oh, you know,

02:30:40.160 --> 02:30:45.080
[Guest 1]: you do by the default assumption is that with a Manmohan Desai film, you know, you just

02:30:45.080 --> 02:30:49.600
[Guest 1]: sort of you're just it's it doesn't require, you can sort of watch it leaving your brains

02:30:49.600 --> 02:30:50.600
[Guest 1]: at home or whatever.

02:30:50.600 --> 02:30:52.440
[Guest 1]: I need my brain for everything.

02:30:52.440 --> 02:30:53.440
[Guest 1]: I need my brain.

02:30:53.440 --> 02:30:57.240
[Guest 1]: I mean, I'd be very afraid of misplacing it.

02:30:57.240 --> 02:31:02.320
[Guest 1]: I need to have it in here for every sort of experience, whether it's the the Tarkovsky

02:31:02.320 --> 02:31:07.520
[Guest 1]: experience or the Manmohan Desai experience, there are different forms of engagement.

02:31:07.520 --> 02:31:13.080
[Guest 1]: And I don't really, I've never seen myself as a passive viewer with any film that I've

02:31:13.080 --> 02:31:17.880
[Guest 1]: truly enjoyed, no matter what category of film it is.

02:31:17.880 --> 02:31:21.520
[Amit Varma]: Image of Manmohan Desai spoon feeding you is, won't leave my mind for a while.

02:31:21.520 --> 02:31:23.880
[Guest 1]: It would be the Sarulak in 1978.

02:31:23.880 --> 02:31:27.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I don't know what Manmohanji would have made of that.

02:31:27.400 --> 02:31:28.400
[Amit Varma]: But but I buy your point.

02:31:28.400 --> 02:31:31.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, in a sense, everything is spoon feeding to an extent, because every choice has been

02:31:31.920 --> 02:31:32.920
[Amit Varma]: made for a reason.

02:31:32.920 --> 02:31:36.360
[Amit Varma]: Camera yaha hai, waha nahi hai, that itself has been made for a reason.

02:31:36.360 --> 02:31:41.440
[Amit Varma]: And I guess it's a question of degrees and quibbling and, you know, all of that.

02:31:41.440 --> 02:31:42.760
[Amit Varma]: Subrata, what's your take on it?

02:31:42.760 --> 02:31:48.120
[Amit Varma]: Because you watch the because you are a lover of both the most overstated Bollywood films

02:31:48.120 --> 02:31:53.440
[Amit Varma]: as well as the most understated and quote unquote, realistic international films.

02:31:53.440 --> 02:31:58.240
[Amit Varma]: How do like, do you have to mode shift from one to the other to appreciate them as they

02:31:58.240 --> 02:31:59.240
[Amit Varma]: are meant to be appreciated?

02:31:59.240 --> 02:32:00.600
[Guest 2]: Or how does it work?

02:32:00.600 --> 02:32:01.600
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

02:32:01.600 --> 02:32:06.280
[Guest 2]: So I think, you know, just picking on picking up from where Jay left, one of the things

02:32:06.280 --> 02:32:13.920
[Guest 2]: that should be there is just the within the film itself, it should have, you know, integrity,

02:32:13.920 --> 02:32:14.920
[Guest 2]: right?

02:32:14.920 --> 02:32:20.080
[Guest 2]: So that it should not be uneven within the film, because that's, then you know that you

02:32:20.080 --> 02:32:24.040
[Guest 2]: are in for this experience, and the director is giving you all of that.

02:32:24.040 --> 02:32:29.400
[Guest 2]: And he's not, you know, thematically not, you know, sort of going in different directions

02:32:29.400 --> 02:32:30.400
[Guest 2]: within the same film.

02:32:30.400 --> 02:32:35.640
[Guest 2]: And I think that's very important, because then you can enjoy it, you know, just as a

02:32:35.640 --> 02:32:36.960
[Guest 2]: single piece of work.

02:32:36.960 --> 02:32:44.200
[Guest 2]: So, like Jay mentioned on Masaan, you were watching a certain sensibility right through

02:32:44.200 --> 02:32:45.200
[Guest 2]: the film.

02:32:45.200 --> 02:32:49.880
[Guest 2]: And therefore, the ending could not have been a different one, and maybe you could quibble

02:32:49.880 --> 02:32:55.000
[Guest 2]: about, could they have pulled back a little bit more, I think where they left it was,

02:32:55.000 --> 02:32:59.520
[Guest 2]: in some sense, still consistent with the overall sensibility that the film had.

02:32:59.520 --> 02:33:03.340
[Guest 2]: And then therefore, Manmohan Desai is completely consistent, right?

02:33:03.340 --> 02:33:06.000
[Guest 2]: And therefore, not mindless at all.

02:33:06.000 --> 02:33:12.800
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, people don't appreciate, there was a time in 76, four Manmohan Desai

02:33:12.800 --> 02:33:15.000
[Guest 2]: films were running at the same time.

02:33:15.000 --> 02:33:17.720
[Guest 2]: I don't know when the guy made those four films together.

02:33:17.720 --> 02:33:18.720
[Guest 1]: Which ones?

02:33:18.720 --> 02:33:23.320
[Guest 1]: There was Chacha Bhatija, Parvaresh, Shama, Amar Akbar, Antony and Dharamveer.

02:33:23.320 --> 02:33:25.840
[Guest 2]: So it would have been 77 actually.

02:33:25.840 --> 02:33:26.840
[Guest 2]: 77.

02:33:26.840 --> 02:33:27.840
[Guest 2]: 77.

02:33:27.840 --> 02:33:28.840
[Guest 2]: All four films.

02:33:28.840 --> 02:33:34.240
[Guest 2]: And, you know, it was like a combination of characters, I mean, it was same, there was

02:33:34.240 --> 02:33:39.840
[Guest 2]: Amitabh, there was Vinod Khanna, in somewhere there was Dharmendra, somewhere there was

02:33:39.840 --> 02:33:43.480
[Guest 2]: Randhir Kapoor and Dharmendra, Chacha Bhatija.

02:33:43.480 --> 02:33:46.560
[Guest 2]: So all different films.

02:33:46.560 --> 02:33:52.000
[Guest 2]: I remember watching these films at different times in my life, you know, mostly mid to

02:33:52.000 --> 02:33:53.000
[Guest 2]: late 80s.

02:33:53.000 --> 02:33:58.960
[Guest 2]: And much later, I realized the guy was making all these four films simultaneously, all great

02:33:58.960 --> 02:33:59.960
[Guest 2]: entertaining films.

02:33:59.960 --> 02:34:08.840
[Guest 2]: I mean, Parvaresh is all these, you know, one, it's like Nature, Nurture, one brother,

02:34:08.840 --> 02:34:14.360
[Guest 2]: other brother, all those kind of stuff happening, Chacha Bhatija is complete sort of, you know,

02:34:14.360 --> 02:34:18.320
[Guest 2]: two tricksters and things of that kind.

02:34:18.320 --> 02:34:21.720
[Guest 2]: And within themselves, they are fully consistent.

02:34:21.720 --> 02:34:23.000
[Guest 2]: So that's one point.

02:34:23.000 --> 02:34:30.700
[Guest 2]: The other point is, there is some cultural context to, you know, where the film is being

02:34:30.700 --> 02:34:32.200
[Guest 2]: made and who's watching it.

02:34:32.200 --> 02:34:38.400
[Guest 2]: And I sometimes think that while there is a lot of universal sort of thing about watching

02:34:38.400 --> 02:34:44.040
[Guest 2]: a good film, good cinema everywhere, I mean, a good cinema being good cinema everywhere.

02:34:44.040 --> 02:34:52.480
[Guest 2]: So a good example of this is this, you know, this Man, Woman and Child, this Eric Segal's

02:34:52.480 --> 02:35:00.520
[Guest 2]: book and then that was made into a film and Shekhar Kapoor made it into Masoom.

02:35:00.520 --> 02:35:05.840
[Guest 2]: Had he kept that ending of Man, Woman and Child in India, it would have been, you know,

02:35:05.840 --> 02:35:11.120
[Guest 2]: it was not a mega box office hit, but it was a very well received popular film.

02:35:11.120 --> 02:35:14.480
[Guest 2]: But I mean, again, this is 40 years back, so no spoilers here.

02:35:14.480 --> 02:35:22.240
[Guest 2]: So, you know, in the original book, the Jugal Hansraj character doesn't stay back.

02:35:22.240 --> 02:35:30.120
[Guest 2]: He is sent off to the, you know, the boarding school, although the mother, you know, accepts

02:35:30.120 --> 02:35:33.240
[Guest 2]: the fact that he's there, but he goes back.

02:35:33.240 --> 02:35:41.320
[Guest 2]: Whereas in Masoom, they accept Jugal Hansraj and he stays back as part of the family.

02:35:41.320 --> 02:35:45.920
[Guest 2]: I think, you know, that you could not have done that.

02:35:45.920 --> 02:35:51.520
[Guest 2]: And maybe in the US, Indian ending would have felt ki yeh kuch zyada kar diya, yaar aisa

02:35:51.520 --> 02:35:53.080
[Guest 2]: koi nahi karta hai.

02:35:53.080 --> 02:35:58.600
[Guest 2]: Whereas in India, we needed that at the end, that emotional sort of closure.

02:35:58.600 --> 02:36:03.360
[Guest 2]: I mean, I would not have accepted that film if they would have sent him back.

02:36:03.360 --> 02:36:05.880
[Guest 2]: But you would have thought about it more after it was over.

02:36:05.880 --> 02:36:11.120
[Guest 2]: Maybe, but I would have been so disgusted with the idea that they sent him back.

02:36:11.120 --> 02:36:16.240
[Guest 2]: Because I mean, you know, at different times in that film, you're so invested in the, in

02:36:16.240 --> 02:36:19.360
[Guest 2]: that boy and you know, his story and everything.

02:36:19.360 --> 02:36:21.520
[Guest 2]: You didn't want anything bad to happen.

02:36:21.520 --> 02:36:25.560
[Guest 2]: I mean, I remember that film, even I think I watched it five, six years back, not the

02:36:25.560 --> 02:36:29.760
[Guest 2]: whole film, there was something was happening, I was just watching it, there is a particular

02:36:29.760 --> 02:36:34.720
[Guest 2]: scene at the later part, in the later part of the film where this young Jugal actually,

02:36:34.720 --> 02:36:36.800
[Guest 2]: you know, cuts his hand with a knife.

02:36:36.800 --> 02:36:43.080
[Guest 2]: And he winces in pain and immediately runs, but he knows that he's not having, you know,

02:36:43.080 --> 02:36:45.240
[Guest 2]: Shabana's sympathy in any case.

02:36:45.240 --> 02:36:49.080
[Guest 2]: And Shabana looks at him, he wants to tell her, but then he knows that he will get no

02:36:49.080 --> 02:36:50.080
[Guest 2]: sympathy.

02:36:50.080 --> 02:36:54.280
[Guest 2]: So he just puts his hand behind and doesn't tell that he's actually cut his hand, right?

02:36:54.280 --> 02:36:57.800
[Guest 2]: It really broke my heart even after so many years while watching that.

02:36:57.800 --> 02:37:02.960
[Guest 2]: Uske baad agar usko phir bhej doge, I would have never accepted the film.

02:37:02.960 --> 02:37:09.560
[Guest 2]: So I think there are certain choices, which some of the directors will have to, you know,

02:37:09.560 --> 02:37:14.240
[Guest 2]: offer based on just what they think is right for themselves, because they are, they are

02:37:14.240 --> 02:37:17.440
[Guest 2]: part of a particular milieu, they have grown up in a particular cultural context, and they

02:37:17.440 --> 02:37:18.440
[Guest 2]: know their audience.

02:37:18.440 --> 02:37:22.120
[Guest 2]: And in some of them, I think we will be different.

02:37:22.120 --> 02:37:26.240
[Guest 2]: And therefore, there is some merit in saying that Indian films will be of a certain kind.

02:37:26.240 --> 02:37:31.880
[Guest 2]: I mean, some of us, maybe you Amit, might not otherwise have that Indian sensibility

02:37:31.880 --> 02:37:36.960
[Guest 2]: in general, because of the, you know, some of your, you know, past, etc.

02:37:36.960 --> 02:37:38.760
[Guest 2]: Par logon ko chahiye yaar wo.

02:37:38.760 --> 02:37:42.800
[Guest 1]: Well, I think there's also within India, there are just so many cultures and subcultures

02:37:42.800 --> 02:37:47.480
[Guest 1]: anyway, you know, I mean, it's, it also depends on the type of film we're talking about.

02:37:47.480 --> 02:37:53.120
[Guest 1]: Masoom is actually somewhat difficult to classify film in some ways, but yeah, broadly speaking,

02:37:53.120 --> 02:37:59.320
[Guest 1]: it is from a tradition of the dramatic, the emotion soaked film, even though it's got

02:37:59.320 --> 02:38:03.440
[Guest 1]: Naseer and Shabana in it, and it was made in that period.

02:38:03.440 --> 02:38:07.160
[Guest 1]: But around the same time, the stuff that Shyam Vennigal was making, or Govind Elani was making,

02:38:07.160 --> 02:38:14.120
[Guest 1]: was, of course, representative of a different Indian aesthetic or sensibility.

02:38:14.120 --> 02:38:19.960
[Guest 1]: And of course, that's without even getting into the many non-Hindi films from around

02:38:19.960 --> 02:38:20.960
[Guest 1]: the country.

02:38:20.960 --> 02:38:25.200
[Guest 1]: So of course, that's, and today, of course, as you know, there's just so many different

02:38:25.200 --> 02:38:32.800
[Guest 1]: types of Indian films or web series or whatever from the 200 crore blockbusters that we think

02:38:32.800 --> 02:38:37.960
[Guest 1]: of as sort of catering to the lowest common denominator or whatever, to the Hindi film,

02:38:37.960 --> 02:38:42.760
[Guest 1]: to the South Indian films, whatever, it's just so much.

02:38:42.760 --> 02:38:49.320
[Guest 1]: So I'm not sure there really is such a thing as an Indian film in that sense anymore.

02:38:49.320 --> 02:38:55.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, see, like, for instance, some of our early, whatever you call it, this parallel

02:38:55.680 --> 02:38:58.520
[Guest 2]: cinema movement guys, right?

02:38:58.520 --> 02:39:05.600
[Guest 2]: Money Call, Kumar Sahani kind of characters, greatly influenced by, especially by Bresson.

02:39:05.600 --> 02:39:12.960
[Guest 2]: I've also seen Pickpocket, I've seen Ghadhe Ka Kahani.

02:39:12.960 --> 02:39:15.080
[Amit Varma]: Ohazad Balthazar was a damn good film.

02:39:15.080 --> 02:39:16.080
[Amit Varma]: I'm very offended.

02:39:16.080 --> 02:39:17.080
[Guest 1]: But anyway.

02:39:17.080 --> 02:39:20.480
[Guest 1]: And baby donkeys are pretty much the cutest animals there are.

02:39:20.480 --> 02:39:21.840
[Amit Varma]: Sorry to have hurt both of you.

02:39:21.840 --> 02:39:28.560
[Amit Varma]: I have no experience with baby donkeys, but okay, okay, okay.

02:39:28.560 --> 02:39:36.240
[Guest 2]: But then, Money Call comes back and makes, you know, Uski Roti or Ashaad.

02:39:36.240 --> 02:39:40.560
[Amit Varma]: Can I quickly disturb you, sorry, to tell you this great story by a former guest on

02:39:40.560 --> 02:39:43.040
[Amit Varma]: my show, Naren Shannoy.

02:39:43.040 --> 02:39:48.480
[Amit Varma]: So Naren Shannoy has a story that around the time Money Call ki Uski Roti came out, they

02:39:48.480 --> 02:39:53.000
[Amit Varma]: had got a TV in the house, or antenna upar tha, but kabhi kabhi there would be a storm

02:39:53.000 --> 02:39:56.960
[Amit Varma]: and then people would have to go and they would have to mess around with the antenna

02:39:56.960 --> 02:39:57.960
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

02:39:57.960 --> 02:40:03.200
[Amit Varma]: To Money Call ki Uski Roti TV pe aaye, I assume it was one of these Tosca things, film aaye

02:40:03.200 --> 02:40:04.960
[Amit Varma]: abhi toh dekhna hai.

02:40:04.960 --> 02:40:09.200
[Amit Varma]: And so they sat down, they're watching the film and suddenly the screen freezes.

02:40:09.200 --> 02:40:11.600
[Amit Varma]: A few seconds pass, the screen is frozen.

02:40:11.600 --> 02:40:16.520
[Amit Varma]: So immediately, boy is dispatched upstairs, uncle is leaning out of the window, the boy

02:40:16.520 --> 02:40:20.960
[Amit Varma]: is moving the antenna here and there and shouting, theek hua ki nahi, and uncle is saying nahi

02:40:20.960 --> 02:40:23.520
[Amit Varma]: thora left try karo, thora right try karo.

02:40:23.520 --> 02:40:28.080
[Amit Varma]: After half an hour they discover antenna ka fault nahi tha, TV ka fault nahi tha, it was

02:40:28.080 --> 02:40:29.080
[Amit Varma]: a film.

02:40:29.080 --> 02:40:30.480
[Amit Varma]: So ki Money Call ne waise hi banayi.

02:40:30.480 --> 02:40:35.120
[Amit Varma]: And all I remember of Uski Roti is that the sound was out of sync at one point and I asked

02:40:35.120 --> 02:40:38.920
[Amit Varma]: my father what's going on because I must have been watching it with him back then.

02:40:38.920 --> 02:40:42.960
[Unknown]: And he was like, no, no, this is a film, you're supposed to appreciate it.

02:40:42.960 --> 02:40:43.960
[Guest 1]: So anyway, I'm sorry.

02:40:43.960 --> 02:40:49.600
[Guest 1]: You shouldn't have called the antenna guy, you should have called call, better call call.

02:40:49.600 --> 02:40:55.320
[Guest 1]: No, but very quickly, sorry, we are just going on interrupting you Subrath, but that reminds

02:40:55.320 --> 02:41:02.920
[Guest 1]: me of watching Goddard's Perele Phu at Plaza Cinema in Delhi back in the 90s.

02:41:02.920 --> 02:41:08.000
[Guest 1]: And very poor projection, generally the International Film Festival of India was going on.

02:41:08.000 --> 02:41:13.440
[Guest 1]: But because this is a Goddard film, and we were all primed for, we had seen Goddard films.

02:41:13.440 --> 02:41:17.280
[Guest 1]: At one point, the screen sort of just goes completely out of whack, you know, this is

02:41:17.280 --> 02:41:22.600
[Guest 1]: sort of it becomes like a split screen with part of it going down and the bottom half

02:41:22.600 --> 02:41:24.240
[Guest 1]: going to the top half, etc.

02:41:24.240 --> 02:41:28.560
[Guest 1]: And we sat there for two minutes, sort of around 80% sure it was deliberate.

02:41:28.560 --> 02:41:32.840
[Guest 1]: It was part of the film, you know, just sitting with this sort of this hallowed sort of expression

02:41:32.840 --> 02:41:33.840
[Guest 1]: on our faces.

02:41:33.840 --> 02:41:39.520
[Guest 1]: It's the reverse Narendra Nooyi story.

02:41:39.520 --> 02:41:40.720
[Guest 1]: And then of course, it got corrected.

02:41:40.720 --> 02:41:43.520
[Guest 1]: And then it became a very sort of very standard.

02:41:43.520 --> 02:41:48.560
[Amit Varma]: Goddard, there was himself watching that and thinking, hmm, that's what I should have done.

02:41:48.560 --> 02:41:49.560
[Unknown]: This would have been better.

02:41:49.560 --> 02:41:50.560
[Guest 2]: This would have been better.

02:41:50.560 --> 02:41:51.560
[Guest 2]: Sorry.

02:41:51.560 --> 02:41:58.600
[Guest 2]: Anyway, I mean, the point is, oh, you watch Kumar Shani's Maya Darpan or Uski Roti, Aashad

02:41:58.600 --> 02:42:00.160
[Guest 2]: ka Ek Din or whatever.

02:42:00.160 --> 02:42:05.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, I was it's difficult to have that in the Indian context.

02:42:05.680 --> 02:42:11.680
[Guest 2]: I think there was something happening then in France, maybe that kind of stuff was even

02:42:11.680 --> 02:42:12.680
[Guest 2]: popular.

02:42:12.680 --> 02:42:21.960
[Guest 2]: I mean, you could watch it, but and you knew maybe there is something happening here.

02:42:21.960 --> 02:42:30.560
[Guest 2]: But you know, so while whatever Shyam Benegal was doing and even what Mrinal Sen was doing,

02:42:30.560 --> 02:42:31.560
[Guest 2]: they were doing it at the same time.

02:42:31.560 --> 02:42:38.800
[Guest 2]: I mean, the early 70s, you know, Benegal just was starting off and Mrinal Sen had possibly

02:42:38.800 --> 02:42:40.840
[Guest 2]: the Calcutta Trilogy at that time.

02:42:40.840 --> 02:42:45.360
[Guest 2]: There were good films, I mean, you didn't have to do what Bresson was doing in India

02:42:45.360 --> 02:42:46.360
[Guest 2]: with this.

02:42:46.360 --> 02:42:48.360
[Guest 2]: You could still make good, good films.

02:42:48.360 --> 02:42:52.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, I never understood that phase, for instance, you know, I can watch an interview

02:42:52.680 --> 02:42:59.880
[Guest 2]: of Mrinal Sen or whatever Calcutta 71, I mean, but, you know, watching Uski Roti again is

02:42:59.880 --> 02:43:00.880
[Guest 2]: very tough.

02:43:00.880 --> 02:43:05.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, not very tough, I'll never watch it again, but so I think there is some something

02:43:05.920 --> 02:43:06.920
[Guest 2]: is there.

02:43:06.920 --> 02:43:12.440
[Guest 2]: So there is some aspect of storytelling, etc, that appeals to us, I have a feeling.

02:43:12.440 --> 02:43:17.520
[Guest 1]: No, no, I have to also say, you know, much as I like to, it's like a confession time

02:43:17.520 --> 02:43:23.440
[Guest 1]: in a way, much as I like to, and I also take pride in the fact that I love many different

02:43:23.440 --> 02:43:28.640
[Guest 1]: types of films, you know, across a very wide spectrum, there are certain filmmakers that

02:43:28.640 --> 02:43:33.080
[Guest 1]: I find very difficult, even today, I mean, I find Tarkovsky difficult.

02:43:33.080 --> 02:43:37.240
[Guest 1]: And I wish I didn't, because I really sort of feel like there's a part of me that, you

02:43:37.240 --> 02:43:41.840
[Guest 1]: know, with a couple of his films, there's a part of me that does manage to click into

02:43:41.840 --> 02:43:46.400
[Guest 1]: the admire the film without quite liking it mode.

02:43:46.400 --> 02:43:50.600
[Guest 1]: But that's not a mode I like to be in, because I feel like it's a bit pretentious then and

02:43:50.600 --> 02:43:54.300
[Guest 1]: when it comes back to what you said that, you know, you need to sort of to some degree

02:43:54.300 --> 02:43:59.400
[Guest 1]: trust your initial, you know, experience of something, and you let it wash over, you know,

02:43:59.400 --> 02:44:06.160
[Guest 1]: so, you know, what would I do if I were asked to sit and write a piece about Ivan's childhood

02:44:06.160 --> 02:44:07.160
[Guest 1]: or something?

02:44:07.160 --> 02:44:09.160
[Guest 1]: How would I write it?

02:44:09.160 --> 02:44:16.360
[Guest 1]: I mean, honestly, if I sort of, you know, in some very detached cerebral way, I appreciated

02:44:16.360 --> 02:44:21.920
[Guest 1]: the film appreciated that here is a serious artist doing, you know, realizing his vision,

02:44:21.920 --> 02:44:26.520
[Guest 1]: but at an emotional level, it really didn't work for me, I was sort of, you know, befuddled

02:44:26.520 --> 02:44:28.280
[Guest 1]: by it a little bored by it.

02:44:28.280 --> 02:44:29.560
[Guest 1]: How do I write about it?

02:44:29.560 --> 02:44:33.080
[Guest 1]: It is a question that that that even today, you know, after more than 20 years of being

02:44:33.080 --> 02:44:36.560
[Guest 1]: a professional writer, I don't really know the answer to.

02:44:36.560 --> 02:44:41.000
[Guest 1]: So these things are, you know, these are, you know, you're, you can spend a lifetime

02:44:41.000 --> 02:44:45.040
[Guest 1]: watching films, thinking about them, engaging with them, but there are always questions

02:44:45.040 --> 02:44:49.960
[Guest 1]: that will be unanswered about the watching experience and, and the sort of viewer that

02:44:49.960 --> 02:44:55.280
[Guest 1]: you are, and how to deal with a particular sort of film.

02:44:55.280 --> 02:45:01.080
[Guest 2]: I think on, on Tarkovsky, I mean, the only film that I mean, I've gone through the same

02:45:01.080 --> 02:45:02.080
[Guest 2]: problem.

02:45:02.080 --> 02:45:07.760
[Guest 2]: Let's say legend has reached to you, you have to appreciate this, so you have not organically

02:45:07.760 --> 02:45:09.080
[Guest 2]: discovered it.

02:45:09.080 --> 02:45:10.080
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:45:10.080 --> 02:45:17.080
[Guest 2]: So I think the only thing that the only film where I could sort of get in fully was Solaris.

02:45:17.080 --> 02:45:18.080
[Unknown]: Likewise.

02:45:18.080 --> 02:45:21.960
[Guest 2]: Because there was a, you know, story to it.

02:45:21.960 --> 02:45:28.640
[Guest 2]: And I think a large part of that credit is to that Stanislavsky, I think that that was

02:45:28.640 --> 02:45:30.880
[Guest 2]: the writer who wrote the original science fiction thing.

02:45:30.880 --> 02:45:33.680
[Guest 2]: So you could figure that thing out, right?

02:45:33.680 --> 02:45:37.520
[Guest 2]: After that, you know, Andrew Rublev or Mirror or something, I mean,

02:45:37.520 --> 02:45:54.400
[Unknown]: every dialogue is like, if I could say in three words, why not 30, Zeenat Aman's father,

02:45:54.400 --> 02:45:56.400
[Guest 2]: by the way, scriptwriter.

02:45:56.400 --> 02:45:57.400
[Guest 2]: Wonderful.

02:45:57.400 --> 02:45:58.400
[Guest 2]: Sorry, who?

02:45:58.400 --> 02:45:59.400
[Guest 2]: Zeenat Aman's father, Aman.

02:45:59.400 --> 02:46:00.400
[Guest 2]: One of the scriptwriters.

02:46:00.400 --> 02:46:07.680
[Guest 2]: I thought he was saying Stanislavsky's Lem was the father of Zeenat Aman.

02:46:07.680 --> 02:46:10.360
[Guest 2]: That would have been quite a connection.

02:46:10.360 --> 02:46:17.440
[Guest 2]: I was saying Mughal-e-Azam, where three words would do 30 would be used.

02:46:17.440 --> 02:46:23.760
[Amit Varma]: So Subrat, let's with a nod to linearity, if that's how you pronounce it, let's get

02:46:23.760 --> 02:46:29.280
[Amit Varma]: back to your sort of story, where eventually, you know, you were one of the driving forces

02:46:29.280 --> 02:46:33.360
[Amit Varma]: behind Passion for Cinema at one point in time, you got in with the filmmaking crowd

02:46:33.360 --> 02:46:35.440
[Amit Varma]: of that time, and you wanted to make movies yourself.

02:46:35.440 --> 02:46:37.960
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that.

02:46:37.960 --> 02:46:40.640
[Guest 2]: Tell us a little bit about that.

02:46:40.640 --> 02:46:45.600
[Guest 2]: Just to set the record straight, driving force would be a huge exaggeration of what I was

02:46:45.600 --> 02:46:46.600
[Guest 2]: doing there.

02:46:46.600 --> 02:46:51.400
[Guest 2]: I mean, there were, I mean, just to go back to some of the origin story of that.

02:46:51.400 --> 02:46:57.320
[Guest 2]: And for those who came in late, Passion for Cinema was a blogging site, where a lot of

02:46:57.320 --> 02:47:02.920
[Guest 2]: people came in and wrote about cinema, with somewhat of a laissez-faire sort of attitude

02:47:02.920 --> 02:47:03.920
[Guest 2]: to quality of writing.

02:47:03.920 --> 02:47:10.560
[Guest 2]: So, initially, we were like, okay, now we'll be a bit, you know, the original plan, of

02:47:10.560 --> 02:47:15.760
[Unknown]: course, for any of this is Cahiers du Cinma, we will make it.

02:47:15.760 --> 02:47:20.880
[Unknown]: Then from there, that dream came true.

02:47:20.880 --> 02:47:26.760
[Guest 2]: But I mean, the initial thing was, you know, there was a guy who was writing on cinema

02:47:26.760 --> 02:47:32.640
[Guest 2]: sitting in the US, went by the sort of a name Oz.

02:47:32.640 --> 02:47:36.440
[Guest 2]: And then a few other people started sort of, you know, commenting on his blog.

02:47:36.440 --> 02:47:38.160
[Guest 2]: And then, you know, things came together.

02:47:38.160 --> 02:47:42.040
[Guest 2]: And then, you know, the idea was, we'll do something called Passion for Cinema.

02:47:42.040 --> 02:47:48.360
[Guest 2]: And I think, you know, both of you, I used to follow both of your blogs at that time.

02:47:48.360 --> 02:47:54.520
[Guest 2]: It was a moment for blogging in India, right, with everyone doing something interesting

02:47:54.520 --> 02:47:58.920
[Guest 2]: in that, I think the two of you, there was Sepia Mutiny, and I used to follow all of

02:47:58.920 --> 02:47:59.920
[Guest 2]: them.

02:47:59.920 --> 02:48:04.920
[Guest 2]: So, we, seven, eight of us initially started writing.

02:48:04.920 --> 02:48:07.320
[Guest 2]: And everyone had a particular niche.

02:48:07.320 --> 02:48:15.000
[Guest 2]: My kind of niche was sort of humorous take on sort of social issues through the lens

02:48:15.000 --> 02:48:20.040
[Guest 2]: of some old Hindi film or song or something and then do random connections in between

02:48:20.040 --> 02:48:23.880
[Guest 2]: Pyaasa and some other, you know, film.

02:48:23.880 --> 02:48:31.240
[Guest 2]: And then I used to have this sort of a, you know, character called Professor, you know,

02:48:31.240 --> 02:48:34.120
[Guest 2]: who would answer questions of people.

02:48:34.120 --> 02:48:38.640
[Guest 2]: And so, somebody would ask a question on what is noir and the professor, I mean, it would

02:48:38.640 --> 02:48:43.440
[Guest 2]: all be sort of laced with some kind of humor and, you know, that kind of stuff.

02:48:43.440 --> 02:48:45.960
[Guest 2]: But you know, seven, eight of us would write.

02:48:45.960 --> 02:48:52.440
[Guest 2]: And then what happened was, just because that there was that kind of a platform that platform

02:48:52.440 --> 02:48:58.160
[Guest 2]: was gaining salience, some people started coming in and writing and one of the big names

02:48:58.160 --> 02:49:02.720
[Guest 2]: and not big then, but clearly someone who had a point of view at that point in time

02:49:02.720 --> 02:49:07.600
[Guest 2]: was Anurag Kashyap, who came in and started writing, so he had his own corner.

02:49:07.600 --> 02:49:13.920
[Guest 2]: And you know, he came and wrote firstly about the making of Black Friday and just the fact

02:49:13.920 --> 02:49:17.240
[Guest 2]: that it wasn't released for a long period of time.

02:49:17.240 --> 02:49:23.280
[Guest 2]: And he wrote it really well, I mean, just you could feel the angst of a person who has

02:49:23.280 --> 02:49:27.760
[Guest 2]: made something good, but was not getting a release and if you sort of combined it with

02:49:27.760 --> 02:49:32.840
[Guest 2]: the fact that Punch was not released as well before that, I think it touched a sort of,

02:49:32.840 --> 02:49:34.240
[Guest 2]: you know, chord with a whole lot of people.

02:49:34.240 --> 02:49:39.440
[Guest 2]: So, you know, just started getting a large number of people reading it.

02:49:39.440 --> 02:49:42.880
[Guest 2]: And then since all of us were also writing stuff, you know, people started engaging with

02:49:42.880 --> 02:49:48.040
[Guest 2]: other content, and then just it just took off, I mean, you know, by the sort of sixth

02:49:48.040 --> 02:49:53.200
[Guest 2]: or the seventh month, we were getting more than a million page views and stuff.

02:49:53.200 --> 02:50:00.480
[Guest 2]: I mean, we would then sort of write in started, at least I am always ready to play to the

02:50:00.480 --> 02:50:04.760
[Guest 2]: gallery, start writing stuff so that you could get 100 comments and you know, those became

02:50:04.760 --> 02:50:09.080
[Guest 2]: metrics that how to write so that you get 100 comments, I have a complete Manmohan Desai

02:50:09.080 --> 02:50:10.080
[Guest 2]: at heart.

02:50:10.080 --> 02:50:15.840
[Guest 2]: So, it was great fun and then, you know, because of Anurag, others started coming in, you know,

02:50:15.840 --> 02:50:22.640
[Guest 2]: gradually you had, you know, Navdeep, Sudhir Mishra, you know, and then, you know, people

02:50:22.640 --> 02:50:25.880
[Guest 2]: would write about some of their iconic work and how that got made.

02:50:25.880 --> 02:50:30.600
[Guest 2]: So, it just started becoming a bit of, you know, history, process of filmmaking, and

02:50:30.600 --> 02:50:38.200
[Guest 2]: we started running a one minute short festival, people would upload their short films and

02:50:38.200 --> 02:50:40.800
[Guest 2]: someone Anurag and others would judge it.

02:50:40.800 --> 02:50:45.040
[Guest 2]: Some of the guys who won that then would get an internship with Anurag and some of them

02:50:45.040 --> 02:50:47.320
[Guest 2]: became big, you know.

02:50:47.320 --> 02:50:55.280
[Guest 2]: And so, that whole thing between 2007 to 2009 was just phenomenally, you know, energizing

02:50:55.280 --> 02:50:59.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, and there's just so much of talent coming in.

02:50:59.920 --> 02:51:03.520
[Guest 2]: And maybe it was always the case that Bombay was attracting some kind of talent, but you

02:51:03.520 --> 02:51:07.760
[Guest 2]: know, just that platform made it somewhat more democratic than what it was in the past.

02:51:07.760 --> 02:51:12.080
[Guest 2]: In the past, you would stand outside famous studio, Mehboob studio, RK studio, bribe the

02:51:12.080 --> 02:51:18.160
[Guest 2]: watchman and then go in and have a cup of tea and try and, you know, get an audience.

02:51:18.160 --> 02:51:23.240
[Guest 2]: But here, you know, somebody could come in, do something, write a good, I mean, there

02:51:23.240 --> 02:51:24.920
[Guest 2]: have been cases of that kind, right?

02:51:24.920 --> 02:51:30.200
[Guest 2]: People would come, write something good, write two, three times and something and then Anurag

02:51:30.200 --> 02:51:34.920
[Guest 2]: would say, let's have a Bombay meetup and then people would land up there and some two

02:51:34.920 --> 02:51:38.520
[Guest 2]: other filmmakers or young filmmakers would come and then two of them would click and

02:51:38.520 --> 02:51:43.600
[Guest 2]: this guy would start assisting him, which is exactly what happened with Neeraj for instance,

02:51:43.600 --> 02:51:48.520
[Guest 2]: it's exactly how Varun possibly wrote a few things and got in and a lot of other cases.

02:51:48.520 --> 02:51:54.600
[Guest 2]: I mean, the early, in the early days, Chaitanya Tamhane, all these people were there, Rajkumar,

02:51:54.600 --> 02:52:00.800
[Guest 2]: what's Rajkumar's full name now, the guy who made No One Killed Jessica, I forget the name.

02:52:00.800 --> 02:52:06.240
[Unknown]: Rajkumar Gupta.

02:52:06.240 --> 02:52:19.600
[Unknown]: But you know, my taste, Rajkumar Kohli, Rajkumar Kohli, have you seen the Rajkumar Kohli canon,

02:52:19.600 --> 02:52:21.480
[Guest 2]: any movie of that canon?

02:52:21.480 --> 02:52:26.160
[Guest 1]: Name the movies, I've seen Nagin for sure.

02:52:26.160 --> 02:52:31.600
[Guest 1]: Nagin was with Sridevi, Reena Roy, Reena Roy, Rekha, lots of people.

02:52:31.600 --> 02:52:35.960
[Guest 1]: But I think I might have seen it also, it's not Nigahe, which was the one in which Sridevi

02:52:35.960 --> 02:52:36.960
[Guest 2]: was a snake?

02:52:36.960 --> 02:52:37.960
[Guest 2]: Nagina.

02:52:37.960 --> 02:52:43.800
[Amit Varma]: Nagina is a slightly, I mean, Rani Dushman with Sanjeev Kumar as a werewolf, spoiler.

02:52:43.800 --> 02:52:47.800
[Amit Varma]: I haven't seen that, Sanjeev Kumar as a werewolf, I mean, quite a chilled out werewolf.

02:52:47.800 --> 02:52:52.400
[Guest 2]: Sanjeev Kumar as a werewolf, only preying on young dulhans.

02:52:52.400 --> 02:52:59.120
[Guest 2]: Yaar iski method acting kaise karte hoonge log?

02:52:59.120 --> 02:53:00.120
[Guest 2]: How do you prepare for this?

02:53:00.120 --> 02:53:05.120
[Guest 2]: Watch the, yeh sawaal toh, you don't ask when American werewolf in whatever.

02:53:05.120 --> 02:53:10.120
[Guest 1]: Listen, after this conversation, Amit's going to go and cleanse himself by watching Decalogue.

02:53:10.120 --> 02:53:14.120
[Unknown]: The whole Kislow sketch, three colours were red, blue, white.

02:53:14.120 --> 02:53:16.120
[Unknown]: Ek haft hai mujhe baith ke.

02:53:16.120 --> 02:53:19.120
[Amit Varma]: Double knife of Melonique, sab dekh raha hai.

02:53:19.120 --> 02:53:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Maza kura ho, maza kura ho, aur ho raha ho.

02:53:22.120 --> 02:53:23.120
[Amit Varma]: So haan, so you were saying?

02:53:23.120 --> 02:53:27.120
[Guest 2]: So yeah, so then, you know, we used to have meetups and there was, you know, this whole

02:53:27.120 --> 02:53:33.120
[Guest 2]: sort of, I mean, there was a certain, you know, what the French call free song in the

02:53:33.120 --> 02:53:34.120
[Guest 2]: air.

02:53:34.120 --> 02:53:39.120
[Guest 2]: Ho raha tha sab kuch, maza raha tha, people were bouncing off ideas with one another,

02:53:39.120 --> 02:53:42.120
[Guest 2]: you know, people are getting breaks and stuff of that kind.

02:53:42.120 --> 02:53:50.120
[Guest 2]: So, I mean, my general sort of role in all of this was, like, I've always seen myself

02:53:50.120 --> 02:53:53.120
[Guest 2]: as a consumer than creator.

02:53:53.120 --> 02:53:57.120
[Guest 2]: But I sort of fancied that I could write a little bit reasonably well.

02:53:57.120 --> 02:54:01.120
[Guest 2]: And since others were doing stuff, so sometimes, yeah, the thought did cross my mind ke kuch

02:54:01.120 --> 02:54:02.120
[Guest 2]: karte hain aisa.

02:54:02.120 --> 02:54:07.120
[Guest 2]: But, you know, you should have a good, strong enough pull.

02:54:07.120 --> 02:54:14.120
[Guest 2]: All my interests that I had in films and everything, I just never was pulled strongly enough.

02:54:14.120 --> 02:54:16.120
[Guest 2]: By pull, you mean your internal desire?

02:54:16.120 --> 02:54:17.120
[Guest 2]: Internal desire.

02:54:17.120 --> 02:54:22.120
[Guest 2]: Because, I mean, whatever work I was doing, I could see a lot of people were not, they

02:54:22.120 --> 02:54:28.120
[Guest 2]: used to be deeply unsatisfied with just the regular work that they were doing, which,

02:54:28.120 --> 02:54:30.120
[Guest 2]: for whatever reason, never happened to me.

02:54:30.120 --> 02:54:33.120
[Guest 2]: So, I could never go down that path eventually.

02:54:33.120 --> 02:54:38.120
[Guest 2]: But I got to know a lot of these people, peripherally, sometimes directly.

02:54:38.120 --> 02:54:43.120
[Guest 2]: And a lot of them in the course of the next three, four years after that, and then, you

02:54:43.120 --> 02:54:48.120
[Guest 2]: know, the passion for cinema had to shut down because like most good things, creative people

02:54:48.120 --> 02:54:50.120
[Guest 2]: together, then they started fighting.

02:54:50.120 --> 02:54:56.120
[Guest 2]: The whole idea was at the core of it, should we be controlling for quality on what comes

02:54:56.120 --> 02:54:57.120
[Guest 2]: on the site or not?

02:54:57.120 --> 02:54:59.120
[Guest 2]: And which way should we go down?

02:54:59.120 --> 02:55:03.120
[Guest 2]: Should we start raising funds and funding our own independent cinema?

02:55:03.120 --> 02:55:07.120
[Guest 2]: All of these things happened, including pitch books were made.

02:55:07.120 --> 02:55:12.120
[Guest 2]: Some of my background in that was useful to raise funds to say that we'll make our kinds

02:55:12.120 --> 02:55:14.120
[Guest 2]: of film and all of that.

02:55:14.120 --> 02:55:17.120
[Guest 2]: Could have happened, something could have happened if we went down that path, because

02:55:17.120 --> 02:55:21.120
[Guest 2]: they were just reasonably talented people in the mix.

02:55:21.120 --> 02:55:28.120
[Guest 2]: But, you know, it was always, I mean, whatever, ego battles and stuff.

02:55:28.120 --> 02:55:33.120
[Guest 2]: So, after three years or so, it shut down, four years almost.

02:55:33.120 --> 02:55:36.120
[Guest 2]: But those four years were very good.

02:55:36.120 --> 02:55:38.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, quite exhilarating.

02:55:38.120 --> 02:55:43.120
[Guest 2]: And I think in some ways, in whatever small way, I think it contributed a fair amount

02:55:43.120 --> 02:55:46.120
[Guest 2]: to Indian films.

02:55:46.120 --> 02:55:53.120
[Guest 2]: At least I can name 15 or 20 people today who have come out of passion for cinema who

02:55:53.120 --> 02:56:02.120
[Guest 2]: actually are directly involved in the Hindi cinema, whatever in Bollywood, and doing fairly

02:56:02.120 --> 02:56:03.120
[Guest 2]: good work.

02:56:03.120 --> 02:56:09.120
[Guest 2]: So, and a lot of film critics also, some of their early work was there.

02:56:09.120 --> 02:56:15.120
[Guest 2]: I remember, I mean, I do not want to name them, but a lot of them started writing first

02:56:15.120 --> 02:56:17.120
[Guest 2]: on the PFC site.

02:56:17.120 --> 02:56:23.120
[Guest 2]: So, that was my brush with the Versova crowd.

02:56:23.120 --> 02:56:28.120
[Guest 2]: I kept in touch, I still am in touch, although it's becoming more and more distant.

02:56:28.120 --> 02:56:33.120
[Guest 2]: Many of them have done so well that it's difficult to sometimes find time.

02:56:33.120 --> 02:56:39.120
[Guest 2]: I've also kind of moved and, you know, in my career, so it's tough.

02:56:39.120 --> 02:56:43.120
[Guest 2]: Looking back, I think, you know, there was a, it would have shut down on its own.

02:56:43.120 --> 02:56:47.120
[Guest 2]: Blogging was a certain point in time kind of a thing, phenomena, and it would have,

02:56:47.120 --> 02:56:50.120
[Guest 2]: Twitter was already there, and it was starting to disrupt this.

02:56:50.120 --> 02:56:56.120
[Guest 2]: But maybe if we had transitioned onto something as a platform, with funding and stuff of that

02:56:56.120 --> 02:56:58.120
[Guest 2]: kind, we could have had, we could have done something.

02:56:58.120 --> 02:57:01.120
[Guest 2]: We could have been contenders.

02:57:01.120 --> 02:57:04.120
[Guest 2]: But hua nahi.

02:57:04.120 --> 02:57:11.120
[Guest 2]: But for me, that was a lot of my, you know, bachpan ka all the sapna and everything of

02:57:11.120 --> 02:57:17.120
[Guest 2]: being on a film set, you know, meeting people who actually do make films.

02:57:17.120 --> 02:57:19.120
[Guest 2]: I think wo sab satisfy ho gaya.

02:57:19.120 --> 02:57:23.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I could never imagine that this was possible.

02:57:23.120 --> 02:57:30.120
[Guest 2]: Although I must tell you that in the first year or so when I came to Bombay, the keeda

02:57:30.120 --> 02:57:33.120
[Guest 2]: was so strong that I did all the stuff.

02:57:33.120 --> 02:57:38.120
[Guest 2]: I went and met Babbar Subhash B. Subhash, who directed movies like Disco Dancer Tarzan.

02:57:38.120 --> 02:57:40.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I just love the guy.

02:57:40.120 --> 02:57:42.120
[Guest 2]: I'm just, so I went and met him.

02:57:42.120 --> 02:57:45.120
[Guest 2]: I have like all kinds of stories of meeting him.

02:57:45.120 --> 02:57:50.120
[Guest 2]: I somehow found my way into catching up with Bappi Lahiri.

02:57:50.120 --> 02:57:55.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, this Dance Dance, Kasam Pehda Karne Wale, these are like, you know, people later,

02:57:55.120 --> 02:57:58.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, it sort of became like you should like them because it's of one kind.

02:57:58.120 --> 02:58:02.120
[Guest 2]: I genuinely watched these films with full enthusiasm.

02:58:02.120 --> 02:58:06.120
[Guest 1]: I have to say Dance Dance was actually one of the films of my childhood.

02:58:06.120 --> 02:58:09.120
[Guest 1]: I don't think I've ever said this in public before or written about it.

02:58:09.120 --> 02:58:11.120
[Unknown]: It's always the first time, go ahead.

02:58:11.120 --> 02:58:17.120
[Guest 1]: No, no, just I think it's just lots of memories attached to it during a summer spent in Bombay

02:58:17.120 --> 02:58:21.120
[Guest 1]: when I was pretty unwell for a large part of this vacation.

02:58:21.120 --> 02:58:30.120
[Guest 1]: But listening to songs and dialogues from it on radio, which kept playing for some reason in Bombay

02:58:30.120 --> 02:58:34.120
[Guest 1]: before I actually came back to Delhi and watched the film and enjoyed it,

02:58:34.120 --> 02:58:36.120
[Guest 1]: I felt like I already knew it.

02:58:36.120 --> 02:58:41.120
[Guest 2]: So, I mean, I think I've mentioned this to a lot of my friends, etc.

02:58:41.120 --> 02:58:46.120
[Guest 2]: So Dance Dance has my sort of a single line, which is my life's philosophy.

02:58:46.120 --> 02:58:53.120
[Guest 2]: So, there is this early in the film, I mean, this is Dance Dance is a story of Mithun,

02:58:53.120 --> 02:58:59.120
[Guest 2]: you know, as a child, I mean, their parents are sort of killed off by Amrish Puri.

02:58:59.120 --> 02:59:06.120
[Guest 2]: And because they go to Amrish Puri's mansion, and they start and they're like dancers and singers

02:59:06.120 --> 02:59:11.120
[Guest 2]: and Amrish Puri takes fancy to the woman and then he knocks off both of them after that.

02:59:11.120 --> 02:59:18.120
[Guest 2]: And so Mithun and his sister who turns out to be Smita Patil later, they are left on their own in Bombay.

02:59:18.120 --> 02:59:21.120
[Guest 2]: And so then they have to sort of make a living.

02:59:21.120 --> 02:59:24.120
[Guest 2]: So they start dancing in Chowpatty, Mithun starts dancing.

02:59:24.120 --> 02:59:27.120
[Guest 2]: And, you know, people put money and stuff.

02:59:27.120 --> 02:59:33.120
[Guest 2]: And then there is a Halwawala who comes in, and then the Halwawala gives them Halwa.

02:59:33.120 --> 02:59:36.120
[Guest 2]: I've never seen on a Bombay Chowpatty Halwawala ever.

02:59:36.120 --> 02:59:39.120
[Guest 2]: But you know, it's tribute to Babar Subhash that he could think of Halwawala.

02:59:39.120 --> 02:59:44.120
[Guest 2]: Not just that he thought of Halwawala, he even decided that he will put a Halwawala song in it.

02:59:44.120 --> 02:59:48.120
[Guest 2]: And that became the iconic song called Aagaya Aagaya Halwawala Aagaya.

02:59:48.120 --> 02:59:57.120
[Guest 2]: And somewhere in that film, just at that early stage, this Smita Patil older sister character tells Mithun

02:59:57.120 --> 03:00:02.120
[Guest 2]: that agar tujhe halwa khana hai, toh tujhe naachna hoga.

03:00:02.120 --> 03:00:04.120
[Guest 2]: Dance, dance.

03:00:04.120 --> 03:00:07.120
[Unknown]: And that's when the thing comes on screen, dance, dance.

03:00:07.120 --> 03:00:11.120
[Guest 2]: And I was like, yeah, this makes sense ki agar tujhe halwa khana hai.

03:00:11.120 --> 03:00:13.120
[Guest 1]: It's as good a life philosophy as anything.

03:00:13.120 --> 03:00:14.120
[Unknown]: Brilliant.

03:00:14.120 --> 03:00:21.120
[Guest 1]: Dance, dance is also that rare heartwarming film of the 80s where Shakti Kapoor finds redemption at the end.

03:00:21.120 --> 03:00:25.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, because Shakti Kapoor and Mithun are part of a dancing troupe.

03:00:25.120 --> 03:00:32.120
[Guest 2]: And like the first 20-30 minutes after they grow up, I think Babar Subhash,

03:00:32.120 --> 03:00:37.120
[Guest 2]: I have a feeling he had just watched Saturday Night Fever and Grease.

03:00:40.120 --> 03:00:42.120
[Guest 2]: So these guys were doing that stuff.

03:00:42.120 --> 03:00:44.120
[Guest 2]: So Shakti Kapoor was doing that.

03:00:44.120 --> 03:00:48.120
[Guest 2]: So because Shakti Kapoor was, you know, part of the dancing troupe.

03:00:48.120 --> 03:00:49.120
[Guest 2]: So it was good fun.

03:00:49.120 --> 03:00:50.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, you did that.

03:00:50.120 --> 03:00:52.120
[Guest 2]: So yeah, so that was that.

03:00:52.120 --> 03:00:54.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, including Babar Subhash in Tarzan.

03:00:54.120 --> 03:00:58.120
[Guest 2]: So Tarzan is this Kimi Katkar debut.

03:00:58.120 --> 03:01:04.120
[Guest 2]: And initially, there is this group who's going into some African jungle

03:01:04.120 --> 03:01:09.120
[Guest 2]: because they know that there is a Tarzan there and they want to catch him

03:01:09.120 --> 03:01:12.120
[Guest 2]: because they want to put him in a circus and make money off him.

03:01:14.120 --> 03:01:15.120
[Unknown]: Simpler times.

03:01:17.120 --> 03:01:20.120
[Guest 2]: So how do they know that there is a Tarzan?

03:01:20.120 --> 03:01:25.120
[Guest 2]: In the initial part of the movie, it's established that they're watching some, you know, Doordarshan news.

03:01:25.120 --> 03:01:28.120
[Guest 2]: And the newsreader says, yeh woh jungle hai.

03:01:28.120 --> 03:01:31.120
[Guest 2]: Aur yaha pe aaye din Tarzan paya jaata hai.

03:01:34.120 --> 03:01:36.120
[Unknown]: Ek Tarzan paya jaata hai.

03:01:37.120 --> 03:01:39.120
[Guest 2]: Anyway, so I had to meet him.

03:01:39.120 --> 03:01:40.120
[Guest 2]: But anyway, going back.

03:01:40.120 --> 03:01:41.120
[Guest 2]: What was meeting him like?

03:01:41.120 --> 03:01:42.120
[Guest 2]: It was great.

03:01:42.120 --> 03:01:44.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, what did you want?

03:01:44.120 --> 03:01:45.120
[Amit Varma]: What did you say?

03:01:45.120 --> 03:01:48.120
[Guest 2]: I just said, you know, I've grown up watching your film and everything.

03:01:48.120 --> 03:01:52.120
[Guest 2]: And he was very, they don't get irony.

03:01:52.120 --> 03:01:55.120
[Guest 2]: And not that I was coming at it that way.

03:01:55.120 --> 03:02:01.120
[Guest 2]: And they've, I mean, many of these guys I've met, they immediately start talking about, you know,

03:02:01.120 --> 03:02:04.120
[Guest 2]: how they did it and what were the, you know, challenges.

03:02:04.120 --> 03:02:07.120
[Guest 2]: And, you know, he was going in Goa one day.

03:02:07.120 --> 03:02:11.120
[Guest 2]: He was stopped at the signal and he saw a girl and a boy.

03:02:11.120 --> 03:02:13.120
[Guest 2]: And then he thought, what if these people, Michael Jackson had become very famous.

03:02:13.120 --> 03:02:15.120
[Guest 2]: Isme se agar ek Michael Jackson ban jaaye to.

03:02:15.120 --> 03:02:29.120
[Guest 2]: So, one of the things I learned there is that for them, it is as much a passion, craft, everything,

03:02:29.120 --> 03:02:34.120
[Guest 2]: as it is for some, you know, otter or whatever you might call him.

03:02:34.120 --> 03:02:37.120
[Guest 2]: Because he's seeing it that way.

03:02:37.120 --> 03:02:43.120
[Guest 2]: In fact, you realize he's not seeing it as you think very commercially as well.

03:02:43.120 --> 03:02:49.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, that was my sort of, you know, moment of understanding that.

03:02:49.120 --> 03:02:52.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, yeah, I mean, it should be commercially successful.

03:02:52.120 --> 03:02:59.120
[Guest 2]: But I think he's as commercially inclined as somebody else who's possibly making a film because it's great art.

03:02:59.120 --> 03:03:02.120
[Guest 2]: At a certain level, I sense that.

03:03:02.120 --> 03:03:04.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's not a cynical exercise.

03:03:04.120 --> 03:03:05.120
[Guest 2]: It's not a cynical exercise.

03:03:05.120 --> 03:03:06.120
[Guest 2]: Deeply invested.

03:03:06.120 --> 03:03:08.120
[Guest 2]: Thinking ki aisa karo to kaisa hoga.

03:03:08.120 --> 03:03:10.120
[Guest 2]: Isko karo to usko hoga.

03:03:10.120 --> 03:03:19.120
[Guest 2]: So, I mean, at one level, you can laugh at disco dancer that, you know, that guy Pinchu Kapoor and Karan Razdan find some guy in London.

03:03:19.120 --> 03:03:23.120
[Guest 2]: Yeh duniya ka sabse achha disco dancer killer hai.

03:03:23.120 --> 03:03:27.120
[Unknown]: Isne chaar disco dancer ko maara hai.

03:03:29.120 --> 03:03:31.120
[Amit Varma]: That's like, you know.

03:03:31.120 --> 03:03:33.120
[Guest 1]: I can imagine that LinkedIn profile.

03:03:33.120 --> 03:03:41.120
[Guest 1]: Well, around the same time that this film was being made, Jaane Bhi Toh Yaaro had the disco killer played by the young Anupam Kher.

03:03:41.120 --> 03:03:43.120
[Guest 1]: Which, of course, never sort of made it to the finished film.

03:03:43.120 --> 03:03:46.120
[Guest 1]: But that, again, was a fairly similar concept.

03:03:46.120 --> 03:03:54.120
[Guest 1]: This is a short-sighted character who goes around with a Sony Walkman in his ears and shoots people while listening to music and doing the disco.

03:03:54.120 --> 03:04:01.120
[Amit Varma]: Main yeh soch raha hoon ki if your future profession is going to be disco dancer killer, what are you interning at?

03:04:01.120 --> 03:04:04.120
[Amit Varma]: Are you, like, hand-breaker of break-dancer?

03:04:04.120 --> 03:04:07.120
[Unknown]: Anyway, sorry, to continue with your narrative.

03:04:07.120 --> 03:04:09.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so...

03:04:09.120 --> 03:04:12.120
[Guest 2]: No, anyway, so the broader point, Amit, is...

03:04:12.120 --> 03:04:19.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, before that, before coming into the passion for cinema kind of circle and meeting these people,

03:04:19.120 --> 03:04:29.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I had paid my homage to a lot of these things by being at those places where these famous films were shot.

03:04:29.120 --> 03:04:35.120
[Guest 2]: You know, I don't know, maybe you folks who've lived in Bombay long or who were in Bombay before,

03:04:35.120 --> 03:04:39.120
[Guest 2]: you know, just going down that Marine Drive the first time,

03:04:39.120 --> 03:04:44.120
[Guest 2]: and if you're a film fan or you've watched films,

03:04:44.120 --> 03:04:46.120
[Guest 2]: you know, it's a different feeling.

03:04:46.120 --> 03:04:49.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, pehli baar, you've seen this so many times.

03:04:49.120 --> 03:04:52.120
[Guest 2]: You've seen this in Leke Pehla Pehla Pyar, Bharke Aankhon Mein Kawar.

03:04:52.120 --> 03:04:59.120
[Guest 2]: From then, Devanand walking down Marine Drive, to Amitabh, Rote Huye Aate Hai Saab,

03:04:59.120 --> 03:05:02.120
[Guest 2]: to Rajni Gandha, Kai Baar Yung Hi Dekha Hai,

03:05:02.120 --> 03:05:06.120
[Guest 2]: Jo Man Ki Seema Rekha Hai, to, you know, Rim Jim Gire Sawan.

03:05:06.120 --> 03:05:10.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, there are, it's like, the first time I came into Bombay,

03:05:10.120 --> 03:05:14.120
[Guest 2]: and the first time I went to Nariman Point, in fact, my office was at Express Towers.

03:05:14.120 --> 03:05:21.120
[Guest 2]: And I, you know, before reaching office itself, I was like, you know, I was overwhelmed.

03:05:21.120 --> 03:05:28.120
[Guest 2]: Because there are just so many scenes that, you know, you have seen the same drive.

03:05:28.120 --> 03:05:32.120
[Guest 2]: But I did all of that, and I went to different places, RK Studios and stuff like that.

03:05:32.120 --> 03:05:37.120
[Guest 2]: But passion for cinema became a medium where I could actually directly interact with people,

03:05:37.120 --> 03:05:40.120
[Guest 2]: see the shoots and everything.

03:05:40.120 --> 03:05:44.120
[Guest 2]: Somehow, it also took away something.

03:05:44.120 --> 03:05:50.120
[Guest 2]: Once you demystify the thing, man, it becomes somewhat less...

03:05:50.120 --> 03:05:51.120
[Guest 2]: The making of the sausage.

03:05:51.120 --> 03:05:53.120
[Guest 2]: It somewhat becomes less magical.

03:05:53.120 --> 03:05:58.120
[Guest 2]: In fact, there is a thing that from 2012, 13, 14,

03:05:58.120 --> 03:06:06.120
[Guest 2]: the intensity with which I would follow cinema, etc. started, you know, ebbing.

03:06:06.120 --> 03:06:11.120
[Guest 2]: Maybe there was also because of other things in life, you know, having a family and things of that kind.

03:06:11.120 --> 03:06:18.120
[Guest 2]: But, and now it is definitely, it's not at the level that it was 10, 12 years back.

03:06:18.120 --> 03:06:25.120
[Guest 2]: And sometimes I regret that I've lost something by not being so deeply passionate about something.

03:06:25.120 --> 03:06:30.120
[Amit Varma]: To what extent do you think you're deciding, no, I don't want to be a filmmaker.

03:06:30.120 --> 03:06:33.120
[Amit Varma]: One, you've pointed out the pull was not so strong.

03:06:33.120 --> 03:06:37.120
[Amit Varma]: But also the push would not have been strong because you were doing well in your career.

03:06:37.120 --> 03:06:41.120
[Amit Varma]: And beyond the point, it obviously didn't make sense to give this up for that.

03:06:41.120 --> 03:06:43.120
[Amit Varma]: And how much of a factor is that trade-off?

03:06:43.120 --> 03:06:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And I imagine anybody who wants to be a filmmaker, there's both of these matter.

03:06:48.120 --> 03:06:52.120
[Amit Varma]: One, the pull can be so intensely strong that you are like, I can't do anything else in life.

03:06:52.120 --> 03:06:58.120
[Amit Varma]: But if the pull is not strong, the push could still be strong in the sense that your job could suck so bad.

03:06:58.120 --> 03:07:00.120
[Amit Varma]: Or you're so fed up in your family business.

03:07:00.120 --> 03:07:03.120
[Amit Varma]: Or you're so fucking useless at other things, you don't have a job.

03:07:03.120 --> 03:07:05.120
[Amit Varma]: That you're saying, okay, I'll do this.

03:07:05.120 --> 03:07:07.120
[Amit Varma]: And the opportunity cost is not that high as it were.

03:07:07.120 --> 03:07:13.120
[Amit Varma]: So how much of a factor do you think that was and do you sometimes like go back to that,

03:07:13.120 --> 03:07:16.120
[Amit Varma]: where there's a fork in the road and think of the road not taken?

03:07:16.120 --> 03:07:25.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, there are, see, firstly, I know people who had they not come into films,

03:07:25.120 --> 03:07:32.120
[Guest 2]: would have almost, you know, I mean, possibly died.

03:07:32.120 --> 03:07:36.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, in the sense that it's they would have just not been able to do anything else.

03:07:36.120 --> 03:07:38.120
[Guest 2]: That was never the case with me.

03:07:38.120 --> 03:07:42.120
[Guest 2]: And therefore, that itself solves for the problem.

03:07:42.120 --> 03:07:48.120
[Guest 2]: The second is, of course, you know, how badly you feel trapped in whatever you're doing.

03:07:48.120 --> 03:07:53.120
[Guest 2]: And some of that how badly you feel trapped in what you're doing is a matter of pull also.

03:07:53.120 --> 03:07:57.120
[Guest 2]: But sometimes, like you said, the opportunity cost is nothing.

03:07:57.120 --> 03:08:00.120
[Guest 2]: You know, you feel so terrible in what you're doing.

03:08:00.120 --> 03:08:05.120
[Guest 2]: And maybe what you're doing, you're also bad at it, that you go down that path.

03:08:05.120 --> 03:08:10.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I've never thought of that that often.

03:08:10.120 --> 03:08:14.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, there are some other like, sometimes I do feel writing something,

03:08:14.120 --> 03:08:17.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, maybe even just a script or, you know, writing a book or something.

03:08:17.120 --> 03:08:25.120
[Guest 2]: I feel that if one had given some time to that, I might have, I don't know whether I might have been good at it,

03:08:25.120 --> 03:08:33.120
[Guest 2]: but I think I would have done something well, you know, something good as part of doing that, you know, getting into that.

03:08:33.120 --> 03:08:36.120
[Guest 2]: Overall filmmaking, I don't know.

03:08:36.120 --> 03:08:39.120
[Guest 2]: I think that phase has gone.

03:08:39.120 --> 03:08:44.120
[Guest 2]: I don't regret or I don't have any what if kind of thinking in my mind.

03:08:44.120 --> 03:08:47.120
[Guest 2]: At that point in time, for a period of time, it was there.

03:08:47.120 --> 03:08:51.120
[Guest 2]: But now it's gone, it's gone.

03:08:51.120 --> 03:08:53.120
[Guest 2]: Will it come back?

03:08:53.120 --> 03:08:56.120
[Guest 2]: I think the writing thing is definitely going to come back.

03:08:56.120 --> 03:08:58.120
[Guest 2]: Filmmaking, I don't know.

03:08:58.120 --> 03:09:08.120
[Guest 2]: It's like I said, the intensity with which I feel for cinema now is much lower than what it was in the past.

03:09:08.120 --> 03:09:13.120
[Guest 2]: So that's one of the things that I think is permanent almost now.

03:09:13.120 --> 03:09:15.120
[Guest 2]: I don't think I will recover it.

03:09:15.120 --> 03:09:21.120
[Amit Varma]: That said, there are many, I mean, history is littered with examples of late bloomers who did great work pretty late in their lives.

03:09:21.120 --> 03:09:28.120
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps the diminishing of intensity may also come with a calmness of vision and a terror that could also lead to something.

03:09:28.120 --> 03:09:30.120
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask you another question.

03:09:30.120 --> 03:09:32.120
[Amit Varma]: And this, in a sense, is for both of you.

03:09:32.120 --> 03:09:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And partly because, you know, many of the people will, you know, that I'll ask about personally.

03:09:37.120 --> 03:09:42.120
[Amit Varma]: But also to really to both of you, because you have also seen Indian cinema evolve.

03:09:42.120 --> 03:09:46.120
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned how passion for cinema at the start wanted to be like a Kayyadu cinema, right?

03:09:46.120 --> 03:09:52.120
[Amit Varma]: So there's a great Andrew Cyrus quote about Andre Bazin, who was one of the founders of Kayyadu cinema.

03:09:52.120 --> 03:09:58.120
[Amit Varma]: And Cyrus wrote, quote, Bazin was the antithesis of Russian film theorist and director Sergei Eisenstein,

03:09:58.120 --> 03:10:04.120
[Amit Varma]: who posited that film didn't become film until it was sliced up and served montage style.

03:10:04.120 --> 03:10:09.120
[Amit Varma]: Eisenstein advocated for the collision of images and conflict of classes in films.

03:10:09.120 --> 03:10:13.120
[Amit Varma]: Bazin believed that film should be smooth and needn't be so socially weighty.

03:10:13.120 --> 03:10:15.120
[Amit Varma]: He felt that film should have a realism to them.

03:10:15.120 --> 03:10:19.120
[Amit Varma]: He focused on mise-en-scene as opposed to montage, stop quote.

03:10:19.120 --> 03:10:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And the sort of the progress that this indicates is, I think, also a way in which young filmmakers would mature.

03:10:29.120 --> 03:10:34.120
[Amit Varma]: In the sense that when you first want to make a film, you're very conscious of it being slick.

03:10:34.120 --> 03:10:43.120
[Amit Varma]: And maybe you're influenced by, you know, maybe Nolan, as JSA Today's kids are, or before that, Tarantino and so on.

03:10:43.120 --> 03:10:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And style matters a lot for its own sake.

03:10:48.120 --> 03:10:51.120
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, you want big ideas, you want weighty films.

03:10:51.120 --> 03:10:57.120
[Amit Varma]: But I would imagine that as time goes by and you mature, you don't necessarily want to do that anymore.

03:10:57.120 --> 03:11:04.120
[Amit Varma]: You just want to let stories tell themselves and, you know, you kind of move to a different sort of place.

03:11:04.120 --> 03:11:09.120
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, with the filmmakers you've known, for example, and you've known guys who've, you know,

03:11:09.120 --> 03:11:13.120
[Amit Varma]: made a journey and evolved a lot in their own way.

03:11:13.120 --> 03:11:15.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, for example, I love Chaitanya Tamane's work.

03:11:15.120 --> 03:11:17.120
[Amit Varma]: I think he's just mind-blowingly good.

03:11:17.120 --> 03:11:20.120
[Amit Varma]: Court must be one of the best first films ever made.

03:11:20.120 --> 03:11:28.120
[Amit Varma]: And equally, I think there was a phase where a lot of young directors would possibly have been in the thrall of stylists

03:11:28.120 --> 03:11:32.120
[Amit Varma]: and trying to, you know, make films in a particular kind of way.

03:11:32.120 --> 03:11:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, maybe they would have grown, maybe they did grow, maybe the ecosystem changed overall.

03:11:37.120 --> 03:11:46.120
[Amit Varma]: So what's your kind of sense of the journey that, you know, these filmmakers have made and that films themselves have made in India?

03:11:46.120 --> 03:11:50.120
[Guest 2]: I don't know about, I mean, of the recent sort of filmmakers.

03:11:50.120 --> 03:11:55.120
[Guest 2]: I don't know if I can point to a particular filmmaker and their evolution.

03:11:55.120 --> 03:11:59.120
[Guest 2]: Forget if whether I know them or remotely know them.

03:11:59.120 --> 03:12:02.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, it is difficult.

03:12:02.120 --> 03:12:05.120
[Guest 2]: I can't immediately think of it.

03:12:05.120 --> 03:12:08.120
[Guest 2]: In fact, somewhat some people have gone the other way.

03:12:08.120 --> 03:12:09.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, like Dibakar.

03:12:09.120 --> 03:12:11.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, that's exactly what I was thinking of.

03:12:11.120 --> 03:12:16.120
[Guest 2]: For instance, was very good in his first couple of films.

03:12:16.120 --> 03:12:20.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, Khosla Ka Ghosla was actually a very smooth, full sort of a film.

03:12:20.120 --> 03:12:28.120
[Guest 2]: And Oi Lucky Lucky Oi, which I think was a fantastic film and, you know, much deeper than many things that came out.

03:12:28.120 --> 03:12:40.120
[Guest 1]: But, you know, if I can just just interact for a bit, I think even between Khosla Ka Ghosla and Oi Lucky Lucky Oi, there's a vast difference in terms of the stylistic binary that Amit was talking about just now.

03:12:40.120 --> 03:12:45.120
[Guest 1]: Oi Lucky Lucky Oi is a much more fast paced film that draws attention to the nuts and bolts of its construction.

03:12:45.120 --> 03:12:54.120
[Guest 1]: Khosla Ka Ghosla is more in the tradition of the Rishi Keshmukherji, Basu Chatterjee, middle cinema, where everything is at the service of storytelling.

03:12:54.120 --> 03:12:58.120
[Guest 1]: And to my mind, I mean, I love Oi Lucky Lucky Oi, I like it better than Khosla Ka Ghosla.

03:12:58.120 --> 03:13:08.120
[Guest 1]: And I think even something like LST, where Dibakar sort of then allowed himself to sort of just get experimental and sort of bordering on avant-garde, you know, by the standards of the cinema.

03:13:08.120 --> 03:13:15.120
[Guest 1]: Like you said, it represents a movement in the opposite direction from what Amit suggested just now.

03:13:15.120 --> 03:13:25.120
[Guest 1]: But again, I don't think it's, you know, it was to his detriment as a filmmaker, it just meant that he was doing, he was trying different things out.

03:13:25.120 --> 03:13:30.120
[Guest 1]: And I also wanted to just point out, I mean, I'll just let you get back to this since you were talking.

03:13:30.120 --> 03:13:48.120
[Guest 1]: But I just want to point out that that Bazin quote was also very sort of explicitly directed at these ideas that the Russians, Eisenstein in particular, had about montage and the idea that film acquires meaning only when different unrelated images are placed next to each other.

03:13:48.120 --> 03:13:53.120
[Guest 1]: Like the lions in the Odessa, the step sequence and stuff like that.

03:13:53.120 --> 03:14:01.120
[Guest 1]: Whereas what Bazin was doing, and this is still very early, relatively early in the 1940s or 50s, but Bazin was pointing to filmmakers like Renoir, etc.

03:14:01.120 --> 03:14:10.120
[Guest 1]: Who didn't need to use montage in that way, who very often had gliding cameras, long takes, but still it wasn't theatrical.

03:14:10.120 --> 03:14:16.120
[Guest 1]: It was still very much cinema because the camera was still choosing what to show you, etc.

03:14:16.120 --> 03:14:22.120
[Guest 1]: So a lot of editing and a lot of cuts was not required, but it was still a different form of cinema.

03:14:22.120 --> 03:14:40.120
[Guest 1]: And I think if you're sort of moving that binary to the current day, 70 years later, I think it can sort of lead us down to some very sweeping generalized statements about directors and their trajectories.

03:14:40.120 --> 03:14:55.120
[Guest 1]: I think the Barker, I'm glad that example came up because he really is, in addition to being a filmmaker of a certain quality, even in his lesser work or whatever we might agree his lesser work might be, he's just done all sorts of things.

03:14:55.120 --> 03:15:08.120
[Guest 1]: And he hasn't, his career in terms of what he's done stylistically, his stylistic or formal choices, has not followed any clearly observable trajectory in either direction.

03:15:08.120 --> 03:15:15.120
[Guest 1]: He just seems to sort of just pick his subjects, his mode of storytelling, and then go with it.

03:15:15.120 --> 03:15:26.120
[Guest 1]: So Khosla Ka Ghuzla can be followed by LSD, which can then be followed by, again, a relatively straightforward narrative film like Shanghai, and then something like Biyomkesh Bakshi.

03:15:26.120 --> 03:15:34.120
[Guest 1]: Again, irrespective of what we think the quality of the films is, just talking about the way they are filmed, the style of it.

03:15:34.120 --> 03:15:49.120
[Guest 1]: So again, I think it's just, you know, if a filmmaker makes an honest decision based on the subject that he has, and how he feels he given his own sensibility, how he feels that subject is best tackled,

03:15:49.120 --> 03:16:01.120
[Guest 1]: then I don't think one should sort of, you know, really, really, really get judgmental in either direction about, you know, either the Eisenstein principle or the Bazin principle.

03:16:01.120 --> 03:16:09.120
[Amit Varma]: I guess what I was, I agree with you. I mean, like, for example, I think both Kurosawa and Ozu are just great, great filmmakers, and they are exactly the opposite approaches, right?

03:16:09.120 --> 03:16:11.120
[Unknown]: Kurosawa choreographs everything.

03:16:11.120 --> 03:16:12.120
[Unknown]: I'm going to come to Ozu.

03:16:12.120 --> 03:16:16.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I mean, I love Ozu a bit more, but I can see why they are great, great filmmakers.

03:16:16.120 --> 03:16:29.120
[Amit Varma]: But what I kind of meant was that when you initially become an artist of any sort, and I see this with young writers also, that, you know, you'll get carried away by what you can do with words so much that the style takes over the substance instead of being a slave to it.

03:16:29.120 --> 03:16:37.120
[Amit Varma]: Whereas in Kurosawa's case, of course, everything serves a film and what he's doing, and there is great style, but everything serves sort of the substance.

03:16:37.120 --> 03:16:42.120
[Amit Varma]: But before we get back to Subrata, I have a question for you, Jai, which is, is it pronounced Bazin?

03:16:42.120 --> 03:16:43.120
[Amit Varma]: I'm not sure.

03:16:43.120 --> 03:16:47.120
[Amit Varma]: Because Andr Bazin, so I thought I was being damn sophisticated.

03:16:47.120 --> 03:16:57.120
[Guest 1]: No, no, I just go to the opposite sort of extreme of the inverse snob thing of pronouncing a word as I see it, if I'm not sure.

03:16:57.120 --> 03:16:59.120
[Amit Varma]: Like a Punjabi, ascetic.

03:16:59.120 --> 03:17:01.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, absolutely.

03:17:01.120 --> 03:17:03.120
[Amit Varma]: I'm sorry, let's hand the mic.

03:17:03.120 --> 03:17:11.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I think I was actually going to come to the Ozu, Kurosawa, you know, in some sense, you know, the difference.

03:17:11.120 --> 03:17:22.120
[Guest 2]: And, you know, you watch an Ozu film, actually, there is, it is, it is like that, it's like a smooth film with, you know, lots of emotions.

03:17:22.120 --> 03:17:28.120
[Guest 2]: And if you watch a Tokyo story, sometimes you're not like, what is so celebrated in this?

03:17:28.120 --> 03:17:32.120
[Guest 2]: Because if there is, it's not showy at all.

03:17:32.120 --> 03:17:36.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, you watch a Rashomon, you know that there is something happening here, right?

03:17:36.120 --> 03:17:43.120
[Guest 2]: But just as a viewer myself, over the years, I have started liking that.

03:17:43.120 --> 03:17:55.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I, I like the, I don't think I've watched it, but every, I mean, I'm sure this year, this time also finally the result may go I got Tokyo story 1, 2, 3, or something that I didn't be there.

03:17:55.120 --> 03:17:57.120
[Guest 2]: Tell the listeners what you're talking about results.

03:17:57.120 --> 03:17:59.120
[Guest 2]: Okay, sorry.

03:17:59.120 --> 03:18:03.120
[Guest 2]: I think there is this every 10 years, I think the last was 2012.

03:18:03.120 --> 03:18:05.120
[Guest 2]: And then so on and so forth.

03:18:05.120 --> 03:18:07.120
[Guest 2]: They've gone back and this is 2022.

03:18:07.120 --> 03:18:21.120
[Guest 2]: There's a UK magazine called Sight and Sound, where they poll film critics around the world as well as directors around the world for their top 10 films.

03:18:21.120 --> 03:18:25.120
[Guest 2]: And then based on the votes, they come out with the top 100.

03:18:25.120 --> 03:18:28.120
[Amit Varma]: And our man Jai is one of the critics.

03:18:28.120 --> 03:18:42.120
[Guest 1]: I'm very proud to announce that I have an Osu on the list, but it is not Tokyo story and it's, it's, it's the second film in the so-called Noriko trilogy early summer, which I have a very special fondness for partly because I really love the film.

03:18:42.120 --> 03:19:06.120
[Guest 1]: And partly one reason why Tokyo story is just sort of an aside really, I tend not to, you know, rate Tokyo story as highly as most people do is simply because I'm a huge fan of a 1937 Hollywood film called Make Way for Tomorrow, which, which is a film that influenced Osu when he was making Tokyo story.

03:19:06.120 --> 03:19:20.120
[Guest 1]: And it's arguably the first major film that deals with the subject of, of elderly parents being neglected by their children and sort of looking forward to a life of, you know, of neglect and just, just being alone by themselves.

03:19:20.120 --> 03:19:29.120
[Guest 1]: So it's a lovely, very atypical film directed by Leo Macare from 1937 and Tokyo story owes something to it.

03:19:29.120 --> 03:19:40.120
[Guest 1]: So, so because of my for special fondness for that film, I just sort of feel like, you know, there are other Osus that I prefer personally, but, but yeah, back to what you were saying.

03:19:40.120 --> 03:19:43.120
[Guest 2]: I think, I mean, maybe we should talk about early summer.

03:19:43.120 --> 03:19:46.120
[Guest 2]: I seem to, I think I watched that.

03:19:46.120 --> 03:19:55.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, Tokyo story just for the listeners often gets in that ranking, often ends up at number two or number three.

03:19:55.120 --> 03:19:57.120
[Amit Varma]: Citizen Kane topped it for decades.

03:19:57.120 --> 03:20:06.120
[Guest 2]: For many decades. And then I think last time 2012 was one of the first time when Vertigo and that also reflects on who are the people who are voting because I think

03:20:06.120 --> 03:20:20.120
[Guest 1]: I wouldn't be surprised if there's a, there's a quite summary change in the list this time, in terms of the position of all these, you know, the films we mentioned Tokyo story, Citizen Kane, Vertigo, I think that there could be a pretty major change this time.

03:20:20.120 --> 03:20:28.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah. So far, I mean, and Tokyo story, you know, it's a very, I think the Indian audience can relate to what the story is.

03:20:28.120 --> 03:20:44.120
[Guest 2]: It's about an old couple coming into Tokyo to live with their kids, you know, and the older kid and his wife, they have no time for this couple.

03:20:44.120 --> 03:20:53.120
[Guest 2]: And they're also somewhat, you know, disoriented in Tokyo. Tokyo was just about sort of becoming a large metropolis then.

03:20:53.120 --> 03:20:59.120
[Guest 2]: And then they have a, they also had a second son who passed away in the war.

03:20:59.120 --> 03:21:06.120
[Guest 2]: And the widow of that son is someone who spends time with this old couple.

03:21:06.120 --> 03:21:08.120
[Guest 2]: And it's very nice. It's really nicely done.

03:21:08.120 --> 03:21:13.120
[Guest 2]: And this is part of the trilogy that Ozu had.

03:21:13.120 --> 03:21:25.120
[Guest 2]: So, and, you know, this, it's a very, it's a very different sort of treatment than some of the more celebrated, you know, Kurosawa kind of films.

03:21:25.120 --> 03:21:30.120
[Guest 2]: But Jaya, maybe a little bit on what draws you to Early Summer?

03:21:30.120 --> 03:21:40.120
[Guest 1]: Early Summer is just, I just, it's hard to say, I think, you know, beyond the point, how do you articulate why you feel a very strong emotional connection with a film.

03:21:40.120 --> 03:21:46.120
[Guest 1]: But it's a film with the same great actress, Setsuko Hara, who plays Noriko.

03:21:46.120 --> 03:21:50.120
[Guest 1]: The character's name Noriko across three films for Ozu.

03:21:50.120 --> 03:21:51.120
[Guest 1]: Not the same Noriko.

03:21:51.120 --> 03:21:52.120
[Guest 2]: It's not the same Noriko.

03:21:52.120 --> 03:21:54.120
[Guest 2]: It's a flower of Japan.

03:21:54.120 --> 03:21:55.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah. Yeah.

03:21:55.120 --> 03:22:00.120
[Guest 1]: So, and she passed away just a few years ago, I think just three, four years back.

03:22:00.120 --> 03:22:12.120
[Guest 1]: But she's, she plays this young woman, maybe a 27, 28 year old woman, which means that she's past, she's well past the age where a young woman of that society needs to get married.

03:22:12.120 --> 03:22:20.120
[Guest 1]: And the whole family, you know, the joint family, everybody's very concerned about this daughter of the family, who's also a working woman, the need for her to get married.

03:22:20.120 --> 03:22:23.120
[Guest 1]: And she's quite stoical about everything.

03:22:23.120 --> 03:22:28.120
[Guest 1]: And, you know, there's this all the speculation about who the right groom for her will be meeting people and so on.

03:22:28.120 --> 03:22:31.120
[Guest 1]: And I don't know, I think there's just something very spare.

03:22:31.120 --> 03:22:33.120
[Guest 1]: This is true of all of Ozu's work, I suppose.

03:22:33.120 --> 03:22:46.120
[Guest 1]: But it's very spare, very to the point about the way this, you know, that that typical tatami mat angle of Ozu, you know, with the camera barely moving or moving maybe two or three times in the whole film.

03:22:46.120 --> 03:22:59.120
[Guest 1]: It's just used to just observe the society with the shifting equations within a family with, and maybe because I'm sort of I'm Indian myself, there's things about it that I could relate to.

03:22:59.120 --> 03:23:10.120
[Guest 1]: The whole joint family set up, some of the themes that emerge in Hindi cinema, when it comes to these subjects, arranged marriages, things like that.

03:23:10.120 --> 03:23:17.120
[Guest 1]: Yet it was sufficiently from a different sort of culture with a different aesthetic, very subdued, I think.

03:23:17.120 --> 03:23:20.120
[Guest 2]: She makes an unconventional choice, right?

03:23:20.120 --> 03:23:29.120
[Guest 1]: Yes, but it's again, so the film really doesn't, it's not like it's underlined in any way, it's just there.

03:23:29.120 --> 03:23:32.120
[Guest 2]: It just sort of happens and it's all sort of organically there.

03:23:32.120 --> 03:23:35.120
[Guest 2]: And everybody accepts there is no drama, you know.

03:23:35.120 --> 03:23:46.120
[Guest 1]: Little things, well, you know, Ozu is full of those little moments, right? Tokyo Story, the famous moment where the Noriko character is just asked, someone rhetorically says to her, isn't life disappointing?

03:23:46.120 --> 03:23:57.120
[Guest 1]: And Setsuko Hara with the most dazzling and beautiful and warm smile in film history just says yes, you know, and it's just a moment like that.

03:23:57.120 --> 03:24:06.120
[Guest 1]: There's so much of that and yeah, you know, when you have things like that, that, you know, at film appreciation, you know, you're appreciating a film on those terms.

03:24:06.120 --> 03:24:18.120
[Guest 1]: Then, of course, you're looking at a film that has completely different strengths from a film made by a Godard or a Felony or a Kurosawa.

03:24:18.120 --> 03:24:27.120
[Guest 1]: Films that are much more cinematic in that specific way that we describe cinema as something very visual, dynamic, kind of kinetic.

03:24:27.120 --> 03:24:40.120
[Guest 1]: But then, you know, you have Ozu, you have Bresson, you have people like that just, again, through the sheer honesty of their work and being able to convey that honesty in filmmaking using a very spare aesthetic.

03:24:40.120 --> 03:24:44.120
[Guest 1]: They are just as great filmmakers in a different way.

03:24:44.120 --> 03:24:57.120
[Guest 2]: Sometimes, some of the Basu Chatterjee films, like for instance, Sara Aakash, the first Basu Chatterjee film was very

03:24:57.120 --> 03:25:09.120
[Guest 1]: It's very striking. It's a very striking film, right from that opening sequence, whether through the streets of Agra, with that music, the classical music, little glimpses of the Taj Mahal in between.

03:25:09.120 --> 03:25:26.120
[Guest 1]: And then, of course, subsequently, he went on to make much more, like Rishikesh Mukherjee in the 70s and 80s, films that had the visual look, the aesthetic of the TV serial, basically.

03:25:26.120 --> 03:25:29.120
[Guest 1]: Nothing very exciting going on at a visual level.

03:25:29.120 --> 03:25:42.120
[Guest 1]: So, it's interesting that So, yeah, that's another example of someone who, closer to what Amit was saying, someone who started off in 1969 with Sara Aakash, making this very dynamic looking film.

03:25:42.120 --> 03:25:45.120
[Guest 1]: And of course, it's a film that also has Mani Kaul in a small role in it.

03:25:45.120 --> 03:25:48.120
[Guest 1]: Yes, he's the brother.

03:25:48.120 --> 03:25:49.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, yeah.

03:25:49.120 --> 03:25:53.120
[Guest 1]: 1969 is quite a year for the, you know, the proto new wave.

03:25:53.120 --> 03:25:54.120
[Unknown]: Bhuvan Shom also.

03:25:54.120 --> 03:26:05.120
[Guest 1]: Bhuvan Shom, Sara Aakash, Uski Roti, all coming out in the same, all shot by the great KK Mahajan, the cameraman of the new wave.

03:26:05.120 --> 03:26:15.120
[Amit Varma]: Maybe if that film had proved to be something that persuaded Mani Kaul to stay on in filmmaking, then you could have said the film didn't make money, but it made money.

03:26:15.120 --> 03:26:37.120
[Amit Varma]: So, in modern times, do you think that there is a greater scope for young filmmakers to develop in unusual directions, which may not depend on what their peers or the people they're working with are doing?

03:26:37.120 --> 03:26:47.120
[Amit Varma]: For example, we're talking about Ozu, and earlier I mentioned Tamhane's Kote, and you know, Kote has a lot of Ozu like characteristics of the still camera and things are just unfolding and all of that.

03:26:47.120 --> 03:26:54.120
[Amit Varma]: And I can't imagine how a film like that could have come to, could have been made in the 1990s in India, for example.

03:26:54.120 --> 03:27:06.120
[Amit Varma]: And today, I think something like that might even be more possible in the sense that the means of production have become so incredibly cheap, that really anybody can make a film.

03:27:06.120 --> 03:27:17.120
[Amit Varma]: Like one film that I saw in Mami, which I loved is the Japanese film One Cut of the Dead, great horror film, which by Shinichiro Ueda, which was made for the equivalent of 20 lakh rupees.

03:27:17.120 --> 03:27:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And it ended up grossing more than 200 crores, you know, and obviously an outlier in that sense.

03:27:23.120 --> 03:27:31.120
[Amit Varma]: But in the sense that a today the means of production have become much cheaper, it's much easier for someone who wants to do audio visual storytelling to say,

03:27:31.120 --> 03:27:36.120
[Amit Varma]: I'll do something on YouTube, I'll do a vlog first, I'll experiment, I'll do this, I'll do that.

03:27:36.120 --> 03:27:43.120
[Amit Varma]: So the big bottleneck as far as I see in the film industry, in my naive understanding is really distribution more than anything else.

03:27:43.120 --> 03:27:51.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, the filmmaking part and, and also because, you know, you learn something by doing it, and it's so much easier to do something.

03:27:51.120 --> 03:28:05.120
[Amit Varma]: So one, there is that. And two, there is also the matter that now influences from everywhere are pouring in, you no longer need to be say in a particular theater in Calcutta at a particular point in time to be exposed to good cinema.

03:28:05.120 --> 03:28:13.120
[Amit Varma]: Good cinema is all around you. In fact, just leaving the term cinema aside, good audio visual content is all around you can get inspired by anywhere.

03:28:13.120 --> 03:28:25.120
[Amit Varma]: So do you think that there, you know, that one should therefore be hopeful about a greater diversity of influences and therefore styles and growth in young Indian filmmakers today?

03:28:25.120 --> 03:28:35.120
[Guest 1]: I think we already have that, right? Don't we already have? I mean, I, I just feel like, you know, when people engage in a certain form of golden ages,

03:28:35.120 --> 03:28:43.120
[Guest 1]: and you know, I'm a big fan of old cinema from various decades and very defensive about it in some ways also.

03:28:43.120 --> 03:28:53.120
[Guest 1]: But, but I always sort of find myself disagreeing when, when, you know, there's a certain sort of nostalgic, you know, talk on social media about how, you know,

03:28:53.120 --> 03:29:05.120
[Guest 1]: the films that used to be made earlier are not made now. And I feel like we are living in an age where pretty much any sort of film can get made and is getting made to some degree or the other.

03:29:05.120 --> 03:29:11.120
[Guest 1]: Now, of course, like you also pointed out, it's a distribution or the right sort of publicity is a different matter.

03:29:11.120 --> 03:29:22.120
[Guest 1]: There'll be, there'll obviously be with the amount of material there is and the amount of content there is now, there will always be films that, that many people won't even notice or won't realize are available out there.

03:29:22.120 --> 03:29:31.120
[Guest 1]: I'm regularly sort of, you know, I'll, I'll see someone mention something on Facebook about a film that's on Amazon Prime, that's on Prime or Netflix or whatever,

03:29:31.120 --> 03:29:37.120
[Guest 1]: which I didn't even realize was there or existing, despite the fact that this is partly my job to know about these things.

03:29:37.120 --> 03:29:50.120
[Guest 1]: But, but I think already we are in the situation where all sorts of films are being made, all sorts of, there's probably a greater variety of approaches, you know,

03:29:50.120 --> 03:30:03.120
[Guest 1]: currently than there has been at any time in the past, you know, in terms of the different, different aesthetics, different approaches to form and content, everything.

03:30:03.120 --> 03:30:10.120
[Guest 1]: So, so, so I think that's already happening. And of course, in terms of the means available, you know, you have internationally, I suppose in India also,

03:30:10.120 --> 03:30:18.120
[Guest 1]: but internationally you have, you have a filmmaker of the stature of Steven Soderbergh shooting a film on a phone and a good film, you know,

03:30:18.120 --> 03:30:24.120
[Guest 1]: a film with an A-list star like Claire Foy, I'm talking about this film called Unsane, which was shot on an iPhone,

03:30:24.120 --> 03:30:32.120
[Guest 1]: directed by Steven Soderbergh, starring Claire Foy and solid feature film that just sort of works as a, as a very immersive experience.

03:30:32.120 --> 03:30:40.120
[Guest 1]: You know, you have someone like that. So then of course, younger filmmakers will also have all sorts of tools available to them.

03:30:40.120 --> 03:30:48.120
[Guest 2]: I think, you know, the production is democratized. The challenge really is both the distribution and discovery then.

03:30:48.120 --> 03:30:54.120
[Guest 2]: You know, the fact that, you know, Jai can't find a film, while it's his professional sort of, you know, pursuit.

03:30:54.120 --> 03:30:56.120
[Unknown]: You had one job.

03:30:56.120 --> 03:31:07.120
[Guest 2]: So, so it's, it's impossible for others to find it, right? I mean, so, and that really is, then you don't know whether you're actually getting,

03:31:07.120 --> 03:31:14.120
[Guest 2]: and, you know, then who are you, I mean, who's promoting you in the sense somebody, you know, I don't know whether those kinds of things will happen ever again,

03:31:14.120 --> 03:31:27.120
[Guest 2]: you know, that some, John Dahl or whoever finds him and starts doing that and that guy makes rounders or something, you know, I mean, and it's like that.

03:31:27.120 --> 03:31:34.120
[Guest 2]: I don't know whether that's possible or is going to happen. But I agree with you that, I mean, there are all kinds of talent.

03:31:34.120 --> 03:31:40.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, I, you know, this, there's this movie called Promising Young Woman. I don't know if you've seen that.

03:31:40.120 --> 03:31:48.120
[Guest 2]: This lady Fennell, Emerald Fennell, who also was the showrunner for Killing Eve.

03:31:48.120 --> 03:31:57.120
[Guest 2]: And who also played, Helena Bonham Carter, who played Camilla in The Crown.

03:31:57.120 --> 03:32:06.120
[Guest 1]: So, I mean, just sometimes you're like, boss, she's such a talent. No, it's a very, very fine film. Promising Young Woman is one of my favorite films of the last few years.

03:32:06.120 --> 03:32:16.120
[Guest 2]: So, there's this Carrie Mulligan film, and she's very good. So, when you see and then you realize that she's made the film,

03:32:16.120 --> 03:32:23.120
[Guest 2]: then she's the showrunner for Killing Eve, and then she herself acted in that, and you're like, boss, one has to keep an eye out.

03:32:23.120 --> 03:32:35.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, these guys will do things, right? So, I think that, I mean, the talent sort of, you know, coming through of all kinds, making different kinds of films, etc.

03:32:35.120 --> 03:32:41.120
[Guest 2]: I think that will continue. And it'll only become easier, but you're right. The discovery is what I sometimes worry about.

03:32:41.120 --> 03:32:50.120
[Guest 2]: You know, who's going to find, who's going to champion, will enough people get to know or by the time you champion, it's an avalanche, you know, you're buried under another 20.

03:32:50.120 --> 03:32:55.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, that's, and that's, again, a function of the sheer volume of things that's available out there.

03:32:55.120 --> 03:33:03.120
[Guest 1]: So, of course, one does feel sorry for a lot of potentially, you know, upcoming directors, scriptwriters, etc.

03:33:03.120 --> 03:33:13.120
[Guest 1]: who might have very good stuff, you know, with them, but might just get buried under everything that's already available and not quite get the opportunities.

03:33:13.120 --> 03:33:19.120
[Guest 1]: That's, you know, it is a problem of plenty in that sense, when it comes to the distribution thing or whatever.

03:33:19.120 --> 03:33:25.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, just thinking aloud, maybe the focus and the importance will shift from producers and studios to filters.

03:33:25.120 --> 03:33:34.120
[Amit Varma]: Because we discover content typically through, you know, we have different kinds of filters, maybe it is a film blogger, maybe it is a particular YouTube channel, which is talking about films or whatever.

03:33:34.120 --> 03:33:46.120
[Amit Varma]: And I think there's a lot there to happen. We were talking about Andrew Sarris earlier and Andrew Sarris, of course, you know, came to fame or notoriety as it then was when he did this review of Hitchcock's Psycho,

03:33:46.120 --> 03:33:52.120
[Amit Varma]: which I know you're also a fan of Hitchcock, where he praised it to the skies and he said it's such a great film and all that.

03:33:52.120 --> 03:33:59.120
[Amit Varma]: And at that time, Hitchcock wasn't particularly taken seriously. And Sarris was attacked for it and so on and so forth.

03:33:59.120 --> 03:34:04.120
[Guest 1]: Pretty much anyone who wrote anything good about Psycho in 1960 was attacked.

03:34:04.120 --> 03:34:24.120
[Guest 1]: I mean, Robin Wood, who's one of my favorite writers, semi-academic writer, who wrote this great book called Hitchcock's Films Revisited, he submitted a review of Psycho when he wasn't a professional film critic to Sight and Sound, run by Penelope Houston at the time.

03:34:24.120 --> 03:34:35.120
[Guest 1]: And a very detailed, wonderful piece, which of course made it to his book eventually, but she rejected it politely saying, you know, you fail to grasp that Hitchcock did not intend this film to be taken seriously.

03:34:35.120 --> 03:34:40.120
[Guest 1]: So, yeah, so that of course, but yeah, sorry, go on.

03:34:40.120 --> 03:34:53.120
[Amit Varma]: So, my question here is that that's a way of looking at what, you know, Subrata also said earlier about history being fickle, about you can regard something as highly at one point and not think of it 100 years later and vice versa.

03:34:53.120 --> 03:35:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And today, of course, Hitchcock is, you know, right there at the top of everybody's mind, including the Sight and Sound poll last time with Vertigo and so on and so forth.

