03:41:57.120 --> 03:42:17.120
[Guest 1]: It's just, you know, a story about a documentary filmmaker whose face we never see and who was voiced by Palathara himself. So, it's got this meta quality. He's in Calcutta to shoot a documentary along the lines of Louis Mal's Calcutta film and he's there with his wife and then the lockdown happens in 2020.

03:42:17.120 --> 03:42:35.120
[Guest 1]: So, they are basically stuck. They can't go out and do their research, etc., any shooting, etc. They are stuck in one room together, in one little flat together. And then, you know, the whole film basically just takes the form of this guy whose face we never see. We only hear his voiceover, pointing his camera repeatedly at his wife, you know, he's getting fed up of her.

03:42:35.120 --> 03:42:58.120
[Guest 1]: They are sort of cloistered together and, you know, saying these extremely, you know, chauvinistic things about her, criticizing her, you know, just saying things like that. And it's such an interesting film in terms of what it, you know, this perspective it provides of the nastiest aspects of the male gaze or whatever it is.

03:42:58.120 --> 03:43:26.120
[Guest 1]: Plus, it's got this experimental side to it because of the very nature of the filmmaking, the handheld camera, the meta-ness of it. It's very interesting. It was along with all of Palathara's films, it was on Mubi India. I don't know if it still is. It might be. But that's one example of someone who, even within the world of Malayalam cinema, I feel he's someone who's just so interesting and should get a wider audience at some point.

