[Guest 2]: I mean, just to sort of...

03:53:11.120 --> 03:53:13.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, my listeners don't have a life. What are they going to do, man?

03:53:13.120 --> 03:53:17.120
[Guest 2]: If I narrate an episode of five hours, they'll be able to watch a movie.

03:53:17.120 --> 03:53:25.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, the 40s, even in the Hindi films, I think, some of the early Dilip Kumar, I think is quite good.

03:53:25.120 --> 03:53:28.120
[Guest 2]: Shaheed, for instance, I like it.

03:53:28.120 --> 03:53:32.120
[Guest 2]: The prints might be poor, so you have to figure out if you're able to get good prints.

03:53:32.120 --> 03:53:37.120
[Guest 2]: Andaz of Mehboob Khan is lovely.

03:53:37.120 --> 03:53:39.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's a love triangle.

03:53:39.120 --> 03:53:45.120
[Guest 2]: Raj Kapoor, Dilip Kumar, Nargis, great songs, Naushad and Majrooh.

03:53:45.120 --> 03:53:49.120
[Guest 2]: And in Andaz, I mean, just to go down this general rabbit hole.

03:53:49.120 --> 03:53:56.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, actually in Andaz, Rafi was singing for Raj Kapoor and Mukesh was singing for Dilip Kumar.

03:53:56.120 --> 03:53:59.120
[Guest 2]: And that was how it was for some time.

03:53:59.120 --> 03:54:03.120
[Guest 2]: You know, Dilip Kumar found Rafi as his voice a little later.

03:54:03.120 --> 03:54:08.120
[Guest 2]: Although in Shaheed, Vatan Ke Vaaste Vatan Ke Naujawas Shaheed Ho was a Rafi song.

03:54:08.120 --> 03:54:11.120
[Guest 2]: But Talat was singing quite often for Dilip Kumar.

03:54:11.120 --> 03:54:15.120
[Guest 2]: In fact, almost the voice of Dilip Kumar in the early 50s.

03:54:15.120 --> 03:54:23.120
[Guest 2]: And in Andaz, Jhoom Jhoom Ke Nacho, Aaj Tu Kahe Agar, etc. were all Mukesh songs, which was picturized on Dilip Kumar.

03:54:23.120 --> 03:54:29.120
[Guest 2]: And some of those early V Shantaram films also of 1940s are quite good.

03:54:29.120 --> 03:54:32.120
[Guest 1]: For the 30s even, Duniya Na Mane.

03:54:32.120 --> 03:54:35.120
[Guest 2]: Duniya Na Mane and Aurat, not Aurat, what is that other one?

03:54:35.120 --> 03:54:40.120
[Guest 2]: The one that had Sai Pranjpe's mother.

03:54:40.120 --> 03:54:50.120
[Guest 2]: But anyway, so these couple of those films, which from Hindi of the 40s, you know, 50s and 60s.

03:54:50.120 --> 03:54:55.120
[Guest 2]: There are, you know, there are, I mean, I'm generally a Billy Wilder fan.

03:54:55.120 --> 03:54:59.120
[Guest 2]: I love, I mean, the guy just had range.

03:54:59.120 --> 03:55:03.120
[Guest 2]: So, I mean, again, I mean, if people, I mean, these are very famous films of those times.

03:55:03.120 --> 03:55:06.120
[Guest 2]: But if people have not watched it, I would suggest, I mean, some like it.

03:55:06.120 --> 03:55:09.120
[Guest 2]: Hot is just a great film.

03:55:09.120 --> 03:55:11.120
[Guest 2]: Absolutely fun.

03:55:11.120 --> 03:55:15.120
[Guest 1]: I think during our last conversation, Amit, I actually mentioned Ace in the Hole.

03:55:15.120 --> 03:55:17.120
[Guest 2]: Billy Wilder's Ace in the Hole.

03:55:17.120 --> 03:55:22.120
[Guest 1]: That's one of the somewhat under the radar films that.

03:55:22.120 --> 03:55:25.120
[Guest 2]: I think Ace in the Hole is just a fantastic film.

03:55:25.120 --> 03:55:27.120
[Guest 2]: This is a Kirk Douglas movie.

03:55:27.120 --> 03:55:29.120
[Guest 2]: Billy Wilder movie.

03:55:29.120 --> 03:55:33.120
[Guest 2]: This is almost like this peoply life kind of, you know, copied it.

03:55:33.120 --> 03:55:37.120
[Guest 1]: 70 years ago with the whole media circus.

03:55:37.120 --> 03:55:43.120
[Guest 2]: So, Kirk Douglas is a sort of, he's been fired from his job in New York or somewhere.

03:55:43.120 --> 03:55:46.120
[Guest 2]: And he goes somewhere down to Colorado or somewhere looking for a job.

03:55:46.120 --> 03:55:51.120
[Guest 2]: He's just a sort of, you know, investigative journalist or whatever.

03:55:51.120 --> 03:55:55.120
[Guest 2]: He's just a guy who's looking for stories to, again, redeem himself.

03:55:55.120 --> 03:56:02.120
[Guest 2]: And finds a story of a guy who, while drilling something, has gone into a, you know, gadda inside.

03:56:02.120 --> 03:56:04.120
[Guest 2]: Stuck in a cave.

03:56:04.120 --> 03:56:09.120
[Guest 2]: And then the story is that this guy wants to prolong the story for as long as possible.

03:56:09.120 --> 03:56:12.120
[Guest 2]: With some disastrous consequences eventually.

03:56:12.120 --> 03:56:13.120
[Guest 1]: Does that sound familiar?

03:56:13.120 --> 03:56:20.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah. And this is, so this is like Wilder simultaneously was doing all kinds of things here.

03:56:20.120 --> 03:56:23.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, he's just amazing.

03:56:23.120 --> 03:56:26.120
[Guest 2]: And a whole lot of them who came from Austria, Germany.

03:56:26.120 --> 03:56:29.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, these are not actually English speaking people.

03:56:29.120 --> 03:56:33.120
[Guest 1]: They brought a very particular sensibility from there.

03:56:33.120 --> 03:56:35.120
[Guest 1]: You know, Lubitsch came first.

03:56:35.120 --> 03:56:37.120
[Guest 1]: Then Wilder assisted him.

03:56:37.120 --> 03:56:44.120
[Guest 1]: The whole bunch of them just played a big part in fashioning the Hollywood of that time also.

03:56:44.120 --> 03:56:47.120
[Guest 2]: In fact, there's this movie called Sweet Smell of Success.

03:56:47.120 --> 03:56:48.120
[Guest 1]: Bert Lancaster film.

03:56:48.120 --> 03:56:49.120
[Guest 1]: And Tony Curtis, yeah.

03:56:49.120 --> 03:56:53.120
[Guest 2]: Just absolutely, you know, great film.

03:56:53.120 --> 03:56:58.120
[Guest 1]: Very hard hitting film, again, about partly about the media and what it can do.

03:56:58.120 --> 03:57:03.120
[Guest 2]: There's a cinematographer, there's a Chinese origin cinematographer, right?

03:57:03.120 --> 03:57:07.120
[Guest 1]: James Wong Howe.

03:57:07.120 --> 03:57:09.120
[Guest 1]: Who's the cinematographer here.

03:57:09.120 --> 03:57:11.120
[Guest 1]: It's a beautiful looking film.

03:57:11.120 --> 03:57:17.120
[Guest 1]: Close to home, one of the films that I, in fact, I think I may have mentioned it to Subrat before we started,

03:57:17.120 --> 03:57:18.120
[Guest 1]: that I watched.

03:57:18.120 --> 03:57:23.120
[Guest 1]: And one of the reasons it strikes me is both because I really enjoyed watching it.

03:57:23.120 --> 03:57:26.120
[Guest 1]: I think watching it for the first time properly as an adult.

03:57:26.120 --> 03:57:30.120
[Guest 1]: Also because there's an excellent print of it available online.

03:57:30.120 --> 03:57:33.120
[Guest 1]: Gulzaaz Mere Apne, which is a 1971 film.

03:57:33.120 --> 03:57:35.120
[Guest 1]: And of course, we were talking about Haal Chaal Theek Thaak Hai sometime back.

03:57:35.120 --> 03:57:42.120
[Guest 1]: That's the name of the song in Mere Apne, which is a very hard hitting commentary on various things,

03:57:42.120 --> 03:57:46.120
[Guest 1]: various problems that the country was facing at that time in 1970-71.

03:57:46.120 --> 03:57:51.120
[Guest 1]: And as is so often the case, you know, when we are living in the present moment,

03:57:51.120 --> 03:57:54.120
[Guest 1]: there's this tendency to sort of, you know, the recency bias or whatever,

03:57:54.120 --> 03:57:58.120
[Guest 1]: to think that the problems we are facing today are exclusively of today.

03:57:58.120 --> 03:58:04.120
[Guest 1]: And very often it's quite surprising to go back and look at a film made 50 or 60 or 70 years ago

03:58:04.120 --> 03:58:06.120
[Guest 1]: and see the same things being talked about.

03:58:06.120 --> 03:58:09.120
[Guest 1]: I don't know if, I don't remember now if I have in our previous talk,

03:58:09.120 --> 03:58:17.120
[Guest 1]: if I mentioned this wonderful 1953 film called, 1952 film called Mr. Sampath, which was a

03:58:17.120 --> 03:58:18.120
[Unknown]: Motilal.

03:58:18.120 --> 03:58:22.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, it's made, it's based very loosely on an R.K. Narayan novel.

03:58:22.120 --> 03:58:26.120
[Guest 1]: But the film is very, and it's a remake of the Tamil film Miss Malini.

03:58:26.120 --> 03:58:31.120
[Guest 1]: But it's, here's a film made less than five years into independence.

03:58:31.120 --> 03:58:37.120
[Guest 1]: You know, a time that we sort of, you know, the persistent narrative is that it's a time of Nehruvian idealism, etc.

03:58:37.120 --> 03:58:39.120
[Guest 1]: It's like biting into a sour lemon.

03:58:39.120 --> 03:58:44.120
[Guest 1]: And, you know, it's got a very sarcastic song called Ache Din Aa Raha Hain Hai Hurra,

03:58:44.120 --> 03:58:48.120
[Guest 1]: where the song basically, song lyrics are about how Ache Din are never actually going to come.

03:58:48.120 --> 03:58:52.120
[Guest 1]: But, you know, it's this ironical thing going on in 1952.

03:58:52.120 --> 03:58:54.120
[Guest 1]: Padmini and Motilal.

03:58:54.120 --> 03:58:56.120
[Guest 1]: The agent kind of thing.

03:58:56.120 --> 03:59:00.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, it's a very, you know, I always refer to that film, you know,

03:59:00.120 --> 03:59:03.120
[Guest 1]: when I often get people telling me with great authority,

03:59:03.120 --> 03:59:08.120
[Guest 1]: Jaane Bhi Toh Yaaro is the first black comedy satire in Indian cinema.

03:59:08.120 --> 03:59:11.120
[Guest 1]: And I say, Hindi cinema mein bhi nahi hai.

03:59:11.120 --> 03:59:13.120
[Unknown]: You know, please.

03:59:13.120 --> 03:59:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Hold my drink.

03:59:14.120 --> 03:59:19.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so this is also, this is another, coming back to what we discussed earlier,

03:59:19.120 --> 03:59:23.120
[Guest 1]: people just, you know, when you don't have a sense of deeper history, which is fine.

03:59:23.120 --> 03:59:27.120
[Guest 1]: Most of us, it's not like we can know everything or be fully formed or something.

03:59:27.120 --> 03:59:32.120
[Guest 1]: But then, it would be nice not to make big statements,

03:59:32.120 --> 03:59:37.120
[Guest 1]: saying that this film is the first example when you don't know what has gone before.

03:59:37.120 --> 03:59:39.120
[Guest 1]: So, Mr. Sampath is one example.

03:59:39.120 --> 03:59:42.120
[Guest 1]: Mere Apne, of course, is not a hard-hitting satire in the same way,

03:59:42.120 --> 03:59:49.120
[Guest 1]: but it's got that song and it's got a few scenes about unemployed youth in the India of that time.

03:59:49.120 --> 03:59:52.120
[Guest 1]: Very disgruntled by the situation that they're in.

03:59:52.120 --> 03:59:58.120
[Guest 1]: But finding some sucker through an old woman played by Meena Kumar,

03:59:58.120 --> 04:00:01.120
[Guest 1]: you become like a nani figure to all of them.

04:00:01.120 --> 04:00:03.120
[Amit Varma]: Lovely print online.

04:00:03.120 --> 04:00:04.120
[Amit Varma]: Some sucker.

04:00:04.120 --> 04:00:06.120
[Amit Varma]: For a moment, I heard it as the other sucker.

04:00:06.120 --> 04:00:08.120
[Guest 2]: So, I was thinking ki.

04:00:08.120 --> 04:00:13.120
[Guest 2]: But 50s again, I mean, so, for instance, sticking to some of the Hindi films of the 50s,

04:00:13.120 --> 04:00:18.120
[Guest 2]: I would still, for those who haven't seen Bimal Roy films,

04:00:18.120 --> 04:00:24.120
[Guest 2]: and, you know, Jai, when I attended one of his film appreciation classes,

04:00:24.120 --> 04:00:29.120
[Guest 2]: where you took us through the Diya song of Parag.

04:00:29.120 --> 04:00:31.120
[Guest 1]: Oh, Parag, yeah, yeah, yeah.

04:00:31.120 --> 04:00:34.120
[Guest 1]: Lovely photography, yeah.

04:00:34.120 --> 04:00:37.120
[Guest 2]: So, Parag is a very good film.

04:00:37.120 --> 04:00:41.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, this is, I mean, the plot is like, you know, there is a village,

04:00:41.120 --> 04:00:44.120
[Guest 2]: and there is like the whole village ecosystem, panchayat,

04:00:44.120 --> 04:00:50.120
[Guest 2]: and there is a particular event that triggers chaos there, you know,

04:00:50.120 --> 04:00:53.120
[Guest 2]: which is, and it's a nicely done thing.

04:00:53.120 --> 04:00:56.120
[Guest 2]: Everybody then starts suspecting that people are jockeying for things.

04:00:56.120 --> 04:01:00.120
[Guest 2]: Great songs, of course, O Sajna Barkha Bahar Hai,

04:01:00.120 --> 04:01:03.120
[Guest 2]: Saril in just peak form.

04:01:03.120 --> 04:01:06.120
[Guest 2]: But that's a good movie.

04:01:06.120 --> 04:01:08.120
[Guest 2]: There's a movie called Uche Log.

04:01:08.120 --> 04:01:15.120
[Guest 2]: Again, I recommend that this is a movie made by a very old sort of director of the 30s

04:01:15.120 --> 04:01:20.120
[Guest 2]: who was still working then called Fani Majumdar.

04:01:20.120 --> 04:01:28.120
[Guest 2]: And Uche Log is a copy of a Tamil, you know, play called Major Chandrakant,

04:01:28.120 --> 04:01:31.120
[Guest 2]: K. Balachandra had written that.

04:01:31.120 --> 04:01:35.120
[Guest 2]: Ashok Kumar and Feroz Khan, Feroz Khan in one of his early films.

04:01:35.120 --> 04:01:39.120
[Guest 2]: It's like a good story.

04:01:39.120 --> 04:01:44.120
[Guest 2]: Has one great Rafi song, Jaag Dil Hai Deewana.

04:01:44.120 --> 04:01:45.120
[Guest 2]: Do you sing?

04:01:45.120 --> 04:01:46.120
[Guest 2]: No, no, I don't sing.

04:01:46.120 --> 04:01:47.120
[Guest 2]: Please don't tell.

04:01:47.120 --> 04:01:49.120
[Guest 2]: Otherwise, I would have asked you to sing a little bit of it.

04:01:49.120 --> 04:01:53.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's just, it's Chitragupt, the father of Anand Meland.

04:01:53.120 --> 04:01:58.120
[Guest 2]: There, his music and Majrooh's lyrics.

04:01:58.120 --> 04:02:00.120
[Guest 2]: But the film is great.

04:02:00.120 --> 04:02:05.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, if you just, you know, if you can't watch it, just read the plot somewhere,

04:02:05.120 --> 04:02:07.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, on IMDb or something.

04:02:07.120 --> 04:02:08.120
[Guest 2]: It's a great plot.

04:02:08.120 --> 04:02:10.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, to have made that film in the 60s.

04:02:10.120 --> 04:02:14.120
[Guest 2]: Fani Majumdar, by the way, I mean, just to go back into time,

04:02:14.120 --> 04:02:21.120
[Guest 2]: in the 30s, Calcutta was a big hub of Indian with new theaters, right?

04:02:21.120 --> 04:02:23.120
[Guest 2]: So there was this guy called B. N. Sarkar.

04:02:23.120 --> 04:02:26.120
[Guest 2]: B. N. Sarkar was a sort of, you know,

04:02:26.120 --> 04:02:30.120
[Guest 2]: aristocratic feudal sort of a guy with a lot of land and everything.

04:02:30.120 --> 04:02:33.120
[Guest 2]: He had gone to London, studied in wherever, Cambridge, etc.

04:02:33.120 --> 04:02:35.120
[Guest 2]: And he was very fascinated by films.

04:02:35.120 --> 04:02:39.120
[Guest 2]: So he came back to India and he set up this new theater.

04:02:39.120 --> 04:02:42.120
[Guest 2]: And then he just decided that all good talent should come here.

04:02:42.120 --> 04:02:47.120
[Guest 2]: So, and the fact that there was generally this whole Bengali renaissance, etc.

04:02:47.120 --> 04:02:50.120
[Guest 2]: So there were people who were writing, listening to music and all that.

04:02:50.120 --> 04:02:59.120
[Guest 2]: So some of the earliest playback stuff, music and all of that was done in Calcutta with new theaters.

04:02:59.120 --> 04:03:05.120
[Guest 2]: So there was this three guys, Raychand Bural, R. C. Bural, Timir Baran.

04:03:05.120 --> 04:03:10.120
[Guest 2]: So these couple of people came in and they started playing.

04:03:10.120 --> 04:03:12.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, they started actually giving playback music.

04:03:12.120 --> 04:03:20.120
[Guest 2]: And till then, the classical Indian music has no concept of harmony.

04:03:20.120 --> 04:03:22.120
[Guest 2]: There is no guitar in the sense, right?

04:03:22.120 --> 04:03:27.120
[Guest 2]: So it's like monotonic, a single instrument or two instruments going.

04:03:27.120 --> 04:03:33.120
[Guest 2]: So in that sense, R. C. Bural was actually almost the pioneer of bringing the notion of music

04:03:33.120 --> 04:03:41.120
[Guest 2]: in that sense of having harmony and different instruments and getting organs and all of that into this.

04:03:41.120 --> 04:03:44.120
[Unknown]: Why did I go here? Oh, from Fani Majumdar, okay.

04:03:44.120 --> 04:03:51.120
[Guest 2]: So now, and then he got some of the best directors.

04:03:51.120 --> 04:03:58.120
[Guest 2]: One of the big directors then who he sort of nurtured was P. C. Barua, who made the first Devdas.

04:03:58.120 --> 04:04:05.120
[Guest 2]: And the first Devdas, again, if you look at the title credits there, the editor was or whatever,

04:04:05.120 --> 04:04:12.120
[Guest 2]: it was Rishikesh or Vimal Roy. And then Vimal Roy's editor was Rishikesh.

04:04:12.120 --> 04:04:15.120
[Guest 2]: And then he got K. L. Saigal.

04:04:15.120 --> 04:04:17.120
[Guest 2]: And it's very difficult.

04:04:17.120 --> 04:04:21.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, now we sort of caricature that particular singing style and all.

04:04:21.120 --> 04:04:27.120
[Guest 2]: But I mean, there was no such phenomena that people have seen after, you know,

04:04:27.120 --> 04:04:34.120
[Guest 2]: in the sense of how popular he was and just the quality of his voice and all of that.

04:04:34.120 --> 04:04:37.120
[Guest 2]: And so Devdas, first Devdas had K. L. Saigal.

04:04:37.120 --> 04:04:39.120
[Guest 2]: It was great songs.

04:04:39.120 --> 04:04:44.120
[Guest 2]: And then the new theaters made some great K. L. Saigal films.

04:04:44.120 --> 04:04:50.120
[Guest 2]: One of them was called President, which had that Ek Bangla Bane Nihara, hugely popular song.

04:04:50.120 --> 04:04:53.120
[Guest 2]: And that was, so that film was made by this guy called Nitin Bose,

04:04:53.120 --> 04:04:56.120
[Guest 2]: who later goes to Bombay and makes Ganga Jamuna and all that.

04:04:56.120 --> 04:04:59.120
[Unknown]: Although critics believe that Dhirub Kumar only made the film.

04:04:59.120 --> 04:05:06.120
[Guest 2]: And then there was a movie called Street Singer, which had the greatest pairing possible of them.

04:05:06.120 --> 04:05:10.120
[Guest 2]: Right. Which is K. L. Saigal and Kanan Devi.

04:05:10.120 --> 04:05:16.120
[Guest 2]: And then K. L. Saigal has that song called Babul Mora Nahi Aur Chhuto Na,

04:05:16.120 --> 04:05:19.120
[Guest 2]: which is actually the song written by Wajid Ali Shah.

04:05:19.120 --> 04:05:21.120
[Guest 2]: And it's a fantastic thing, right.

04:05:21.120 --> 04:05:24.120
[Guest 2]: So Wajid Ali Shah has been driven out of Awadh.

04:05:24.120 --> 04:05:32.120
[Guest 2]: And Wajid Ali Shah, if you remember, he was not necessarily interested in all this statecraft, warfare, etc.

04:05:32.120 --> 04:05:34.120
[Guest 2]: Loses Awadh.

04:05:34.120 --> 04:05:39.120
[Guest 2]: And he's famously that guy whose portraits always have him exposing his left nipple.

04:05:39.120 --> 04:05:43.120
[Guest 2]: So then they exile him to Calcutta.

04:05:43.120 --> 04:05:49.120
[Guest 2]: And then while going, he writes this Babul Mora Nahi Aur Chhuto Na, meaning I'm leaving this.

04:05:49.120 --> 04:05:55.120
[Guest 2]: And of course, going back to the biryani story, Wajid Ali Shah is the reason why Calcutta Biryani has the potatoes.

04:05:55.120 --> 04:05:57.120
[Guest 2]: Why?

04:05:57.120 --> 04:05:59.120
[Guest 2]: Because they came in here.

04:05:59.120 --> 04:06:03.120
[Guest 2]: He was living off a British pension.

04:06:03.120 --> 04:06:06.120
[Guest 2]: So they wanted to add substance as the story goes.

04:06:06.120 --> 04:06:08.120
[Guest 2]: Nobody knows this for a fact.

04:06:08.120 --> 04:06:11.120
[Guest 2]: So they wanted to add a little bit of weight to the biryani.

04:06:11.120 --> 04:06:12.120
[Guest 2]: They didn't have enough meat.

04:06:12.120 --> 04:06:14.120
[Guest 2]: So they started adding potatoes.

04:06:14.120 --> 04:06:21.120
[Guest 2]: So Wajid Ali Shah came to Calcutta, started living in a particular place, brought in two iconic Calcutta dishes, the Calcutta Biryani.

04:06:21.120 --> 04:06:24.120
[Guest 2]: And there is something, if you go to Calcutta, there is something called the Rezala.

04:06:24.120 --> 04:06:28.120
[Guest 2]: Rezala is a particular kind of chicken or mutton dish.

04:06:28.120 --> 04:06:30.120
[Guest 2]: Both were brought in by Wajid Ali Shah.

04:06:30.120 --> 04:06:32.120
[Guest 2]: Why are we at Wajid Ali Shah?

04:06:32.120 --> 04:06:35.120
[Amit Varma]: This is the best kind of conversation.

04:06:35.120 --> 04:06:50.120
[Guest 1]: While we were on Wajid Ali Shah, one of the really interesting discoveries I made fairly recently was that when Satyajit Ray was making Shatranj Ke Khiladi, his first choice for Wajid Ali Shah was Asrani.

04:06:50.120 --> 04:06:51.120
[Guest 1]: Asrani?

04:06:51.120 --> 04:06:52.120
[Guest 1]: He wanted Asrani.

04:06:52.120 --> 04:06:54.120
[Unknown]: Which might have been quite interesting actually.

04:06:54.120 --> 04:06:57.120
[Guest 1]: Maybe not the perfect physical fit.

04:06:57.120 --> 04:06:59.120
[Guest 1]: But that might have been interesting.

04:06:59.120 --> 04:07:00.120
[Guest 2]: But Amjad was a good fit.

04:07:00.120 --> 04:07:01.120
[Guest 2]: He was a very good fit.

04:07:01.120 --> 04:07:03.120
[Guest 1]: He worked very well eventually.

04:07:03.120 --> 04:07:19.120
[Guest 1]: But this came from the letters that Ray and Suresh Jindal exchanged, which are collected in this new book on Shatranj Ke Khiladi, where Suresh Jindal reproduces one of the early letters, where Ray is saying, I'd like to sort of, you know, just meet Asrani to talk about this.

04:07:19.120 --> 04:07:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Maybe Asrani refused to expose his left nipple.

04:07:22.120 --> 04:07:23.120
[Amit Varma]: Possibly.

04:07:23.120 --> 04:07:24.120
[Guest 2]: Anyway, sorry, carry on.

04:07:24.120 --> 04:07:29.120
[Guest 2]: Asrani being an FTII graduate said, I'll do the rest.

04:07:29.120 --> 04:07:33.120
[Unknown]: I'll show you the right nipple.

04:07:33.120 --> 04:07:42.120
[Guest 2]: So anyway, so street singer had that Babul Mora Nahiya Chutona, first time with Wajid Ali Shah, iconic song.

04:07:42.120 --> 04:07:44.120
[Guest 2]: And then Kanan Devi was there.

04:07:44.120 --> 04:07:46.120
[Guest 2]: Kanan Devi also used to sing some of the great songs.

04:07:46.120 --> 04:07:54.120
[Guest 2]: But the Kanan Devi is known for that one song after she also moved to Bombay, because eventually things started shutting down in Kolkata.

04:07:54.120 --> 04:08:00.120
[Guest 2]: Largely because the partition meant that almost 60% of the audience went away.

04:08:00.120 --> 04:08:03.120
[Guest 2]: So the commercially films became difficult.

04:08:03.120 --> 04:08:10.120
[Guest 2]: But Kanan Devi, there is this very famous song called Toofaan Mer, Yeh Jeevan Hai Toofaan Mer.

04:08:10.120 --> 04:08:12.120
[Guest 2]: Huge hit of the early 40s.

04:08:12.120 --> 04:08:23.120
[Guest 2]: Anyway, but if anybody is interested ever to, if you have the time and the inclination, dive a bit deeper into KL Sehgal, you will not be disappointed if you are keeping an open mind about it.

04:08:23.120 --> 04:08:30.120
[Amit Varma]: What I'm going to ask both of you to do is I'm going to ask both of you to make a Spotify playlist or maybe multiple Spotify playlists.

04:08:30.120 --> 04:08:35.120
[Amit Varma]: So music that you love from that era or whatever, categorize it as you want, which is why I said maybe multiple ones.

04:08:35.120 --> 04:08:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And I'll link them from the show notes.

04:08:37.120 --> 04:08:40.120
[Amit Varma]: So if you can do that for me, that'll be quite...

04:08:40.120 --> 04:08:52.120
[Guest 2]: I have some Spotify playlist of the episodes that we did of Haal Chaal, done by people who liked that episode so much that every little snippet of song or something that we would do, they would note it down and then they would have the...

04:08:52.120 --> 04:08:53.120
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful.

04:08:53.120 --> 04:08:56.120
[Amit Varma]: So I'm now outsourcing that to you, though I know you're very busy.

04:08:56.120 --> 04:08:58.120
[Unknown]: So anyway, we were in 60s, right?

04:08:58.120 --> 04:08:59.120
[Unknown]: Correct, long way to go.

04:08:59.120 --> 04:09:00.120
[Guest 2]: We'll carry on.

04:09:00.120 --> 04:09:10.120
[Guest 2]: 70s, I think I would say that there are a bunch of films of, I mean, the whole parallel cinema movement.

04:09:10.120 --> 04:09:15.120
[Guest 2]: Like for instance, I mean, late 60s, 70s, I would definitely again recommend Farah Akash.

04:09:15.120 --> 04:09:18.120
[Guest 2]: I think people have watched Rajinikanth enough.

04:09:18.120 --> 04:09:20.120
[Guest 2]: So that's a good movie.

04:09:20.120 --> 04:09:30.120
[Guest 2]: See, during that time, even Sara Akash, these are all stories of this Nai Kahani movement that was happening in India, in Hindi literature.

04:09:30.120 --> 04:09:34.120
[Guest 2]: So Sara Akash also is a story from the Nai Kahani movement.

04:09:34.120 --> 04:09:43.120
[Guest 2]: Rajinikanth, which was written by, the original story was by a lady called Munnu Bhandari, who passed away just during the pandemic.

04:09:43.120 --> 04:09:50.120
[Guest 2]: Who was married to Rajendra Yadav, who wrote Sara Akash.

04:09:50.120 --> 04:09:52.120
[Guest 2]: I was going to bring that connection.

04:09:52.120 --> 04:09:55.120
[Guest 2]: And so her story was called Yeh Sach Hai.

04:09:55.120 --> 04:09:57.120
[Guest 2]: It starts off beautifully.

04:09:57.120 --> 04:10:00.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, the way she starts Yeh Sach Hai.

04:10:00.120 --> 04:10:02.120
[Guest 2]: So yeah, those two Bhuvan Shom as well.

04:10:02.120 --> 04:10:11.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, Suhasini Mule and Pal Dutt and sort of interesting kind of a film, which people can watch.

04:10:11.120 --> 04:10:17.120
[Guest 2]: In Hollywood, again, I think we've never come back to the Brian D. Palmer conversation.

04:10:17.120 --> 04:10:24.120
[Guest 2]: But I mean, I was saying that earlier, people have watched Coppola and Godfather and everything.

04:10:24.120 --> 04:10:27.120
[Guest 2]: But you know, there is a Coppola movie called The Conversations.

04:10:27.120 --> 04:10:31.120
[Guest 2]: That's a thing that I would suggest.

04:10:31.120 --> 04:10:33.120
[Guest 2]: There's an actor called John Kazal.

04:10:33.120 --> 04:10:36.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if people know enough about him.

04:10:36.120 --> 04:10:39.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so John Kazal is a guy who only acted in five films.

04:10:39.120 --> 04:10:41.120
[Guest 2]: All were nominated for Oscars.

04:10:41.120 --> 04:10:43.120
[Unknown]: Two won Best Oscar film.

04:10:43.120 --> 04:10:45.120
[Amit Varma]: And he was dying during Deer Hunter.

04:10:45.120 --> 04:10:47.120
[Guest 1]: Deer Hunter also.

04:10:47.120 --> 04:10:49.120
[Guest 1]: Godfather and Godfather.

04:10:49.120 --> 04:10:51.120
[Guest 2]: And Godfather, yeah, both the Godfathers.

04:10:51.120 --> 04:10:53.120
[Guest 2]: And then he was there in Conversations.

04:10:53.120 --> 04:10:56.120
[Guest 2]: And he was Meryl Streep's boyfriend at the time.

04:10:56.120 --> 04:11:04.120
[Guest 2]: Meryl Streep, in fact, John Kazal and Pacino were best of buddies because they were in the theater scene.

04:11:04.120 --> 04:11:11.120
[Guest 2]: And they would act in a lot of Broadway plays and stuff.

04:11:11.120 --> 04:11:14.120
[Guest 2]: And then Kazal came in through Pacino.

04:11:14.120 --> 04:11:21.120
[Guest 2]: And then by the time Deer Hunter was almost completing shooting, he had contracted cancer.

04:11:21.120 --> 04:11:26.120
[Guest 2]: And Meryl Streep, same, it's like that Katharine Hepburn story.

04:11:26.120 --> 04:11:29.120
[Guest 2]: She absolutely cared for him till the end.

04:11:29.120 --> 04:11:32.120
[Guest 2]: And therefore, anyway, that's a different thing.

04:11:32.120 --> 04:11:37.120
[Guest 2]: But I mean, maybe Jai will pipe in on Brian De Palma.

04:11:37.120 --> 04:11:43.120
[Guest 2]: A guy who possibly has, again, the later work possibly has not held up.

04:11:43.120 --> 04:11:50.120
[Guest 2]: But during that time, he used to make some quite interesting films.

04:11:50.120 --> 04:11:52.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, there is a movie called Sisters.

04:11:52.120 --> 04:11:54.120
[Guest 1]: Sisters is great.

04:11:54.120 --> 04:11:58.120
[Guest 1]: Well, to me, I mean, obviously, no disrespect to any of the others.

04:11:58.120 --> 04:12:04.120
[Guest 1]: Because they all, I mean, The Godfather and The Godfather Part 2 are just stunningly great films.

04:12:04.120 --> 04:12:06.120
[Guest 1]: And what Scorsese did, etc.

04:12:06.120 --> 04:12:11.120
[Guest 1]: But to me personally, De Palma is the most interesting of all of them.

04:12:11.120 --> 04:12:19.120
[Guest 1]: In terms of his understanding of cinema and his ability to just take enormous risks.

04:12:19.120 --> 04:12:24.120
[Guest 1]: And just make films that were incredibly uneven in places.

04:12:24.120 --> 04:12:29.120
[Guest 1]: But, you know, just put everything that he needed to put into them.

04:12:29.120 --> 04:12:31.120
[Guest 2]: So, Blow Out is one.

04:12:31.120 --> 04:12:33.120
[Guest 2]: The Travolta.

04:12:33.120 --> 04:12:39.120
[Guest 2]: So, Blow Out and Conversation are the two films that I actually sort of did a session about jointly last year.

04:12:39.120 --> 04:12:44.120
[Guest 2]: He mixes the sound and the video together.

04:12:44.120 --> 04:12:50.120
[Guest 2]: And then realizes what's happened is very different from what he was thinking.

04:12:50.120 --> 04:12:55.120
[Guest 2]: It's also a part tribute to Blow Up and Antonioni's Blow Up.

04:12:55.120 --> 04:12:58.120
[Guest 2]: And Sisters, again.

04:12:58.120 --> 04:13:00.120
[Guest 1]: Sisters is an absolute favorite of mine.

04:13:00.120 --> 04:13:02.120
[Guest 2]: Of De Palma.

04:13:02.120 --> 04:13:08.120
[Guest 2]: So, again, people who are, and of course, again, if people have not watched Altman,

04:13:08.120 --> 04:13:12.120
[Guest 2]: you know, one is an Altman noir called Long Goodbye.

04:13:12.120 --> 04:13:14.120
[Guest 1]: Long Goodbye, yeah.

04:13:14.120 --> 04:13:16.120
[Guest 2]: Which has Elliot Gould, who.

04:13:16.120 --> 04:13:22.120
[Guest 1]: Best known to people of my generation as Ross and Monica's dad in Friends.

04:13:22.120 --> 04:13:28.120
[Guest 1]: Not at all known to people of the generation after mine because Friends is cancelled.

04:13:28.120 --> 04:13:30.120
[Guest 2]: Friends is also cancelled. All whites.

04:13:30.120 --> 04:13:36.120
[Guest 1]: No, I mean, also, apparently full of jokes that are, that trigger people.

04:13:36.120 --> 04:13:39.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but you know, if you look closely enough, everything is cancelled.

04:13:39.120 --> 04:13:44.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so, Altman had Long Goodbye, Altman had Nashville.

04:13:44.120 --> 04:13:45.120
[Guest 2]: I love Nashville.

04:13:45.120 --> 04:13:50.120
[Guest 2]: Nashville is like, how can you make a film where there are some 25 characters all speaking simultaneously?

04:13:50.120 --> 04:13:52.120
[Amit Varma]: And there is all kinds of music.

04:13:52.120 --> 04:13:55.120
[Amit Varma]: I think Jai might remember it. Nashville must have been in one of my top 10 lists,

04:13:55.120 --> 04:13:57.120
[Amit Varma]: which I used to give in my callow days.

04:13:57.120 --> 04:13:59.120
[Guest 1]: And then.

04:13:59.120 --> 04:14:02.120
[Guest 1]: You still haven't given me your top 10 list from your non-callow days.

04:14:02.120 --> 04:14:04.120
[Amit Varma]: I'll have to recommend five at the end of this.

04:14:04.120 --> 04:14:07.120
[Guest 1]: So, five Bansalis and what else?

04:14:07.120 --> 04:14:10.120
[Amit Varma]: Nice one. I mean, we could actually.

04:14:10.120 --> 04:14:12.120
[Guest 1]: You can't include Khamoshi because Khamoshi is the Bansali.

04:14:12.120 --> 04:14:16.120
[Guest 1]: Everybody says that's my favorite Bansali because, you know, it's the most understated.

04:14:16.120 --> 04:14:21.120
[Amit Varma]: That is the only tolerable Bansali, but I didn't like even that, actually.

04:14:21.120 --> 04:14:24.120
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, I'll come to my list at the end.

04:14:24.120 --> 04:14:26.120
[Amit Varma]: First, let us take our journey through the decades.

04:14:26.120 --> 04:14:30.120
[Amit Varma]: Like, in a sense, the journey of Subrat from what we understand it today is really,

04:14:30.120 --> 04:14:33.120
[Amit Varma]: you could write a book and call it from Bansali to Beyonce.

04:14:33.120 --> 04:14:36.120
[Unknown]: Because she confessed to liking both, I think.

04:14:36.120 --> 04:14:43.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah. So, I mean, I think, yeah. So, again, I think people must watch some of them.

04:14:43.120 --> 04:14:47.120
[Guest 2]: For instance, Altman. And I guess one of the things, I mean,

04:14:47.120 --> 04:14:51.120
[Guest 2]: just the four, five of them that came up at the same time, right?

04:14:51.120 --> 04:14:59.120
[Guest 2]: Scorsese, Coppola, Brandy Palmer. Who am I missing?

04:14:59.120 --> 04:15:01.120
[Guest 2]: Lucas around that time.

04:15:01.120 --> 04:15:06.120
[Guest 2]: Lucas, Kubrick, Altman. So, I mean.

04:15:06.120 --> 04:15:07.120
[Guest 2]: Prakash Mehra.

04:15:07.120 --> 04:15:14.120
[Guest 2]: Prakash Mehra as well. But, you know, it's funny that, I think, Spielberg also at the time.

04:15:14.120 --> 04:15:20.120
[Guest 2]: So, it's funny that Spielberg and Scorsese, who, I mean, Spielberg always knew

04:15:20.120 --> 04:15:23.120
[Guest 2]: some kind of a thing about the pulse of the mass.

04:15:23.120 --> 04:15:29.120
[Guest 2]: And I think he was very good at that and not too sort of taken in by vision, etc.

04:15:29.120 --> 04:15:31.120
[Guest 2]: And very sort of that kind of a guy.

04:15:31.120 --> 04:15:37.120
[Guest 2]: And I think Scorsese, because his films were in some sense very sort of internal.

04:15:37.120 --> 04:15:40.120
[Guest 2]: They're always biopic like with story of a person.

04:15:40.120 --> 04:15:41.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, everything.

04:15:41.120 --> 04:15:46.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, including some of his names of his films are also very sort of.

04:15:46.120 --> 04:15:51.120
[Guest 2]: Taxi Driver, King of Comedy, Aviator, so on and so forth.

04:15:51.120 --> 04:15:56.120
[Guest 2]: So, I think that's why they kind of, whereas the two guys, whereas Coppola was big theme guy.

04:15:56.120 --> 04:16:00.120
[Guest 2]: And I think once the time went, those themes didn't resonate.

04:16:00.120 --> 04:16:05.120
[Guest 2]: And the other guy was, I think, Palmer, who was very style sort of driven guy.

04:16:05.120 --> 04:16:09.120
[Guest 2]: I think when the style went, I think he got a little dated.

04:16:09.120 --> 04:16:11.120
[Guest 2]: He could not keep up with the style.

04:16:11.120 --> 04:16:14.120
[Guest 2]: But during those times, those guys just did fantastic work.

04:16:14.120 --> 04:16:18.120
[Guest 1]: From the same generation, there's also, you know, with a little before them,

04:16:18.120 --> 04:16:22.120
[Guest 1]: there was Arthur Penn, who also, you know, and one of the things,

04:16:22.120 --> 04:16:26.120
[Guest 1]: one of the conversations I'm hoping to have sometime soon with my online group is

04:16:26.120 --> 04:16:35.120
[Guest 1]: some of the really under the radar films of the 70s that belong broadly to this group of directors.

04:16:35.120 --> 04:16:38.120
[Guest 1]: So, one of the films, for instance, is The Missouri Breaks,

04:16:38.120 --> 04:16:43.120
[Guest 1]: which has Marlon Brando and Jack Nicholson, which is directed by Arthur Penn,

04:16:43.120 --> 04:16:45.120
[Guest 1]: which is a quite interesting film.

04:16:45.120 --> 04:16:49.120
[Guest 1]: It's not really a major work in that sense.

04:16:49.120 --> 04:16:55.120
[Guest 1]: But what is interesting that is also Scarecrow with Gene Hackman and the very young Al Pacino,

04:16:55.120 --> 04:16:59.120
[Guest 1]: which is interesting that some of these that are worth looking at.

04:16:59.120 --> 04:17:06.120
[Guest 1]: When Coppola was sort of, when he was being set up as the leader of this group of directors,

04:17:06.120 --> 04:17:10.120
[Guest 1]: Peter Bogdanovich was right up there with it, except that Bogdanovich, of course,

04:17:10.120 --> 04:17:14.120
[Guest 1]: he made two or three very acclaimed films and then he sort of faded.

04:17:14.120 --> 04:17:21.120
[Guest 2]: The Last Picture Show is just fantastic, Paper Moon, even Bogdanovich's The Noir.

04:17:21.120 --> 04:17:26.120
[Guest 2]: Even Targets, which was with Boris Karlovich, which is an interesting meta film.

04:17:26.120 --> 04:17:31.120
[Guest 1]: But, of course, Bogdanovich eventually sort of, I think, went more in the direction of being a film historian.

04:17:31.120 --> 04:17:33.120
[Guest 2]: Nice interviews, great conversations.

04:17:33.120 --> 04:17:39.120
[Guest 1]: We're talking about book recommendations, Bogdanovich's Book of Conversations with Orson Welles.

04:17:39.120 --> 04:17:47.120
[Guest 1]: This is Orson Welles, one of the most interesting, it's easily up there with the Hitchcock True Four book,

04:17:47.120 --> 04:17:50.120
[Guest 1]: which always gets so much publicity.

04:17:50.120 --> 04:17:54.120
[Guest 2]: Actually, Bogdanovich did a screwball comedy for the 70s.

04:17:54.120 --> 04:17:57.120
[Guest 1]: What's Up Dog with Barbra Streisand.

04:17:57.120 --> 04:18:00.120
[Guest 1]: A tribute to Bringing Our Baby, because he was a huge fan of Howard Hawks.

04:18:00.120 --> 04:18:04.120
[Guest 1]: So Bogdanovich was also one of the great champions of Howard Hawks.

04:18:04.120 --> 04:18:06.120
[Guest 2]: Did we mention Hawks?

04:18:06.120 --> 04:18:08.120
[Unknown]: We have not mentioned Hawks.

04:18:08.120 --> 04:18:10.120
[Unknown]: We've mentioned him now.

04:18:10.120 --> 04:18:15.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so along with Preston Sturgess, the other guy was Howard Hawks,

04:18:15.120 --> 04:18:22.120
[Guest 2]: who had this whole idea of something called a Hawksian woman or the Hawksian heroine, right?

04:18:22.120 --> 04:18:30.120
[Guest 2]: So who, like the Barbra Steinway, and Bringing Our Baby, the front page, what was the name of the film?

04:18:30.120 --> 04:18:31.120
[Guest 1]: His Girl Friday.

04:18:31.120 --> 04:18:32.120
[Guest 2]: His Girl Friday.

04:18:32.120 --> 04:18:39.120
[Guest 1]: So he also is another director, and this is something I've experienced firsthand through a somewhat acrimonious exchange online.

04:18:39.120 --> 04:18:42.120
[Guest 1]: The sort of director that you just sort of end up having to defend,

04:18:42.120 --> 04:18:47.120
[Guest 1]: because he was very much, in some ways, in some superficially interpreted ways,

04:18:47.120 --> 04:18:50.120
[Guest 1]: he was very much a male director.

04:18:50.120 --> 04:18:53.120
[Guest 1]: He had a masculine, he was a man's man from a certain period.

04:18:53.120 --> 04:18:55.120
[Guest 1]: And some of that gets reflected in his films.

04:18:55.120 --> 04:18:59.120
[Guest 1]: Though for my money, his best films have fascinating women characters.

04:18:59.120 --> 04:19:01.120
[Guest 2]: And who are always retorting.

04:19:01.120 --> 04:19:02.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, yeah.

04:19:02.120 --> 04:19:11.120
[Guest 1]: But of course, this ties into the ways in which one has different ideological lenses while watching films.

04:19:11.120 --> 04:19:15.120
[Guest 1]: His Girl Friday, which to my mind is such an empowering film from,

04:19:15.120 --> 04:19:19.120
[Guest 1]: though of course I'm speaking as a guy also, from the gender parity point of view,

04:19:19.120 --> 04:19:27.120
[Guest 1]: especially because it was a remake of a play and a film where Hawks and his writers took a male character

04:19:27.120 --> 04:19:34.120
[Guest 1]: and turned that male character into a woman with a lot of power within the story.

04:19:34.120 --> 04:19:38.120
[Guest 1]: But I had a bit of an online argument once with someone who said,

04:19:38.120 --> 04:19:47.120
[Guest 1]: His Girl Friday is a chauvinistic film because it ends with this woman following Cary Grant out of the room.

04:19:47.120 --> 04:19:54.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think people who do all this, their lives are so sad because they're not taking in art for its own sake,

04:19:54.120 --> 04:19:56.120
[Amit Varma]: for the beauty and the joy that is in art.

04:19:56.120 --> 04:19:58.120
[Guest 1]: They're putting a lens on everything.

04:19:58.120 --> 04:20:01.120
[Amit Varma]: What can I get offended by to show how virtuous I am?

04:20:01.120 --> 04:20:05.120
[Guest 1]: Well, you know, we should keep in mind that we are after all three men talking about this right now.

04:20:05.120 --> 04:20:07.120
[Guest 1]: So maybe we should be a bit circumspect.

04:20:07.120 --> 04:20:10.120
[Guest 1]: But it's not just art for art's sake.

04:20:10.120 --> 04:20:17.120
[Guest 1]: It's also that, you know, once my problem with this sort of ideological interpretation of a certain sort

04:20:17.120 --> 04:20:23.120
[Guest 1]: is that once you have those blinkers on, you sometimes just, you know, prevent yourself from seeing the entirety of the work.

04:20:23.120 --> 04:20:26.120
[Guest 1]: You just sort of, you see only what you need to see.

04:20:26.120 --> 04:20:31.120
[Guest 1]: And again, coming back to what we said earlier, that, you know, you need a single takeaway from the work.

04:20:31.120 --> 04:20:37.120
[Guest 1]: Is this film, is it a liberal film or a progressive film?

04:20:37.120 --> 04:20:40.120
[Guest 1]: Is it progressive or regressive? Is it liberal or conservative?

04:20:40.120 --> 04:20:43.120
[Guest 1]: And you're looking for or you're asking reductive questions like that.

04:20:43.120 --> 04:20:48.120
[Guest 1]: You will only, you know, get reductive answers, which you will supply yourself.

04:20:48.120 --> 04:20:53.120
[Guest 1]: Whereas a lot of the sorts of films we are talking about are much more complex in terms of their entirety,

04:20:53.120 --> 04:20:55.120
[Guest 1]: in terms of what they're doing.

04:20:55.120 --> 04:21:00.120
[Guest 1]: And I'm not even saying that somebody who makes this point about a Howard Hawks film or a John Ford film is wrong.

04:21:00.120 --> 04:21:02.120
[Guest 1]: I'm not saying that.

04:21:02.120 --> 04:21:04.120
[Amit Varma]: But it is one point. There is so much else.

04:21:04.120 --> 04:21:06.120
[Guest 1]: It is one way of looking at something.

04:21:06.120 --> 04:21:11.120
[Guest 1]: And there are counterpoints to it within the same work.

04:21:11.120 --> 04:21:19.120
[Guest 2]: So yeah, so, but yeah, so Hawks is, I mean, Hawks also, Hawks directed The Big Sleep, the original Philip Marlowe,

04:21:19.120 --> 04:21:23.120
[Guest 1]: which is one of the most incomprehensible great films ever made at the plot level.

04:21:23.120 --> 04:21:32.120
[Guest 1]: Because even Raymond Chandler had no idea who the murderer was, who one of the murderers was.

04:21:32.120 --> 04:21:36.120
[Guest 2]: And then he also, did he do To Have and Have Not?

04:21:36.120 --> 04:21:38.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah. So he did To Have and Have Not.

04:21:38.120 --> 04:21:41.120
[Guest 2]: This is a trivia quiz question.

04:21:41.120 --> 04:21:43.120
[Unknown]: Faulkner, Hemingway.

04:21:43.120 --> 04:21:44.120
[Unknown]: To Have and Have Not.

04:21:44.120 --> 04:21:45.120
[Unknown]: Has he spoiled the question?

