[Guest 1]: He spoiled the question.

04:21:46.120 --> 04:21:47.120
[Unknown]: Why do you spoil questions?

04:21:47.120 --> 04:21:49.120
[Unknown]: Oh, it was an actual question.

04:21:49.120 --> 04:21:51.120
[Unknown]: I was asking Amit.

04:21:51.120 --> 04:21:57.120
[Guest 2]: The only film which has a screenplay that's done by two Nobel Prize winners.

04:21:57.120 --> 04:21:59.120
[Amit Varma]: Amazing question. You missed it.

04:21:59.120 --> 04:22:01.120
[Guest 2]: Anyway, carry on.

04:22:01.120 --> 04:22:05.120
[Guest 2]: Anyway, so we went to Hawks because we were on Bogdanovich.

04:22:05.120 --> 04:22:09.120
[Guest 2]: So what was Bogdanovich doing? What's Up Dog, Last Picture Show, Paper Moon.

04:22:09.120 --> 04:22:11.120
[Guest 2]: I think after that he disappeared.

04:22:11.120 --> 04:22:18.120
[Guest 2]: 70s, if you take Hindi, I think some of the masala, you know, Vijayanand, Goldie,

04:22:18.120 --> 04:22:23.120
[Guest 2]: which is Johnny Mera Naam and Jyoti, great fun films.

04:22:23.120 --> 04:22:30.120
[Guest 1]: There's also the little film which I realized that no one, no young person, quote unquote,

04:22:30.120 --> 04:22:32.120
[Guest 1]: in any of the classes I've taught has seen.

04:22:32.120 --> 04:22:38.120
[Guest 1]: Many of them have heard of it, Sholay, 1975.

04:22:38.120 --> 04:22:44.120
[Guest 1]: I was having this discussion about Sanjeev Kumar the other day, you know,

04:22:44.120 --> 04:22:49.120
[Guest 1]: who, as you know, he passed away at a young age in the 1980s.

04:22:49.120 --> 04:22:53.120
[Guest 1]: And therefore is sort of completely under the radar of many people

04:22:53.120 --> 04:22:56.120
[Guest 1]: who were not around when those films were coming out.

04:22:56.120 --> 04:22:59.120
[Guest 1]: So there are people who sort of vaguely know who Sanjeev Kumar is

04:22:59.120 --> 04:23:03.120
[Guest 1]: because they've seen him in a poster of Sholay with a shawl.

04:23:03.120 --> 04:23:05.120
[Guest 1]: So they sort of figured that that's the person.

04:23:05.120 --> 04:23:10.120
[Guest 1]: So these are people who know Sholay by name.

04:23:10.120 --> 04:23:13.120
[Guest 1]: Some of them know The Godfather by name.

04:23:13.120 --> 04:23:16.120
[Guest 1]: But watching these films is out of the question.

04:23:16.120 --> 04:23:17.120
[Guest 1]: End of rant.

04:23:17.120 --> 04:23:20.120
[Amit Varma]: Brutal, brutal. I mean, there should be, there should, like,

04:23:20.120 --> 04:23:24.120
[Amit Varma]: if there's a serial killer in Delhi who is going around killing young people

04:23:24.120 --> 04:23:27.120
[Unknown]: who don't appreciate cinema adequately.

04:23:27.120 --> 04:23:29.120
[Unknown]: The needle of suspicion.

04:23:29.120 --> 04:23:32.120
[Unknown]: The needle of suspicion has to go to, you know.

04:23:35.120 --> 04:23:38.120
[Guest 1]: It would have to be the grandson of the disco killer killer.

04:23:38.120 --> 04:23:39.120
[Amit Varma]: The disco dancer killer.

04:23:39.120 --> 04:23:42.120
[Amit Varma]: We don't know your antecedents too well.

04:23:42.120 --> 04:23:44.120
[Amit Varma]: So what is one to say?

04:23:44.120 --> 04:23:47.120
[Amit Varma]: All right, back to Subrath for the 800th time.

04:23:47.120 --> 04:23:49.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so the 80s, yeah, I mean, the 80s.

04:23:49.120 --> 04:23:51.120
[Guest 2]: 80s is only Back to the Future and Mr. India.

04:23:51.120 --> 04:23:54.120
[Guest 2]: Back to the Future, Mr. India.

04:23:54.120 --> 04:23:56.120
[Guest 1]: Mr. India is good fun.

04:23:56.120 --> 04:23:58.120
[Amit Varma]: Amit's favorite Sridevi film, Nagina.

04:23:58.120 --> 04:24:01.120
[Amit Varma]: I thought you were going to say John Huston's dead, but never mind.

04:24:01.120 --> 04:24:02.120
[Guest 2]: Nagina pe aage.

04:24:02.120 --> 04:24:04.120
[Unknown]: Ungli mein anguthi, anguthi mein Nagina.

04:24:04.120 --> 04:24:07.120
[Guest 2]: Harmesh Malhotra, I was the guy who used to make these Nagina films.

04:24:07.120 --> 04:24:10.120
[Guest 2]: Nigahe Nagina, Harmesh Malhotra.

04:24:10.120 --> 04:24:12.120
[Guest 2]: He made these movies.

04:24:12.120 --> 04:24:16.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, no, you don't need to know him for any other reason except this.

04:24:16.120 --> 04:24:17.120
[Unknown]: But are you recommending these films?

04:24:17.120 --> 04:24:18.120
[Unknown]: No, no, no.

04:24:18.120 --> 04:24:21.120
[Guest 2]: I see, I think, if I remember right,

04:24:21.120 --> 04:24:25.120
[Guest 2]: Jai had recommended Rahul Ravel, who I can't recommend enough.

04:24:25.120 --> 04:24:27.120
[Guest 2]: He was great fun.

04:24:27.120 --> 04:24:31.120
[Guest 2]: Then I will recommend a few JP Dutta films of the 80s.

04:24:31.120 --> 04:24:32.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, of course.

04:24:32.120 --> 04:24:34.120
[Guest 1]: JP Dutta, Mukul Anand to some degree also.

04:24:34.120 --> 04:24:39.120
[Guest 1]: These are directors who had some sort of, you know, the visual sensibility at a time

04:24:39.120 --> 04:24:42.120
[Guest 1]: when there wasn't that much of it happening in the Hindi mainstream.

04:24:42.120 --> 04:24:44.120
[Guest 2]: Hatyaar and stuff.

04:24:44.120 --> 04:24:46.120
[Guest 2]: Hatyaar, Gulami.

04:24:46.120 --> 04:24:49.120
[Guest 2]: And then, of course, Rajiv Rai.

04:24:49.120 --> 04:24:56.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, maybe it was my time and whatever, the time and context in which I saw Yod.

04:24:56.120 --> 04:25:03.120
[Guest 2]: Tridev, I mean, if you want to watch an 80s film in India, you know, watch Tridev.

04:25:03.120 --> 04:25:07.120
[Guest 2]: Tridev is the ultimate 80s masala film.

04:25:07.120 --> 04:25:08.120
[Guest 2]: There are three big heroes.

04:25:08.120 --> 04:25:10.120
[Guest 2]: There is Amrish Puri.

04:25:10.120 --> 04:25:15.120
[Guest 2]: And every single guy that you see in 80s movie Peeche as one of the henchmen is there.

04:25:15.120 --> 04:25:21.120
[Guest 2]: In fact, all of them are there together in one song, where they are trying to disrobe

04:25:21.120 --> 04:25:26.120
[Guest 2]: Sangeeta Bijlani, you know, through the song one after one.

04:25:26.120 --> 04:25:28.120
[Guest 1]: The much bigger villains gallery though was in Naseeb.

04:25:28.120 --> 04:25:30.120
[Guest 2]: Naseeb also, yes.

04:25:30.120 --> 04:25:38.120
[Guest 2]: But, you know, I have personal liking for Dan Dhanoa, Mahesh Anand, these sidey guys.

04:25:38.120 --> 04:25:40.120
[Guest 1]: Underappreciated sidekicks.

04:25:40.120 --> 04:25:45.120
[Guest 2]: Dan Dhanoa, Mahesh Anand, Dilip Tahil is there.

04:25:45.120 --> 04:25:50.120
[Guest 2]: What is that, that Sapru, Tej Sapru, Seema Sapru's brother.

04:25:50.120 --> 04:25:54.120
[Guest 2]: Seema Sapru was the person who was there in every Ram Seh brother, Ram Seh films.

04:25:54.120 --> 04:25:57.120
[Guest 2]: And in fact, 80s Ram Seh films should also be watched.

04:25:57.120 --> 04:25:58.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah, we haven't even come to Ram Seh.

04:25:58.120 --> 04:26:04.120
[Guest 1]: I mean, Shamu Dasgupta's book, my friend Shamu Dasgupta's book, which I wrote an introduction for.

04:26:04.120 --> 04:26:10.120
[Guest 2]: Loga Zameen Ke Niche Hai was the early 70s film, which was the film that established Ram Seh.

04:26:10.120 --> 04:26:16.120
[Guest 2]: This Imtiaz, the brother of Amjad Khan is the character, sort of the bad guy there.

04:26:16.120 --> 04:26:21.120
[Guest 2]: But 80s Ram Seh really took off with one movie called Vee Rana.

04:26:21.120 --> 04:26:24.120
[Guest 2]: Purana Mandir.

04:26:24.120 --> 04:26:31.120
[Guest 1]: Which unofficially though, it's not there on any records apparently because of the way records were maintained or not maintained for smaller towns.

04:26:31.120 --> 04:26:36.120
[Guest 1]: But apparently it was the second biggest hit of the year in Hindi cinema.

04:26:36.120 --> 04:26:37.120
[Guest 2]: Manish Bahl's debut.

04:26:37.120 --> 04:26:38.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

04:26:38.120 --> 04:26:40.120
[Amit Varma]: And it has some good songs also.

04:26:40.120 --> 04:26:44.120
[Amit Varma]: Mujhe lag raha hai ki show notes banate banate, is episode phule main paagal ho jaunga.

04:26:44.120 --> 04:26:45.120
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

04:26:45.120 --> 04:26:49.120
[Guest 1]: You'll have to, just in the interest of research, you'll have to watch all these films.

04:26:49.120 --> 04:26:52.120
[Amit Varma]: Fat chance of me doing that.

04:26:52.120 --> 04:26:56.120
[Guest 2]: But yeah, just putting the show notes only will take a week.

04:26:56.120 --> 04:27:01.120
[Guest 2]: People should watch Vee Rana.

04:27:01.120 --> 04:27:04.120
[Guest 2]: People should watch some of those early Govinda films.

04:27:04.120 --> 04:27:05.120
[Guest 2]: And of course, Babbar Subhash.

04:27:05.120 --> 04:27:07.120
[Guest 2]: Babbar Subhash we've already spoken about.

04:27:07.120 --> 04:27:09.120
[Guest 2]: But some of these early Govinda films.

04:27:09.120 --> 04:27:11.120
[Guest 2]: The guy was so happy.

04:27:11.120 --> 04:27:13.120
[Guest 1]: He was a force of nature.

04:27:13.120 --> 04:27:15.120
[Guest 1]: You know, even before the David Dhawan phases.

04:27:15.120 --> 04:27:16.120
[Unknown]: Before that I'm saying.

04:27:16.120 --> 04:27:17.120
[Unknown]: Yeah.

04:27:17.120 --> 04:27:18.120
[Unknown]: So, you know, films like Ilzaam.

04:27:18.120 --> 04:27:20.120
[Guest 1]: I remember having a sense.

04:27:20.120 --> 04:27:26.120
[Guest 1]: Though I think I was already getting phased out of the world of Hindi cinema around that time.

04:27:26.120 --> 04:27:29.120
[Guest 1]: My mother would end up being a big Govinda fan in the 90s.

04:27:29.120 --> 04:27:33.120
[Guest 1]: But I remember just having a sense that here is someone who is very unusual.

04:27:33.120 --> 04:27:35.120
[Guest 2]: Who's just this presence.

04:27:35.120 --> 04:27:37.120
[Amit Varma]: Very uninhibited.

04:27:37.120 --> 04:27:39.120
[Amit Varma]: So far you've made predictions about two young Bollywood stars.

04:27:39.120 --> 04:27:40.120
[Amit Varma]: One is Govinda.

04:27:40.120 --> 04:27:41.120
[Amit Varma]: One is Ranveer Singh.

04:27:41.120 --> 04:27:42.120
[Amit Varma]: So well done.

04:27:42.120 --> 04:27:44.120
[Amit Varma]: That's a good track record.

04:27:44.120 --> 04:27:50.120
[Guest 2]: About Govinda is, yeah, even on Govinda he felt that there is something.

04:27:50.120 --> 04:27:52.120
[Unknown]: He felt that there is something and it turned out that there was.

04:27:52.120 --> 04:27:56.120
[Guest 2]: So Ilzaam, I mean, although I am a street dancer.

04:27:56.120 --> 04:28:01.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, just great.

04:28:01.120 --> 04:28:03.120
[Guest 2]: Govinda was good fun.

04:28:03.120 --> 04:28:05.120
[Guest 2]: Even before David Dhawan.

04:28:05.120 --> 04:28:11.120
[Guest 2]: I think in Hollywood, like I said, you can do some of this.

04:28:11.120 --> 04:28:14.120
[Guest 2]: Peter Weyer watching and you can do.

04:28:14.120 --> 04:28:19.120
[Guest 1]: We haven't even really got into world cinema or what we call world cinema.

04:28:19.120 --> 04:28:25.120
[Guest 1]: Anyway, but I think, you know, we just started off with Amit asking us for five recommendations each.

04:28:25.120 --> 04:28:28.120
[Unknown]: We've basically gone through all of film history.

04:28:28.120 --> 04:28:33.120
[Guest 1]: And you need to come and help me teach this class that I'm starting from next month.

04:28:33.120 --> 04:28:38.120
[Guest 1]: Especially with all the PC Barua and KL Sehgal context.

04:28:38.120 --> 04:28:40.120
[Unknown]: Happy to do.

04:28:40.120 --> 04:28:42.120
[Amit Varma]: They can't cancel PC Barua.

04:28:42.120 --> 04:28:44.120
[Amit Varma]: Because he's PC.

04:28:44.120 --> 04:28:46.120
[Guest 2]: Sorry.

04:28:46.120 --> 04:28:49.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, we have not done world cinema.

04:28:49.120 --> 04:28:51.120
[Guest 2]: But 80s was a good time for some of that also.

04:28:51.120 --> 04:28:53.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, absolutely.

04:28:53.120 --> 04:28:56.120
[Guest 1]: So Amit, you have to now give us your list.

04:28:56.120 --> 04:28:57.120
[Guest 2]: Let him finish first.

04:28:57.120 --> 04:28:58.120
[Guest 1]: Oh, okay.

04:28:58.120 --> 04:28:59.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, 90s.

04:28:59.120 --> 04:29:02.120
[Guest 2]: Then, of course, there are, I think I did mention John Dahl.

04:29:02.120 --> 04:29:05.120
[Guest 2]: I think there are, of course, Tarantino came, Roberto Rodriguez.

04:29:05.120 --> 04:29:07.120
[Guest 2]: There are some smaller films of these guys.

04:29:07.120 --> 04:29:12.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, for instance, Jackie Brown, I think is a better Tarantino film than most.

04:29:12.120 --> 04:29:13.120
[Guest 2]: I don't know.

04:29:13.120 --> 04:29:14.120
[Guest 1]: What do you think about?

04:29:14.120 --> 04:29:19.120
[Guest 1]: Well, my favorite is actually Pulp Fiction, which is a very boring thing to say.

04:29:19.120 --> 04:29:26.120
[Guest 2]: But yeah, I mean, we've missed one of his strengths, as I discovered when I was just talking to him before this.

04:29:26.120 --> 04:29:36.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, the whole Wes Craven and John Carpenter stuff, Halloween and Nightmare on M3, which I just absolutely enjoyed a lot.

04:29:36.120 --> 04:29:37.120
[Guest 2]: Scream.

04:29:37.120 --> 04:29:39.120
[Guest 2]: Scream had some of the early stars.

04:29:39.120 --> 04:29:41.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, all kinds of the first Scream.

04:29:41.120 --> 04:29:55.120
[Guest 1]: The early 90s also, I just remembered because I was discussing this with someone recently, has one of the great, to my mind, action films, Terminator 2.

04:29:55.120 --> 04:29:57.120
[Unknown]: I saw it just two months back.

04:29:57.120 --> 04:30:07.120
[Guest 1]: I just find myself appreciating that film more and more because I feel again at risk of sounding like this old person who can't take too much of the new.

04:30:07.120 --> 04:30:17.120
[Guest 1]: But that isn't it, because there's another much more recent film that I love is Mad Max Fury Road, which I think was just a wonderful film.

04:30:17.120 --> 04:30:21.120
[Guest 1]: No qualification at all that it's a wonderful action film.

04:30:21.120 --> 04:30:28.120
[Guest 1]: But jokes about Christopher Nolan aside, because obviously the guy has a lot of strengths, etc.

04:30:28.120 --> 04:30:36.120
[Guest 1]: One of the problems I have with his Batman films is that the action sequences in them are so cluttered.

04:30:36.120 --> 04:30:39.120
[Guest 1]: I very often just can't make sense of them.

04:30:39.120 --> 04:30:44.120
[Guest 1]: I can't make sense of them at the level of where is one character in relation to the other character.

04:30:44.120 --> 04:30:53.120
[Guest 1]: There's such a thing as doing chaos deliberately, which is a different thing.

04:30:53.120 --> 04:31:05.120
[Guest 1]: But with some of the action sequences in Christopher Nolan's films, including the Dark Knight and so on, I just get the impression that it's just messy because he hasn't been able to declutter it.

04:31:05.120 --> 04:31:17.120
[Guest 1]: And then when I look at something like Mad Max Fury Road or The Terminator 2, those are examples to my mind of really clean action films where you're getting the thrill and the adrenaline and there's a lot going on at the same time.

04:31:17.120 --> 04:31:23.120
[Guest 1]: But you know exactly what's happening at all the time.

04:31:23.120 --> 04:31:27.120
[Guest 2]: I rewatched it two months back because I was showing it to my 13 year old.

04:31:27.120 --> 04:31:38.120
[Guest 2]: So, you are right, the first motorbike chase, this guy goes above that, you know, it's just especially you are there, right?

04:31:38.120 --> 04:31:39.120
[Guest 2]: You are right.

04:31:39.120 --> 04:31:50.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, a lot of broader Avengers and this Marvel Universe stuff, sometimes especially I can't make out what is happening because it's all three dimensional stuff that's happening.

04:31:50.120 --> 04:31:53.120
[Guest 2]: Here, it's clear, it's coming from here and going from there.

04:31:53.120 --> 04:32:00.120
[Guest 1]: So, I think that's something that you just have to acknowledge that when it happens.

04:32:00.120 --> 04:32:03.120
[Guest 1]: I don't know what you think of Mad Max Fury Road, if you've seen it or something.

04:32:03.120 --> 04:32:07.120
[Amit Varma]: I intended to see it, but I haven't seen it yet.

04:32:07.120 --> 04:32:08.120
[Amit Varma]: So, I will see it now.

04:32:08.120 --> 04:32:15.120
[Amit Varma]: But what I did read about it was somebody saying something to the effect of if you watch it at double speed, everything still makes sense.

04:32:15.120 --> 04:32:17.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know what that means.

04:32:17.120 --> 04:32:19.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't watch films at double speed, by the way.

04:32:19.120 --> 04:32:21.120
[Guest 1]: No, but I don't think you should do that.

04:32:21.120 --> 04:32:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Or there was some meta comment on it so well constructed that it, you know, whatever.

04:32:27.120 --> 04:32:35.120
[Guest 2]: Actually, the great part about 90s and 2000s that I have enjoyed.

04:32:35.120 --> 04:32:39.120
[Guest 2]: And now again, it has also started becoming a bit of a thing, which it's fine.

04:32:39.120 --> 04:32:42.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's like my early fascination for Mithun and Govinda.

04:32:42.120 --> 04:32:45.120
[Guest 2]: Then later I realized that that itself has become sort of everybody.

04:32:45.120 --> 04:32:52.120
[Guest 2]: I have always been a fan of Nicolas Cage and Keanu Reeves.

04:32:52.120 --> 04:33:00.120
[Guest 2]: And I'm so glad that today there is one separate cult of Keanu Reeves and Nicolas Cage.

04:33:00.120 --> 04:33:04.120
[Guest 2]: So much so that there is a separate film about Nicolas Cage being Nicolas Cage.

04:33:04.120 --> 04:33:07.120
[Unknown]: Which was about two months, one month back that has come out.

04:33:07.120 --> 04:33:10.120
[Amit Varma]: First time I saw Nicolas Cage was in Wild at Heart.

04:33:10.120 --> 04:33:11.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

04:33:11.120 --> 04:33:13.120
[Amit Varma]: I think it won the Golden Palm at Cannes.

04:33:13.120 --> 04:33:19.120
[Guest 2]: No, Nicolas Cage is there in, there is a John Dahl movie in which Nicolas Cage is there.

04:33:19.120 --> 04:33:22.120
[Guest 2]: I think it's called, what is it called? The Last Seduction or something.

04:33:22.120 --> 04:33:29.120
[Guest 2]: Of course, the other guy was Edward Norton, who I used to love in those late 90s films.

04:33:29.120 --> 04:33:31.120
[Guest 1]: He made a great anti-virus film.

04:33:31.120 --> 04:33:33.120
[Guest 2]: American Violence, whatever, American History.

04:33:33.120 --> 04:33:34.120
[Guest 1]: American History X.

04:33:34.120 --> 04:33:38.120
[Guest 2]: History X and Rounders as well.

04:33:38.120 --> 04:33:40.120
[Amit Varma]: You must like Rounders, it's a poker film.

04:33:40.120 --> 04:33:44.120
[Amit Varma]: I like Rounders, I mean all poker films get poker completely wrong.

04:33:44.120 --> 04:33:45.120
[Unknown]: Including this one.

04:33:45.120 --> 04:33:46.120
[Amit Varma]: But Rounders is fine.

04:33:46.120 --> 04:33:55.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it doesn't commit sacrilegious, I mean it simplifies as Hollywood must.

04:33:55.120 --> 04:34:00.120
[Guest 2]: But 90s again on the Hindi and actually 80s there is a movie called New Delhi Times.

04:34:00.120 --> 04:34:05.120
[Unknown]: This is this Shikapur and Anand Sharma, Ramesh Sharma.

04:34:05.120 --> 04:34:07.120
[Guest 2]: Great film, Gulzar's script.

04:34:07.120 --> 04:34:09.120
[Guest 2]: I like the film, that was a good film.

04:34:09.120 --> 04:34:14.120
[Guest 2]: 90s again, I think one of the, of course, Satya and other things changed stuff.

04:34:14.120 --> 04:34:20.120
[Guest 2]: But the Drohokal of Nilani, I had enjoyed at that time.

04:34:20.120 --> 04:34:25.120
[Guest 2]: There were some classic masala stuff of 90s also, which is not bad.

04:34:25.120 --> 04:34:29.120
[Guest 2]: Gupt, for instance, again coming back to Rajiv Rai and Mohra, both.

04:34:29.120 --> 04:34:31.120
[Guest 2]: Wow, total.

