[Guest 2]: But anyway, I mean, I'll not bore with 2000s and 2010s, but that's a whole list of stuff that people can watch.

04:35:09.120 --> 04:35:11.120
[Guest 1]: I think a lot of it is not very obscure.

04:35:11.120 --> 04:35:14.120
[Guest 1]: Amit, your 15 favorite Hindi masala films of the 2000s.

04:35:14.120 --> 04:35:20.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so Fanda kya hai ki when I sent you guys this email saying ki paanch paanch film aap name karo, underappreciated.

04:35:20.120 --> 04:35:24.120
[Amit Varma]: Then I thought that shit, why did I volunteer myself for this?

04:35:24.120 --> 04:35:26.120
[Amit Varma]: And I didn't really feel like choosing five.

04:35:26.120 --> 04:35:31.120
[Amit Varma]: And also I keep talking about films, so I don't want to go through the same ones ki Decalogue achha hai, yeh achha hai, woh achha hai.

04:35:31.120 --> 04:35:33.120
[Amit Varma]: I've spoken so much about films.

04:35:33.120 --> 04:35:38.120
[Amit Varma]: So I decided to narrow the focus down so sharply that it becomes easy to choose.

04:35:38.120 --> 04:35:42.120
[Amit Varma]: So I narrowed the focus to films that I watched at Mummy over the last three, four years.

04:35:42.120 --> 04:35:44.120
[Amit Varma]: World Cinema that I discovered there.

04:35:44.120 --> 04:35:46.120
[Amit Varma]: So very quickly, these are the films I'd recommend.

04:35:46.120 --> 04:35:50.120
[Amit Varma]: There's a very fine film called Wild, directed by Nicolette Krebitz.

04:35:50.120 --> 04:35:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Have you seen it?

04:35:51.120 --> 04:35:59.120
[Amit Varma]: So it's a lovely film about this woman who's, it's a German film, who's in the city and she's got a bad job and her boss is an asshole.

04:35:59.120 --> 04:36:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And she's kind of fed up.

04:36:01.120 --> 04:36:05.120
[Amit Varma]: And once in a while, she'll go out into the woods, into the forest and all of that.

04:36:05.120 --> 04:36:08.120
[Amit Varma]: And through a mysterious turn of events, she kidnaps a wolf.

04:36:08.120 --> 04:36:11.120
[Amit Varma]: And she gets a wolf back in her apartment with her.

04:36:11.120 --> 04:36:18.120
[Amit Varma]: And I think the wolf, if I remember correctly, is kind of serrated when she manages to bring it back, but obviously snaps out of that state.

04:36:18.120 --> 04:36:19.120
[Amit Varma]: And now there's a lot of work.

04:36:19.120 --> 04:36:22.120
[Amit Varma]: She's got to feed the wolf. She's got to build a relationship with the wolf.

04:36:22.120 --> 04:36:24.120
[Amit Varma]: She's got to make sure the wolf doesn't kill her.

04:36:24.120 --> 04:36:26.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting how it develops.

04:36:26.120 --> 04:36:29.120
[Amit Varma]: It's a very interior psychological kind of film.

04:36:29.120 --> 04:36:33.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is a real wolf, it's not a wolf played by Andy Serkis.

04:36:33.120 --> 04:36:35.120
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's a real wolf.

04:36:35.120 --> 04:36:36.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's a lovely film.

04:36:36.120 --> 04:36:38.120
[Amit Varma]: Sexual overtones and all that.

04:36:38.120 --> 04:36:42.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's a very, it's a very, you know, a different kind of film.

04:36:42.120 --> 04:36:47.120
[Amit Varma]: Just to have the courage to conceive of it and then make it so well, kind of really impressed me.

04:36:47.120 --> 04:36:54.120
[Amit Varma]: Another film is actually a mainstream Hollywood film that didn't get any Oscar nominations, didn't make waves, which is very sad.

04:36:54.120 --> 04:36:55.120
[Amit Varma]: It's called Waves.

04:36:55.120 --> 04:36:57.120
[Amit Varma]: It's by a director called Trey Edward Schultz.

04:36:57.120 --> 04:37:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And I thought it's an absolute masterpiece when I saw it.

04:37:01.120 --> 04:37:10.120
[Amit Varma]: And it did get some rave reviews from some people I respect, but made absolutely no mark, either in the box office or at the Oscars or whatever.

04:37:10.120 --> 04:37:14.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's a lovely film, which has two sort of rhythms to it.

04:37:14.120 --> 04:37:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Like if you enjoy listening to, if you enjoy the part that music can play in a film really well, you know, you kind of get it here.

04:37:22.120 --> 04:37:29.120
[Amit Varma]: Where the first half of the film about this young man who's, you know, pumped up and on adrenaline and all of that.

04:37:29.120 --> 04:37:33.120
[Amit Varma]: The first half of the film, it's like the music is just driving it forward.

04:37:33.120 --> 04:37:35.120
[Amit Varma]: There is this relentless propulsion that is happening.

04:37:35.120 --> 04:37:37.120
[Amit Varma]: Till giving nothing away, the guy dies.

04:37:37.120 --> 04:37:41.120
[Amit Varma]: And then the rest of the film follows his sister and how she copes with it.

04:37:41.120 --> 04:37:45.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's very quiet, slow, lot of tear off.

04:37:45.120 --> 04:37:47.120
[Amit Varma]: It's a sudden change in rhythm.

04:37:47.120 --> 04:37:49.120
[Amit Varma]: And yet it's so beautiful.

04:37:49.120 --> 04:37:51.120
[Amit Varma]: And these halves fit together so well.

04:37:51.120 --> 04:37:55.120
[Amit Varma]: So I thought it was a masterpiece, but just went unnoticed by almost everyone.

04:37:55.120 --> 04:38:03.120
[Amit Varma]: The third film, perhaps controversial, is Gaspar Noe's film Climax, which is about a bunch of people at a party.

04:38:03.120 --> 04:38:07.120
[Amit Varma]: And somebody mixes psychedelic stuff in their drinks, I think LSD.

04:38:07.120 --> 04:38:10.120
[Amit Varma]: And it just, it just goes nuts.

04:38:10.120 --> 04:38:17.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's a film that doesn't have a logical plot from a point of view of things happening beyond what I just told you.

04:38:17.120 --> 04:38:19.120
[Amit Varma]: It's kind of hard to describe.

04:38:19.120 --> 04:38:23.120
[Amit Varma]: But they kind of, like, they kind of go mad.

04:38:23.120 --> 04:38:25.120
[Amit Varma]: Everything goes crazy.

04:38:25.120 --> 04:38:27.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's just so visceral.

04:38:27.120 --> 04:38:31.120
[Amit Varma]: It's like you're sitting in a movie hall and everything about it, you know.

04:38:31.120 --> 04:38:35.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's a very choreographed film in the sense there's a lot of movement.

04:38:35.120 --> 04:38:39.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, the way everything comes together.

04:38:39.120 --> 04:38:41.120
[Guest 1]: I thought that was very visceral.

04:38:41.120 --> 04:38:45.120
[Guest 1]: Gaspar Noe's film about people not being intoxicated would be quite visceral anyway.

04:38:45.120 --> 04:38:47.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

04:38:47.120 --> 04:38:55.120
[Amit Varma]: And the film is oddly described as a psychological horror, but I don't even know if it's that.

04:38:55.120 --> 04:38:57.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if any category really fits.

04:38:57.120 --> 04:39:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And another film described as psychological horror, which I think is again a phosphate, is Darren Aronofsky's Mother.

04:39:03.120 --> 04:39:06.120
[Amit Varma]: Which again, similar visceral experience.

04:39:06.120 --> 04:39:08.120
[Amit Varma]: The plot makes absolutely no sense.

04:39:08.120 --> 04:39:13.120
[Amit Varma]: And half the people I was with in the hall when we saw it were just like, what the fuck is this?

04:39:13.120 --> 04:39:15.120
[Unknown]: Makes no sense.

04:39:15.120 --> 04:39:19.120
[Amit Varma]: And the other half is just reeling like I was at the sheer force of the film.

04:39:19.120 --> 04:39:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And again, it's one of those things where you just have to kind of sit back and experience it and leave your brain out of it.

04:39:25.120 --> 04:39:30.120
[Amit Varma]: So if you misplace your brain, Jai, as you were saying you'll never do, you should probably watch this.

04:39:30.120 --> 04:39:36.120
[Amit Varma]: And finally, a film I mentioned earlier in this episode, One Cut of the Dead by Shinichiro Ueda.

04:39:36.120 --> 04:39:39.120
[Amit Varma]: Japanese horror film and it's like a film within a film.

04:39:39.120 --> 04:39:44.120
[Amit Varma]: It's about a bunch of guys trying to make a single cut film and it's a horror film and what happens to them.

04:39:44.120 --> 04:39:50.120
[Amit Varma]: And it is no other film that I have ever seen has communicated the joy of cinema better than this.

04:39:50.120 --> 04:39:55.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, at the surface level, it's a bunch of guys trying to make a film and taking joy in that.

04:39:55.120 --> 04:39:59.120
[Amit Varma]: But the joy I got from sitting in the audience was kind of incredible.

04:39:59.120 --> 04:40:04.120
[Amit Varma]: So I narrowed my gaze down to films I've seen at MAMI in the last five years.

04:40:04.120 --> 04:40:11.120
[Amit Varma]: And these five would be, you know, among the ones that really hit me hard and moved me.

04:40:11.120 --> 04:40:12.120
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, that's my list.

